<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mejia Wins Dominican Election  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Left-leaning populist
Hipolito Mejia was declared the winner of the Dominican
presidential race Thursday after his opponents withdrew from a
run-off election.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you for this clean and complete victory,'' Mejia,
surrounded by his children and grandchildren, told cheering
supporters at a Santo Domingo hotel. He promised a ''government of
national unity, a shared government that will rise above the
confrontation and partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Mejia was pronounced the winner by Manuel Morel, president of
the Central Electoral Board, after Danilo Medina of the incumbent
Dominican Liberation Party and ex-President Joaquin Balaguer said
they were leaving the race because a costly second round would
cause instability and hurt the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the good of the country, we waive our right to participate
in a second round,'' Medina said as frustrated party members
objected angrily.
</P>
<P>
   President Leonel Fernandez later congratulated Mejia and
applauded Medina for his ''greatness and generosity'' in not
forcing a second round.
</P>
<P>
   Reynaldo Pared, the Liberation Party delegate on the Central
Electoral Board, said Medina made the decision after failing to
strike an alliance with Balaguer. Balaguer, the third-place
candidate, told Medina he was unable to guarantee that his Social
Christian Reformist Party could deliver enough votes to give Medina
a second-round win, Pared said.
</P>
<P>
   With returns from only 18 of 11,422 polling stations in
Tuesday's election still not fully counted, officials said Mejia,
of the center-left Dominican Revolutionary Party, had 49.86 percent
of the vote, a hair shy of the 50 percent-plus margin needed to
avoid a June 30 runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Free-market advocate Medina had 24.95 percent. Despite his
blindness and frailty, the 93-year-old Balaguer, a conservative,
won 24.61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dominican law, the Central Electoral Board can declare a
winner if one of the two candidates withdraws from the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to be a government for everyone, a government
that won't destroy the country and one that listens to civil
society,'' Mejia's vice presidential running mate, Milagros Ortiz
Bosch, said. The new administration will be inaugurated Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Medina's party reacted with anger. A furious
Miguel Solano, a former assistant chief of staff for President
Leonel Fernandez, called party leaders ''traitors'' and claimed
that the administration had ''negotiated an impunity pact so
nothing happens'' to members of the Medina government involved in
alleged corruption after Mejia takes power.
</P>
<P>
   But many voters reacted with relief to the news that there would
be no runoff, saying they were weary of nearly two years of
sometimes violent campaigning and an election that claimed three
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have voted for (Medina), but what I'd like now is that
they leave it the way it is,'' said Santo Alguilino Abreu, a
39-year-old taxi driver. ''We don't need a second round. It costs
too much and there are too many problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Mejia, who had declared a victory with only 5 percent of the
votes counted on Tuesday night, was more cautious on Thursday,
thanking the other candidates, but waiting on the elections board
for a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign elections observers said they were satisfied with the
developments and affirmed that Tuesday's vote was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they had to have a second round, it would have been OK, but
this will be better for the Dominican people,'' said Richard
Soudriette, president of the International Foundation for Elections
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Carter Center and the Washington-based
National Democratic Institute for International Affairs also called
the elections fair during a joint news conference Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia, 59, criticized Fernandez's administration for failing to
relieve endemic poverty and has promised to spend more on social
programs and community-level public works projects. He offers no
overreaching changes in economic policy, although businessmen fear
he'll take money from much-needed infrastructure investments to
make good on his campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
   A former director of the Dominican Tobacco Institute, Mejia runs
an agrochemical business and was agriculture secretary from 1978-82
under President Antonio Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   Married with four children, Mejia has been his party's vice
president for years but never held elected office. In 1990, he was
the vice presidential running mate of the legendary Jose Francisco
Pena Gomez -- who made three unsuccessful runs for the presidency.
Pena Gomez died in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
