<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pier collapses sending dozens into Delaware River  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN POET
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A pier holding a new open-air bar collapsed
and plunged into the Delaware River Thursday night, killing at
least three people and injuring more than three dozen including
several rescue workers, hospital and city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It went down so quick people were just running,'' said Julie
Morgan of Haddonfield, N.J., who was pulled out of the water and
was sitting with police blankets draped over her on the back of a
police car.
</P>
<P>
   Three people died and 37 people, including eight rescue workers,
were taken to area hospitals, said Stephanie Franklin-Suber, the
mayor's chief of staff. The identities were not immediately
released.
</P>
<P>
   Divers continued to search the water and pier wreckage through
the night, though Police Commissioner John Timoney said there was
no reason to believe there were more people in the water.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 people were on the pier when it dropped into the
water about 8:25 p.m. A canvas tent over the pier also collapsed,
covering many people who fell into the water.
</P>
<P>
   One person was pronounced dead and 11 people were being treated
for minor injuries at Methodist Hospital, said hospital spokesman
Jeff Baxt. One person was pronounced dead at Thomas Jefferson
Hospital, where three others were being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   A third person was pronounced dead by the medical examiner,
according to Fire Commissioner Harold Hairston.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people, including six rescue workers, were taken to
Hahnemann University Hospital, emergency room Dr. Bartholomew
Tortella said. One person was critical, two were in stable and the
six rescue workers suffered cuts and bruises. The other two
people's conditions are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Four people with non-serious injuries were taken to Pennsylvania
Hospital, a hospital spokeswoman said. St. Agnes had two victims
and the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania had four. Two
other firefighters suffered minor injuries, though it was not known
where they were being treated.
</P>
<P>
   The pier held the new bar, Heat, which is attached to a ballroom
dancing area at the Moshulu restaurant, a boat docked on the river.
Heat opened earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The pier is about one-quarter the size of a football field,
behind the restaurant. The section that collapsed was along the
back wall of the ballroom facing the deck, Franklin-Suber said.
</P>
<P>
   A hostess at the restaurant, Eve McCarney, said workers had been
replacing some floorboards but did not do any major structural
work. She arrived for work Thursday night after the accident and
was standing with police and fire crews.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard a loud crash, and then all hell broke loose. I went
straight down ... then I was just trying to fight my way up,'' said
bartender Joseph Capaci, 28, of Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   Fire and police officials were investigating, as were officials
from the Department of Licenses and Inspections. Mayor John F.
Street was also at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a pier collapsed on the New Jersey side of the
Delaware River, submerging at least five vehicles and causing about
$10 million in damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
