<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani Expresses Regets  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani expressed regret Thursday
for the way he handled a recent police shooting of an unarmed black
man, speaking at a public forum at which he gave no hint whether
he'll continue his run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The town hall meeting came three weeks after Giuliani revealed
that he has prostate cancer and said he didn't know if he would
continue to seek the Senate seat against first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong forum, Giuliani told MSNBC moderator Andrea
Mitchell he has some regrets, including how he handled the police
shooting of Patrick Dorismond, who was killed in a scuffle with
undercover police.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was widely criticized for releasing Dorismond's police
record-- including sealed details of a juvenile arrest. Giuliani
said he did right in releasing the records, but also said he should
have been more understanding about the loss of a person's life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a mistake,'' he said. ''I should have also conveyed
human feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Mitchell whether he has become more compassionate
because of his illness, Giuliani said ''something has to happen to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor insisted Thursday -- both before and during the town
hall meeting 900 people attended -- that he has not yet chosen a
cancer treatment. He has said that step will precede any
announcement of whether he will keep up the Senate run.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had thought the decision would be easier.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it would be like a budget or a (court) case, but it
is a much more personal decision,'' said the former prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how people should take recent revelations about the
mayor's private life -- including his acknowledgment of a close
relationship with another woman and plans to separate from his wife
-- the mayor said: ''I guess I would just like people to take a look
at me and say I'm a human being. I'm not a religious leader, I'm a
governmental leader.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he ''has not always put his family first,'' but declined
to answer questions about Judith Nathan, whom he has called a
''very good friend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
