<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Francois cannot plead and avoid death penalty  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The death penalty trial of Kendall Francois
for strangling eight women in the Poughkeepsie area will proceed
following a ruling by the state's highest court, Dutchess County
District Attorney William Grady said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Court of Appeals decided 7-0 Thursday that Francois
was barred from pleading guilty in the case in December 1998
because Grady had not yet decided whether he was going to seek the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Grady said a hearing is scheduled for June 14 before Dutchess
County Court Judge Thomas Dolan. At that time, the timing of
Francois' trial will become clearer, Grady said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 1995 capital punishment statute gives prosecutors
120 days after a suspect's arraignment to decide whether to seek
the death penalty. One day after Francois tried to enter his guilty
plea, Grady filed notice that he would seek Francois' execution.
</P>
<P>
   Francois' lawyers were trying to take advantage of a Court of
Appeals' ruling in December 1998 in another death penalty case
which they interpreted as opening the door to such pleas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals said Thursday it is the prosecutors'
call during the 120-day period and that a defendant ''does not have
an unqualified right to plead guilty to the entire indictment'' in
the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   To decide otherwise, Judge Howard Levine wrote, would lead to an
''unseemly race to the courthouse between defense and prosecution
to see whether a guilty plea or notice of intent to seek the death
penalty will be filed first.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be contrary to the ''thorough, fully deliberative
decision-making'' that prosecutors should engage in when weighing
whether to seek the death penalty, Levine wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan refused to accept Francois plea in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Francois is accused of strangling eight women and stashing their
bodies in the Poughkeepsie home he shared with his family in an
alleged 22-month killing spree. He was arrested in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Grady said the court wrote a broadly worded decision to guide
future instances where defendants might use a plea to avoid the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''This decision in essence closes the door with regard to any
future attempts by defendants to enter pleas in advance of either
the 120-day period running or the district attorney filing his
death notice,'' Grady said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Harris, Francois' lead attorney from the state Capital
Defender Office, said he was disappointed in the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that some issues still remain and we'll just
continue on with the fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible Francois can appeal in federal court on claims
that his U.S. constitutional rights were violated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0011 </DOCNO>
