<HEADLINE> Johnson, Davis Break Meet Records  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Lawrence Johnson, using the Gatorade
Classic as a tuneup for the U.S. Olympic trials, broke his own meet
record in the pole vault Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The former American record-holder and 1996 Olympian had a vault
of 18 feet, 10\ inches, which bettered his old mark of 18-6}, set
in 1994. Tim Mack, competing unattached, took second at 18-4{.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very windy,'' Johnson said. ''We were working on
stabilizing the technical aspects. As far as that is concerned, it
was a solid performance. The wind made it hard, but I'm pretty
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he's confident as he prepares for the Olympic
Trials on July 17 in Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to Atlanta for the Georgia Tech Invitational and
then I will train hard for three weeks,'' he said. ''I'm shooting
for 19-10. It's just a matter of coming out and having nice
conditions. Technically, everything is in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquis Davis of Memphis Elite Track Club broke the meet record
in the 200 meters with a time of 20.27 seconds. The previous record
of 20.30 was held by Harvey McSwain of North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   In women's competition, Tracy Carrington, competing unattached,
broke her own meet record in the pole vault at 13-0\. She set the
old record of 12-6} last year.
</P>
<P>
   The meet was billed as a last-chance NCAA qualifier and several
athletes took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Matt Rush earned an automatic qualifying mark in the
110 hurdles with a time of 13.58. Dwayne Wallace won the event in
13.37. Tennessee's Pat Buckheit earned a provisional mark in the
decathlon with a score of 7,354 points.
</P>
<P>
   Three runners earned provisional spots in the 3,000
steeplechase. Notre Dame's Luke Watson won in 8:46.77, Eastern
Kentucky's James Mutusi was second in 8:47.57 and Virginia
Commonwealth's Alberto Vicente was third in 8:47.60.
</P>
<P>
   Women's provisional qualifiers included Lutricia Purham of
Southeast Missouri State and Andrea Pappas of Tennessee in the shot
put. Purham had a mark of 50-6} and Pappas followed at 49-5.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Barber and Rodena Barr of South Carolina posted
provisional times in the 100. Barber won in 11.46 and Barr was
second in 11.50.
</P>
