<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly Democrats say legislative process on hold  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albany, N.Y. (AP) -- It is still unclear who would come out on
top of a power struggle between the state Assembly's speaker and
former majority leader, but one thing is already certain.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber's Democrats say the battle between Speaker Sheldon
Silver and Assemblyman Michael Bragman would effectively halt the
legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Robin Schimminger, who supports Silver, said
Bragman's move to oust the speaker would ''result in one piece of
the government being chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This ensures gridlock in the state government,'' the Erie
County Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman John McEneny of Albany, also a Silver backer, said
there is a ''ton of legislation,'' ranging from smaller,
district-specific items to the larger bills with statewide impacts,
that needs to be considered before the current session ends. He
called Bragman's move ''divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The big-ticket items ... those things really require party
leadership so you can hammer out and move it forward. It becomes
more difficult when you have no unity,'' McEneny said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the togetherness that Democrats displayed Tuesday in
nominating Hillary Rodham Clinton for U.S. Senate was ''very rare''
among Assembly members who came from different geographic, ethnic
and philosophical backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We OD'd on unity,'' he said of Bragman going public the day
after the convention with his bid to overthrow Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Steven Sanders of Manhattan said the action ''throws
an enormous monkey wrench into the whole process.'' Sanders is a
Silver partisan.
</P>
<P>
   A shift in power from Silver to Bragman would also mean that for
the first time in more than 80 years, a Democratic speaker would
come from outside New York City. Silver is from Manhattan while
Bragman represents a district near Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said Bragman is an ''upstate conservative'' who has ''an
antagonistic view'' toward issues that downstate constituents
support, like rent regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Another downstate Silver supporter, Thomas DiNapoli of Nassau
County, said the ''geographic back-and-forth'' argument is ''moot
because Shelly will be the speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The real tragedy is that the people's business has to take a
back seat to this internal battle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God the budget's over with,'' said Assemblyman William
Magee, who supports Bragman. ''I don't expect any bills to be
passed the next week. This is an issue that needs to be addressed
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Magee, who represents Oneida, said he will not regret his
decision even if Silver retaliates by removing him as chairman of
the Assembly agriculture committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that's the case, that's the case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders have picked the week of June 12 as the last
of the 2000 regular session, though Silver has never regarded such
dates as hard-and-fast deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's leadership struggle with Bragman, plus Tuesday's
Democratic convention in Albany, effectively caused work this week
in the Assembly to grind to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he plans to formally move against Silver on Monday,
but that could merely trigger a longer battle before Assembly
Democrats decide whom their speaker will be.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Bragman supporters -- Martin Luster of Ithaca and
Ronald Tocci of Westchester County -- were stripped of their
committee chairmanships Thursday by Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Luster said losing the chairmanship and taking sides doesn't
change the dynamics within the party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have friends on both sides, and we have made a point that we
remain friends. There is no acrimony,'' Luster said. ''There will
be changes no matter what the outcome is. Changes take time to
settle in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 0107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court says Pataki did not violate law with ice storm gifts  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki's thank you gifts to
volunteer relief workers during the North Country ice storm of 1998
did not violate state laws or the constitution, a court has found.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division of state Supreme Court decided 5-0
Thursday that a challenge to the giveaways filed by government
spending critic Robert Schulz was unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, from Queensbury north of Albany, contended that Pataki
was illegally rewarding those who removed downed trees, delivered
food and water and otherwise helped residents when a wide swath of
northern New York was paralyzed by the January 1998 storm.
</P>
<P>
   The state organized parties to thank emergency workers in
Watertown and Plattsburgh, and also sent them two complimentary
lift tickets to the state's Whiteface Mountain ski center in the
Adirondacks and two passes to the State Fair in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   About 40,000 tickets were distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz argued that the tickets represented impermissible gifts
at public expense to the recipients. He also contended that the
mailings were thinly veiled promotional materials for Pataki --
again at public expense -- who was facing re-election that year.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court found neither argument persuasive. The judges
said no state taxpayer money was expended by the free tickets at
Whiteface Mountain or the State Fair. While a ''small portion'' of
the cost of mailing out the tickets was picked up by Pataki's
office, the judges said ''that his was a reasonable expenditure
consistent with the goal of disaster preparedness.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges also said the materials under Pataki's name were not
designed to advance his political fortunes, but the governor's
''intention to thank members of the public who came forward and
rendered assistance during an emergency situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We find no interference with the right to a free election,''
the court said in a ruling written by Justice Anthony Cardona.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said it should have been obvious
that the giveaways were appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was done as a gesture to all the volunteers to help their
neighbors,'' McKeon said. ''It shouldn't take a court to make it
clear that was an appropriate thing to do. Unfortunately, that was
what it came down to.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said he had no comment after reading Thursday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling upholds a decision by a state Supreme Court
justice in Albany in February 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 0107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Place Three Pitchers on DL  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Just when the Cleveland Indians thought they
were finally healthy -- they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitchers Jaret Wright and Charles Nagy, and reliever
Ricardo Rincon were all placed on the 15-day disabled list
Thursday, just hours before the Indians got back manager Charlie
Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy will undergo surgery Friday to remove bone chips in his
right elbow and will be out 6-8 weeks. Rincon has bone spurs in his
left elbow and surgery could keep him out until July or August,
''at least'' said Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   Wright has a muscle strain in his right shoulder, and won't be
eligible to come off the DL until next week. He is scheduled to
start May 27 at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the welcome back Manuel was hoping for. And it was
another bad break for the Indians, who had just started playing
well after briefly dropping into second place in the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   ''First I heard one pitcher, and then two pitchers and it ended
up being three,'' said Manuel, who was coming back from colon
surgery. ''I said, 'You've got to be kidding me. But that's the way
it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday actually ended on a positive note for Cleveland.
The Indians and Detroit Tigers were rained out, allowing Manuel to
rest his pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   For the woeful Tigers, it was just more bad luck. It was the
second time this season they led a game that was eventually
postponed by rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not a doggone thing you can do about it,'' Tigers
manager Phil Garner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians raided their Triple-A Buffalo farm team for pitching
help, recalling Scott Sanders, Jim Brower and Mark Watson.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI performed on Wright late Wednesday night revealed a
strained right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a problem. Think about it -- 40 percent of your rotation
gone in 30 minutes,'' Indians owner Larry Dolan said Thursday.
''But how long will they be gone? This is a team of resilience. I
think the depth is there to handle these missteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolan's comments came before he learned of the loss of Rincon,
Cleveland's most consistent reliever this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll guess we'll find out how good we are,'' catcher Sandy
Alomar said.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy's surgery will end a remarkable run of consistency for the
33-year-old, who hasn't missed a start since 1993. But when Nagy
started the season 2-4 with a 7.19 ERA, Manuel knew something was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were times when Charlie's velocity would be between 87
and 90 mph, and other times when it was between 82 and 85,'' Manuel
said. ''I wondered why there was such a big gap at times. But I
didn't really know until Charlie started slinging the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagy has won at least 15 games in each of the past five seasons,
and has pitched his turn in the starting rotation since starting
the season finale on Oct. 3, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who had been released by the Indians this spring before
signing a minor league contract with the club, was signed to a
contract for the remainder of this season and started Thursday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up back-to-back homers in the first inning, but ended up
getting a no-decision thanks to the rainout.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have contributed to Cleveland's early-season struggles
this year. The Indians have already had All-Stars Bartolo Colon,
Alomar and Kenny Lofton on the DL, and they lost center fielder
Jacob Cruz to a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something we're going to have to play our way
through,'' said Manuel, who said he feels fine and looked better
following his second surgery since February. ''
</P>
<P>
   Wright has pitched well this year, bouncing back from a dreadful
1999 season. He allowed just four hits in 7 2-3 innings of his last
start on May 11 against Kansas City, but left with tightness in his
right shoulder after throwing 100 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he went a little bit too far,'' Alomar said. ''One
pitch can cost you your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 3-2 with a 3.15 ERA in seven starts, was on the DL twice
last year with a strained muscle in his right shoulder. The Indians
insist the current problem is not related to last year's injury.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nagy, Rincon hid his elbow troubles from the Indians. But
despite having soreness in his arm for the past month, Rincon went
2-0 with a 0.96 ERA in 16 games and didn't allow an inherited
runner to score.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pitched with my heart, not my arm,'' said Rincon, who was
going to keep his injury a secret until his arm started feeling
worse in a relief appearance Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who pitched for the Chicago Cubs last season, had a
rough spring camp and was cut by the Indians before they grabbed
him for insurance. At Buffalo, he was 3-1 with a 3.61 ERA in seven
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Brower went 5-2 with a 3.94 ERA in eight starts at Buffalo. He
pitched in nine games for the Indians last year as a late-season
callup. He'll be used in long relief this time but could make a
start.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I'll wait my turn,'' he said looking around the
Indians clubhouse. ''I guess a lot of guys are waiting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
