<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National media blitz unveiled as part of Buffalo economic development plan </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Hoping to shake their city's snowy,
past-its-prime reputation, Buffalo business leaders will launch a
national media campaign as part of a well-financed plan to attract
50,000 new jobs and $1 billion in private investment over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in August, image-building ads on CNN, CNBC, the Wall
Street Journal and sponsorships on National Public Radio will
spotlight a work force that includes 125,000 underemployed workers
and 100,000 college students.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign unveilled Thursday even tries to calm Buffalo
weather fears by pointing out that the city enjoys more sun than
Atlanta, Ga., and less rain than Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are one element of a five-pronged economic development
plan crafted by the Buffalo Niagara Enterprise, a business-led
coalition formed last year with the goal of encouraging businesses
to invest in the eight westernmost counties of New York and
southern Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition members, which include local municipalities and
private businesses like HSBC Bank, the Buffalo Bills and Moog Inc.,
have committed $27 million over the next five years, making the
effort the largest non-state-funded initiative of its kind in North
America, according to Ted Levine, chairman of the consulting group
steering the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's appreciation of well-paying jobs and abundance of
college students should be attractive to employers frustrated by
high turnover and a lack of qualified applicants, said Levine,
whose Development Counsellors International specializes in
recruiting businesses for client regions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Buffalo has a lot to offer and if we say it and promote it
with a single voice, we'll succeed,'' Mayor Anthony Masiello said.
</P>
<P>
   Initial marketing efforts will focus on three growth-oriented
sectors: information technology, medical manufacturing and call
centers/back office operations.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's tag line will be: ''I am Buffalo Niagara.
Available. Productive. People.''
</P>
<P>
   A simultaneous internal marketing effort will be aimed at
building self-esteem among local business owners and employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those of us who live and work in this region are the
stakeholders,'' said BNE president Thomas Kucharski. ''We want to
put some tangible, substantive information in front of the local
community so we can dispel many of the misconceptions about our
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Niagara Enterprise was launched last year by local
business executives following the lead of counterparts elsewhere
who have found success with similar efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We realize that an advertising campaign won't create 50,000
new jobs,'' said Doug Bean, managing partner of Eric Mower and
Associates, the advertising agency that developed the campaign.
''It's all part of a much more comprehensive game plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 0108 </TRAILER>
