<HEADLINE> S.Korea Seeks Joint Team With North  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's proposal to form a joint
soccer team with North Korea for international competition will
depend on the success of an upcoming inter-Korea summit.
</P>
<P>
   Chung Mong-joon, head of South Korea's Football Association,
said he would like to visit North Korea to discuss the issue. The
Asian Football Confederation overwhelmingly approved Chung's
proposal that the two Koreas field a unified team at this year's
Asia Cup competition, scheduled for n Lebanon in October.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea has earned a berth in that tournament, while North
Korea was eliminated in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   If the two Koreas can field a single team for the Asian Cup,
that would help them form another unified team for the 2002 World
Cup, which will be co-hosted by Japan and South Korea, Chung said.
FIFA, soccer's governing body, has taken a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea is willing to share with North Korea some of the 32
World Cup games it is scheduled to stage in 2002. The other 32
games will be in Japan, including the final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
