<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox Relies on Big Names For Comeback  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Even though he hasn't shot a roll of film for
his new Fox series, ''Boston Public,'' Emmy-winning producer David
E. Kelley asked advertisers to take it on faith that it will be
good.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the best thing I have ever done,'' Kelley said Thursday.
''You can believe that, looking at me -- the man who gave you
'Snoops.'''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisers -- and maybe a few Fox executives -- laughed
nervously at the reference to his failed ABC series from last year.
Fox, in introducing its fall schedule, is banking on big-name
creators to fuel a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kelley, creator of ''Ally McBeal'' and ''The Practice,''
Fox has signed ''Titanic'' producer James Cameron, ''The X-Files''
creator Chris Carter, ''ER'' creator Michael Crichton and ''The
Blair Witch Project'' producer Gregg Hale to make some of its nine
new series this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which slumped badly in the ratings this year, announced the
biggest makeover of any broadcast network this week. It is facing
uncertainty with the retirement of its long-running shows,
''Beverly Hills 90210'' and ''Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   One note of stability was a last-minute deal for ''The X-Files''
to return for an eighth season, although actor David Duchovny's
agent Mulder will be a part-timer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UPN announced that it was adding three new series and
picking up ''The Hughleys'' after it was canceled by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox reached separate deals with Carter and Duchovny to continue.
Co-star Gillian Anderson was already contracted for another year.
Duchovny's deal, completed Wednesday, calls for him to film 11
episodes, or half the 22 new episodes that most series film each
year.
</P>
<P>
   That enabled Fox to keep intact its Sunday schedule, its most
successful night of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will also carry ''The Lone Gunmen,'' a spinoff of ''The
X-Files'' created by Carter, on Thursdays next season. It will be
paired with a Crichton-created drama that does not have a title or
cast yet. Appearing before advertisers on Thursday, Crichton
wouldn't offer a hint of what the series is about.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is giving Carter and Crichton extra time, and won't debut
the Thursday schedule until the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Mondays are being turned over entirely to Kelley. ''Boston
Public,'' follows a group of teachers working at a high school in
suburban Boston. It will be followed by ''Ally McBeal,'' his
returning series about a group of lawyers working at a firm in
downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron is producing ''Dark Angel,'' a science-fiction adventure
series set in ''post-apocalyptic America.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox returns two comedies whose midseason successes were among
the network's only bright spots this year, ''Malcolm in the
Middle'' and ''Titus.'' One new comedy is ''Don't Ask,'' which
stars John Goodman as a gay dad.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from Fox's schedule is the game show ''Greed,'' which was
quickly put together to capitalize on the success of ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire.'' Fox has also canceled ''Time of Your Life,''
''Get Real'' and ''Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN recovered from a near-death experience this year to surge
past its archrival, the WB, in the ratings. It was almost entirely
because of its new Thursday night World Wrestling Federation
franchise, which will return.
</P>
<P>
   The network adds two new series on Friday nights: ''Freedom,''
an action series made by ''Matrix'' producer Joel Silver, and
''Level 9,'' a drama about an FBI unit trained to hunt down
high-tech criminals. Both series are trying to grab the young male
audience that is UPN's target.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are proud to be known as the guy network,'' said UPN chief
executive Dean Valentine. ''Somebody needs to stand up for the
high-testosterone American male.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in February, UPN said it will broadcast games of the
new XFL football league created by the World Wrestling Federation.
NBC is broadcasting XFL games on Saturday nights. UPN also plans to
produce a weekly rap music countdown series with the hip-hop
magazine The Source.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is canceling ''Dilbert,'' ''The Beat,'' ''Malcolm &AMP; Eddie,''
''The Grown-Ups'' and ''I Dare You.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0112 </TRAILER>
