<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsonist Feared in Fla. Neighborhood  </HEADLINE>
By VICKIE CHACHERE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- During the last decade, tens of millions of
dollars have gone into restoring Tampa Heights, a once grand
neighborhood and home to city founders that had fallen into decay.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of celebrating its rebirth, city officials and
residents are trying to ensure the neighborhood doesn't go up in
flames.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, 36 fires have been set in Tampa Heights and
neighboring sections of Ybor City, near downtown. The targets have
been abandoned and occupied homes, a church and an upscale
apartment complex under construction that's intended to be one of
the area's anchor developments.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been injured, but some of the fires have been set at
night in homes where people were sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been sleeping two or three hours a night,'' said Dave
Davis, who has spent the last five years renovating a 1912 home.
''Every time the dog barks I'm looking out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has formed a task force with state and federal arson
investigators. Without even a description of a suspect they have
little to go on.
</P>
<P>
   The arsons have been a blow to city leaders who've pushed to
rebuild neighborhoods where an eclectic mix of homes and brick
streets built from the 1890s to 1920s turned in recent years into
the turf of drug dealers and prostitutes. Young professionals have
been lured to restore the historic homes with the help of
government tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Only one person has been arrested, for the most recent fire in a
vacant home Tuesday. But task force investigators do not believe
the man, Carl Lester Simms, is responsible for the other fires.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Serrales, a real estate agent, said the area still holds
promise of becoming a desirable neighborhood despite the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of negative that there's an arsonist in the area,
it's a little frightening and scary,'' he said. ''But it's also
helped Tampa Heights, it's put it on the map. People see it on
television and see the beautiful houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Noriega, the mayor's top aide on redevelopment issues,
said the fires aren't scaring away those willing to invest in
redevelopment -- yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been an uphill battle,'' he said. ''There are a lot of
urban pioneers who have made a lifetime investment there. There are
appraisers going out there, lenders taking a look. Although they
say they don't worry, I'm sure they do.''
</P>
<P>
   When the fires first began, the neighborhoods buzzed with
theories on who is responsible. Some blamed owners of ramshackle
houses or the city, thinking they did it to save the cost of
tearing down houses. Others speculated it was residents who felt
shoved aside by monied newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Noriega dismisses such theories, saying it costs no more to haul
away a dilapidated house as it does to haul away the burned
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a person who is really sick,'' Noriega said of the
arsonist. ''I hope the neighborhood doesn't get him before the
authorities do. There isn't going to be much left of him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leader of Supremacy Church Arrested  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Mo. (AP) -- The leader of a white-supremacist
religious sect has been charged with abducting six of his
grandchildren from North Dakota several years ago and hiding them
at his Missouri farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Since the pastor was arrested Wednesday, the children, ages 9
through 16, have refused to leave the farmhouse, engaging in a
standoff with authorities on the property. Negotiations entered a
third day today.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of our officers have been in the house. Our approach is
not to push this,'' Missouri Highway Patrol spokesman Lou Wehmer
said. ''We just want to get them back home in the least destructive
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Steve Bartlett said the children may be armed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no plans to rush in there,'' he said. ''We are taking
our time with this so that everyone makes it out safely.''
</P>
<P>
   John Schneider, the U.S. attorney in North Dakota, said his
office and the FBI have suspected for some time that the children
were being held somewhere in Missouri. But it wasn't until about
three months ago that ''we had the first real indication'' of their
whereabouts, he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The farmhouse is on a 300-acre ranch belonging to the Rev.
Gordon Winrod, 73, pastor of Our Savior's Church in Gainesville, in
southwestern Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have linked the church to the Christian Identity
movement, which considers white Christians superior to nonwhites
and Jews. They said Winrod has sent out thousands of newsletters
around the country each year, often calling for the killing of
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Winrod, his son Steven Winrod, 33, and his daughter Carol
Winrod, 27, were arrested Wednesday, charged with six counts of
child abduction and held in the county jail on $500,000 bail
apiece. Authorities did not know whether the Winrods had an
attorney who could comment.
</P>
<P>
   They are accused of kidnapping the children from the youngsters'
fathers -- Winrod's former sons-in-law -- in North Dakota and hiding
them on the Missouri farm. The children were all allegedly
kidnapped in 1994 and 1995 after the fathers were awarded sole
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Winrod's other grandchildren were also abducted; they
were recently returned to their homes in North Dakota, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ozarks region in southwestern Missouri has become a hotbed
for the Christian Identity movement. Of the 102 Christian Identity
affiliates operating in 35 states nationwide, 14 are based in
Missouri and five in Illinois, officials say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reports: AG up for federal bench nomination  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- President Clinton is awaiting only the
results of a background check before announcing the nomination of
Richard Blumenthal for a seat on the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals,
The Associated Press has learned.
</P>
<P>
   ''An announcement is expected in the very near future, within a
matter of days,'' said one source, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what we're being told by the White House,'' said a
second source.
</P>
<P>
   The normally media-friendly Blumenthal declined any comment
regarding the nomination at a news conference Thursday in which he
announced a settlement with a sweepstakes promoter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in recent years that Blumenthal's name
has come up in connection with a seat on the federal bench. In
1997, the White House was close to sending his name up to Capitol
Hill for consideration by the Senate Judiciary Committee, but
Blumenthal opted to run for a third term as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Pagani, spokesman for Republican Gov. John Rowland, said
the governor has not given any thought to a possible successor to
Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the attorney general is placed in nomination, I'm sure
people who are interested in taking over that job will be coming
out of the woodwork,'' Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   Once nominated, Blumenthal would have to win the approval of the
Republican-controlled Senate in a presidential election year. The
high-profile Connecticut Democrat has been in the forefront of
actions against the tobacco industry and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Senate has confirmed seven judges, and six of
those were nominations made last year. There are 43 nominations
pending and 78 vacancies on federal courts across the country.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard College and Yale Law School, Blumenthal
was first elected attorney general in 1990. Before that he was a
member of the state Senate from 1987-1990, and the state House from
1984-1987. He was U.S. attorney for Connecticut from 1977-1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
