<HEADLINE> Schaghticokes file injunction over Paugussett application  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Schaghticoke Tribal Nation has asked a
federal court to force the government to consider its petition for
federal recognition at the same time as that of another tribe it
claims appropriated its ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogy is the critical factor the BIA must consider when
deciding tribal recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe contends another Connecticut tribe, the Golden Hill
Paugussetts, are listing Schaghticoke ancestors on their
application for recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are trying to steal Schaghticoke's genealogy. That's
exactly what it is, theft,'' said Schaghticoke Chief Richard Velky.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Indian Affairs is poised to rule on the Paugussett
petition, according to a request for a temporary restraining order
filed Thursday in U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Schaghticoke recently learned that in GHP's petition
papers, to support its claim for recognition, GHP relies upon
certain genealogy, community and history that in fact belongs to
the Schaghticoke,'' the court documents state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Schaghticoke have asked the BIA to consider the two
petitions at the same time to resolve the conflicting claims,'' the
documents continue.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet Hawk, council chief of the Golden Hill Paugussetts, said
he believed the Schaghticoke's are ''trying to jump on the Golden
Hill bandwagon'' and are claiming common ancestry in order to avoid
what could be an eight-year wait before their own petition for
recognition is heard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it disheartening to find that another Indian tribe
would engage in Indian bashing because of their own problems with
the federal government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Velky said the Golden Hill Paugussetts are claiming they can
trace their heritage back to Gideon Mauwee. Born in 1687, Mauwee is
the first recorded leader or sachem of the Schaghticoke, Velky
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the overlap ''if for some reason or another the BIA
should find them to be a tribe and they took away Schaghticoke's
ancestry, then what happens when it's our turn?'' asked Velky,
whose state-recognized tribe lives on a 400-acre reservation in
Kent and has claims to nearly 4,000 acres of land nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The Schaghticokes applied for federal recognition more than six
years ago. The tribe said it has been three years since the BIA
formally accepted the application.
</P>
<P>
   BIA officials could not be reached for comment. Phone calls were
left with a bureau spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on the request for a temporary restraining order is
expected early next week.
</P>
<P>
   If recognized ''we have no intentions of putting a casino on the
reservation in Kent,'' Velky said.
</P>
<P>
   In March the BIA recommended federal recognition of the Eastern
Pequot and Paucatuck Eastern Pequot tribes, which share 224-acre
reservation in North Stonington.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has two other federally recognized tribes, the
Mashantucket Pequots and Mohegans. Both tribes operates highly
successful casinos in southern Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 0113 </TRAILER>
