<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sentencing postponed in Yale child porn case  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A Yale University professor convicted on
child pornography charges has been given more time to prepare for
his sentencing hearing while a federal judge considers a defense
motion to dismiss one of the counts.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Alvin Thompson on Thursday dismissed
the prosecution's motion to revoke the bond for Antonio Lasaga, 50,
saying the defendant was entitled to the freedom needed to prepare
his presentation for the sentencing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be candid...he has a lot of persuading to do,'' Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomspon postponed sentencing and did not set a date.
</P>
<P>
   Lasaga will remain under house arrest in his Cheshire home until
the sentencing. He wears an electronic monitoring bracelet when he
leaves his home to get religious and psychological counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Lasaga in February accepted a plea bargain where he admitted to
federal charges of downloading tens of thousands of child
pornography images from the Internet and making two pornographic
videos of a preteen boy on the Yale campus.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, William Dow, is seeking to dismiss a charge of
possessing pornography stemming from possession of two videotapes
based on a recent U.S. Supreme Court ruling. He has until Tuesday
to submit a brief and federal prosecutors have until Friday to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   To prove the charges, prosecutors had to show the images were
child pornography and had been transported across state lines, from
foreign countries or had not been manufactured in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   A sentencing date has not been set. Lasaga could get up to 20
years in prison, three years of probation and $500,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Lasaga still faces a civil lawsuit and state charges, including
sexual assault, risk of injury to a minor and promoting a minor in
an obscene performance.
</P>
<P>
   Lasaga, a geology professor, has been on leave from Yale since
the charges surfaced in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, two counselors from the Yale Child Studies
Center testified that Lasaga's victim suffers from severe trauma,
is angry, has trouble communicating, does poorly in school and
lives in fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''He and his family have great difficulty in developing trust as
a direct result of this case,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Kari
Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   Two professors, one from Harvard, the other from Penn State,
testified for the defense. They praised Lasaga as a great
contributor to scholarship and to society.
</P>
<P>
   Lasaga taught chemistry at Harvard in the 1970s and became a
lecturer in 1976. The following year, he joined Penn State as an
assistant professor, becoming a full professor in 1983. He came to
Yale in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
