<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Goalie Makes a Classic Save  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Patrik Elias had a tie game on his
stick until Brian Boucher's glove changed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Elias didn't get the short-handed goal and the New Jersey Devils
never caught the Philadelphia Flyers on Thursday night in a 4-2
loss in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils left wing roared in on a breakaway, with teammate
Claude Lemieux off for high-sticking. He worked around Boucher's
attempted poke check and was incredibly denied on a short wrist
shot that stayed on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got lucky there,'' Boucher said of his save, while lying
flat on his back, that protected a 2-1 lead 1:30 into the second
period. ''He made a pretty good move. If it gave our team a boost,
then great.''
</P>
<P>
   As Boucher tried to knock the puck away from Elias, the forward
cut left and tried to slip the puck past the rookie goalie. Boucher
flipped onto his back, and his outstretched arm blindly kept
Philadelphia's 2-1 lead in tact.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just desperation,'' Boucher said. ''You feel like
you're beat when you miss him with the poke check. There's nothing
left, you can't get it with your legs. ''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers would go up by two goals minutes later and now lead
the best-of-seven series 2-1 -- with Game 4 on Saturday night again
at Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think at the time what impact it will have on a game
or a series,'' Boucher said. ''I just try and do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck was not on New Jersey's side. The Devils were playing
without rookie John Madden, the NHL's leader this season with six
short-handed goals. Madden injured his knee in the Devils' 4-3 loss
in Game 2 and will miss the remainder of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Elias did everything right on the play, except put the puck into
the net.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a breakaway. I didn't score, that's it,'' said Elias,
still frustrated following the game. ''That was his only chance to
save that -- with that hand. It was good sense on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it keep the Flyers in front, it led to an
all-important Game 3 victory for the team that has been rallying
all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't want to be making saves like that all the time,''
Boucher said. ''You need to be more controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher was content to let others marvel at his work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen a lot of hockey games in the NHL, that was top five
I have ever seen,'' said Flyers forward Rick Tocchet, who scored at
7:15 of the second to give Philadelphia a 3-1 lead. ''You have to
put everything, the pressure, the big game. Put that all together
and it's one of the top five saves I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Primeau, who had two assists, including setting up
Tocchet's goal, was also impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got such great composure for such a young goaltender,''
Primeau said. ''Nothing seems to rattle him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0116 </TRAILER>
