<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Spending Up in Moscow  </HEADLINE>
By DEBORAH SEWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Newly confident Moscow consumers are opening their
wallets again and filling up shopping baskets -- defying perceptions
Russia remains mired in its 1998 financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The spending pickup is fueled by a recovery in Russian incomes
from the ruble meltdown, and by gleaming new stores hawking a
dazzling variety of products.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's hard to keep Moscow shoppers away. Typical is Irina
Nikolayeva, a ceramic artist who on a sloppy spring day trudged
through the mud to a new shopping center in western Moscow -- just
for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   She filled her shiny cart with tea and apples she didn't really
need. And she could easily have found carrots and cookies for less
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really nice to come to shop here. It's not that I lose my
head or anything,'' Nikolayeva said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Nikolayeva's shopping choices consisted mainly
of expensive items aimed at rich Russians, or cheap goods brought
back from trips to China, India and Turkey to be sold on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   But in the nearly two years following the nation's economic
emergency, consumer-oriented shops stocked with quality products
have started to appear in Moscow and other major Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of Russia by the Paris-based Organization for
Economic Co-Operation and Development shows incomes are recovering
following the August 1998 crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign companies from Finland, Turkey, China and elsewhere have
opened or expanded supermarkets and shopping complexes, mainly in
the city's center or prosperous neighborhoods. But Russian
entrepreneurs also have invested, taking over and remaking former
Soviet food and clothing stores.
</P>
<P>
   Leaflets, special offers and sales are all part of the
increasingly competitive Moscow shopping scene.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I can compare prices,'' Nikolayeva said as she picked up
her bags at Ramstor, a shopping complex built with Turkish capital.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has always been the benchmark of economic reform in
Russia, a city that in Soviet times daily drew some 2 million
outsiders who scoured the metropolis for scarce consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not the majority of goods in most stores are still
imports, with the high end of the market occupied by Western
companies, especially from Germany and Scandinavia, and the low end
held by firms from China and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,000 shoppers stormed the Swedish furniture and household
goods store Ikea on opening day in March, and thousands more have
visited the vast complex on the northern edge of Moscow since then.
</P>
<P>
   After former President Boris Yeltsin lifted price controls in
January 1992, Russian foods -- already scarce -- virtually
disappeared from the shelves overnight as people faced with soaring
prices stocked up. Other Russia-made products -- often packaged in
brown paper, plain boxes or bottles with rusty tops -- were shunned
for brighter imports.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1998 ruble crisis pushed import prices sharply higher,
spurring demand for less expensive domestic products. As consumer
confidence and spending power improved, Russian producers slowly
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Prices gradually have come down across the board, unleashing
pent-up consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   These days, products made in Russia proudly are stocked along
with imports. Usually cheaper, their familiar tastes are selling
points among Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow-made ''Good Morning'' sour cream boasts on the package
that it's a ''Russian national product.'' A leading brand of
Russian cigarettes is called ''Otchizna,'' or Fatherland.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of well-stocked, well-lit, clean stores is
putting real pressure on kiosks and street traders who hawk their
wares from small stands and tables.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's much harder now because there are many stores,'' said
Irina Smirnova, a retired school teacher who sells Russian-made
cigarettes from a street-side table.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stores get their cigarettes directly from the factory while I
have to buy mine wholesale. I don't know how long I can keep this
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Business is so bad Smirnova is hawking her library, asking three
rubles (10 cents) for a volume of lyrics by Fyodor Tyutchev, one of
Russia's great poets.
</P>
<P>
   While kiosks and street traders are having a hard time, some old
shopping habits flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Lines quickly form on the days when a rusty truck from the
Rzheva collective farm drives up on Yartseva Street in western
Moscow. Farm workers unload cartons of non-pasteurized milk, sour
cream and package of cottage cheese.
</P>
<P>
   It's cheaper, fresher and tastier, the customers say as they
load up their bags.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's markets have had to spruce themselves up to keep
customers from defecting to supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ''I prefer shopping in the market,'' said Alla Mitayeva, an
engineer. ''The vegetables are fresher. They get them directly from
the farm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0127 </TRAILER>
