<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jimenez Leads Deutsche Bank  </HEADLINE>
By ROY KAMMERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALVESLOHE, Germany (AP) -- Tiger Woods was not too happy with the
crowd at the Deutsche Bank Open.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators popped camera flashbulbs during his swing. They
wandered on to the fairways. It was just too close for comfort, as
far as Woods was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem can be solved very easily. In the States, we have
a one-arm-length rule -- one away from the ropes,'' Woods said
Thursday after shooting a 2-under-par 70 in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here, it's a little bit different. They walk in the middle of
the fairways and stand right in front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryder Cup player Miguel Angel Jimenez of Spain shot a 67 to hold
a 1-stroke lead over a trio of players.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had four bogeys, including on each of the first two holes.
He recovered from that slow start with four birdies and by chipping
in from 25 yards at the eighth hole for an eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a solid round of golf,'' said Woods, the defending
champion. ''I got off to a poor start and played well after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez sank a birdie putt on the 18th hole to pull ahead of
British Open champion Paul Lawrie, France's Jean Van de Velde and
South Africa's Retief Goosen, all of whom were at 4-under 68.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, reportedly being paid $1 million in appearance money,
played with a Nike ball for the first time in an event. Woods is
under contract to Titleist.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been testing it for a few months,'' Woods said of the new
ball. ''Basically, I wanted a test round on the tour. If I think
it's viable to switch, I'll switch. If not, I'll go back to my
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the world's top 20 players are entered in the
tournament, but there was little doubt about who was at the center
of the spectators' attention. More than 2,000 followed Woods and
his playing partners, Spain's Sergio Garcia (who shot a 72) and
England's Lee Westwood (71).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 9,000 spectators for the day showed up shortly after
Woods' 8:10 a.m. starting time. That's double the normal opening
day attendance for a German tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The threesome was slapped with a warning for slow play on the
16th hole, where the crowd was particularly unruly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to play fast when there are so many people inside
the ropes and photographers walking down the middle of the
fairway,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had some problems with the cameras a few times. They got me
on my downswing at hole No. 8 eight with a flash.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Jesper Parnevik, coming off his title Sunday at the
Byron Nelson Classic, shot a 70, while Scotland's Colin Montgomerie
carded a 73.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
