<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paraguay Reports Minicrisis Handled  </HEADLINE>
By PEDRO SERVIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Paraguay's president said his
administration had subdued a ''mini-crisis'' amid reports late
Thursday that rebellious soldiers and police had risen up against
his government.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear whether the crisis had ended, since armored
carriers remained posted outside the legislature in downtown
Asuncion. There were no reports of injuries or deaths.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press photographer saw three armored personnel
carriers take up posts outside the building and heard some shots
fired. A strong explosion could be heard after the uprising, which
Interior Minister Walter Bower said began around 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear was how many soldiers were involved and what kind
of action might have been undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   Some Air force planes were seen flying overhead. No soldiers
were spotted on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez Macchi appealed to Paraguayans to remain calm, telling
local radio: ''The crisis is under control.'' Other army divisions
expressed support for the president, as Paraguayan television
broadcast developments into the early hours Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bower charged that the rebellious soldiers were sympathetic to
former army strongman Lino Cesar Oviedo. But he did not elaborate
on the details or say how many soldiers were involved.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the latest crisis for this landlocked South American
nation, which was last thrown into upheaval in March 1999 when
former president Raul Cubas was ousted and replaced by Gonzalez
Macchi.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo, a former army general, is wanted by Paraguayan
authorities in connection with the assassination of Paraguay's vice
president. Authorities also said he has yet to complete a 10-year
sentence for a brief mutiny in April 1996 against former President
Juan Carlos Wasmosy.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo sought political asylum in Argentina, but went into
hiding days before new Argentine President Fernando de la Rua took
office Dec. 10. At last report, he was claiming to be in a remote
area of Paraguay, making sporadic telephone contact with news media
and denouncing the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
