<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fusaichi Pegasus Tours Pimlico  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD ROSENBLATT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- A few days before the Wood Memorial, trainer
Neil Drysdale stood by his barn at Aqueduct looking over the
pedigree of Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now this is interesting,'' Drysdale said, smiling and pointing
to the name of a distant relative of Fusaichi Pegasus.
''Rambunctious. That makes sense. That's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambunctious turns out to be the sire of Fusaichi Pegasus' third
dam, Ramhyde, and rambunctious -- along with playful -- is a word
often used by Drysdale to describe his colt's behavior before and
after races.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus was up to his usual tricks Thursday morning --
two days before the Kentucky Derby winner faces seven challengers
in the $1 million Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   On his first trip to Pimlico's track after arriving on
Wednesday, the frisky $4 million bay colt stopped eight times to
check out his new surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a typical day,'' Drysdale said. ''He wants to see
what's going on. He stopped a couple of times. ... There's no
rushing him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was just stopping and looking around.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough to figure whether Fusaichi Pegasus liked what he saw, but
Drysdale said the son of Mr. Prospector ''half-cantered'' around
the track twice and was comfortable in Barn 7 on the backstretch,
far removed from the Stakes Barn where the other Preakness horses
are stabled.
</P>
<P>
   While displaying powerful finishing kicks to win the Wood by 4\
lengths over Red Bullet and the Derby by 1{ lengths over Aptitude,
Fusaichi Pegasus has become the talk of the racing world. He is the
3-5 favorite for the 1 3-16-mile Preakness, with Red Bullet the
second choice at 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   He's also become quite the character when he isn't racing. He
delayed the start of the Wood on April 15 by three minutes when he
stopped to look around the track before handlers finally led him to
the starting gate. After the win, Fusaichi Pegasus spent the next
five minutes on the first turn staring out at the parking lot and
into the stands before jockey Kent Desormeaux was able to get him
to the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days before the Derby, Fusaichi Pegasus reared up, unseated
his exercise rider and fell on his side without injury while
leaving the track after a workout. ''He's playful,'' Drysdale says.
</P>
<P>
   But when the colt moves into the gate, he's all business.
Fusaichi Pegasus has won five in a row after finishing second in
his first -- and only -- start as a 2-year-old. With each win, his
popularity has grown, and Japanese owner Fusao Sekiguchi's
investment already is paying off in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has earned $1,704,400 -- plus a $250,000 bonus
for winning the Wood and Derby -- and could be worth as much as $50
million through syndication if he continues to win.
</P>
<P>
   The name adds a bit of mystique, too. It is a combination of the
owner's first name -- Fusao -- and the Japanese word ''itchi,'' which
means No. 1. Pegasus is the winged horse of Greek mythology.
</P>
<P>
   The first name is pronounced Fu sah EE chee.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the Preakness, most of the trainers
said it will take the race of a lifetime to upset Fusaichi Pegasus.
Asked how Fusaichi Pegasus might lose, trainer D. Wayne Lukas said,
''He might not. I thought he had less chance of winning the Derby
than he does of winning the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said his colt should be closer to the pace then he was
in the 1\-mile Derby, when Desormeaux settled him into 13th place
along the rail before moving into the lead in the stretch. The
Preakness is a sixteenth of a mile shorter and the field is much
smaller than the 19-horse Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But Drysdale is still concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ''You never know what's going to happen,'' he said. ''I've seen
fields of four or five, and sometimes a horse can get in terrible
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The last three odds-on Preakness favorites have failed to win --
Easy Goer was second to Sunday Silence in 1989 at odds of 3-5;
Swale was seventh in 1984 at 4-5; and Linkage was second to Aloma's
Ruler in 1982 at 1-2. However, 16 of 23 odds-on favorites have won,
the last being Spectacular Bid in 1979 at 1-10.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale is optimistic, but will be more comfortable when the
Belmont Stakes rolls around on June 10. He says Fusaichi Pegasus is
more suited for the 1{-mile distance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here, we are backing up in distance and it's just two weeks
between races,'' Drysdale said. ''It's three weeks before the
Belmont. I think he has a very good style for the Belmont. He
settles very well, is tactical and relaxes very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness field, from the rail out is: Hugh Hefner (Victor
Espinoza, 20-1); Snuck In (Cash Asmussen, 12-1); Impeachment (Craig
Perret, 8-1); Red Bullet (Jerry Bailey, 9-2); High Yield (Pat Day,
10-1); Captain Steve (Robby Albarado, 8-1); Fusaichi Pegasus
(Desormeaux, 3-5); and Hal's Hope (Roger Velez, 20-1).
</P>
<P>
   The winner earns $650,000, the runner-up $200,000, third place
$100,000 and fourth place $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http//www.pimlico.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
