<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kimeses convicted of murder in death of elderly widow  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prosecutors didn't have the body of the murdered
82-year-old millionaire widow, but they did show the blueprints to
the crime that led jurors to convict a mother-and-son team of
murder, robbery and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, Robert Hernandez, 32, said 14 spiral-bound notebooks
in which the 65-year-old mother, Sante Kimes, scribbled
compulsively were key to the verdicts delivered Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The jury forewoman said ''guilty'' 118 times -- 58 times for
Sante Kimes and 60 times for her son, Kenneth Kimes -- to charges
related to a plot to kill Irene Silverman, a former Radio City
Music Hall dancer, and steal her $10 million home. Her body has
never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had advised jurors during closing arguments that the
notebooks and other papers were virtual diagrams of Mrs. Kimes'
thinking as she planned what was perhaps her biggest scam.
</P>
<P>
   ''The notebooks helped me put the pieces together,'' Hernandez
said. ''Everything that was said about the case was in the
notebooks.''
</P>
<P>
   One page listed New York properties Mrs. Kimes had researched.
Next to Silverman's name she wrote, ''Yes! Older ... Go!'' Another
entry read: ''Easy marks ... elderly with money.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notes were lists of weapons to buy -- stun gun, knives,
Mace. There were lists of videos to watch, including ''Whispering
Death,'' and pamphlets to read -- ''Document Fraud and Other
Crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers told the jurors that much of the information in
the notebooks was forged or altered by police. They also said
prosecutors read too much into the notes and jumped to false
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses, who evoke memories of the mother and son in the
film ''The Grifters,'' were stoic as the verdicts were read. After
Mrs. Kimes was pronounced guilty about 20 times, her son began
chatting with his lawyer, Mel Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   The mother and son, natives of Oklahoma and longtime residents
of Las Vegas, face life in prison when State Supreme Court Justice
Rena Uviller sentences them on June 27. Meanwhile, they are charged
with murder in Los Angeles in the fatal shooting of a businessman
there.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of eight women and four men began deliberating shortly
after 2 p.m. Monday following a 13-week trial. They sent out a note
saying they had reached verdicts on all the charges shortly before
2:30 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Juror Michael Alvarez, 34, and Hernandez said jurors had no
problems convicting the Kimeses of murder without a corpse. They
said they considered the murder counts Wednesday, and the first
votes on them were unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Uviller had instructed the jurors that the absence of a body did
not mean there had not been a murder.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said the verdict ''sends a
clear message that you cannot escape a murder conviction by
disposing of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman vanished July 5, 1998, the day the Kimeses were
arrested here in New York on a stolen car warrant from Cedar City,
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But for the bad $14,900 check they wrote to pay for the green
1997 Lincoln Town Car, the Kimeses might have remained at large
much longer, and might never have been charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they believe the Kimeses strangled Silverman,
bound her with duct tape and put her into large garbage bags,
stuffed her into a duffel bag, and then disposed of the body.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said the Kimeses killed Silverman as part of
their plan to steal the elegant six-story, beaux-arts mansion her
late husband Sam, a real estate millionaire, had left her on
Manhattan's tony Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrested them, the Kimeses still had Silverman's
personal documents and a plethora of other suspicious items.
</P>
<P>
   In the car, police found loaded 9 mm and .22-caliber pistols, a
red wig and two fright masks, plastic handcuffs, $30,000 in cash, a
stun gun box, syringes, and a pink liquid similar to a known ''date
rape'' drug.
</P>
<P>
   They also found cassettes of Silverman's telephone conversations
-- secretly taped by the Kimeses -- and a deed with Silverman's
forged signature that transferred her town house to the Kimeses for
a fraction of its value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
