<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Toledo Won't Enter May Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's government says a presidential runoff
election will go forward on May 28, despite candidate Alejandro
Toledo's decision not to participate and a warning from the
Organization of American States that it will not endorse the vote.
</P>
<P>
   After the National Election Board rejected Toledo's demand to
push back the second-round vote until June 18, he called on
supporters to stage massive street protests this evening in Peru's
major cities to force a postponement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The dictatorship has taken the cruel decision to remain in
power,'' Toledo shouted to a crowd of thousands of banner-waving
supporters at a street rally in Lima's working-class neighborhood
of La Victoria on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   His followers roared their agreement.
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori scorned Toledo's demand, accusing him
of quitting because he knew he was going to lose the election.
Polls show the two tied in voter preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't change the rules at this stage of the process,''
Fujimori told reporters hours earlier in the southern city of
Ayacucho.
</P>
<P>
   His statement was broadcast on television, after dozens of
protesters yelling ''Get out, tyrant!'' stoned his vehicle as it
pulled away from a campaign rally filled with thousands of his
supporters and curious onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's bodyguards fired automatic rifles into the air to
drive back the demonstrators near the main plaza in Ayacucho, high
in the Andes 230 miles southeast of Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ''Toledo has realized that to beat this guy he has to force a
political crisis,'' said political scientist Julio Carrion.
''Fujimori is not somebody who sticks to constitutional rules or
any sort of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's rivals maintain the vote should have been scheduled
within 30 days after all results from the April 9 general election
were in, including congressional seats, which were determined only
last week. Those results are under scrutiny for alleged
vote-rigging by election workers and several candidates from
Fujimori's slate. One congressional candidate from Toledo's party
has also been implicated.
</P>
<P>
   The May 28 date was set on the night of April 29, after the
national election board received final results for the presidential
race. Fujimori's government maintains that it is interpreting the
constitution correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Peru narrowly averted political turmoil in the first election --
a process riddled with irregularities and allegations of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The vote ended with Fujimori falling some 20,000 votes short of
outright victory after three days of protests by Toledo's
supporters and the threat of economic and diplomatic sanctions from
the United States if vote counting conditions were not improved.
</P>
<P>
   But in the weeks following, the OAS said the government was
still dragging its feet on fixing a chronically faulty system. This
week, the OAS mission said it was ''technically impossible'' to
correct the vote-counting system and ensure a fair vote in the time
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round, independent monitors were denied access to
tabulation centers during the tallying of votes. Ballot totals
mysteriously decreased as the tally progressed and when the final
results were delivered, the figures showed about 1 million more
ballots were cast than there were voters.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Stein, the OAS mission's chief of election observers, on
Wednesday complained that Peruvian officials handed his mission an
incomplete copy of vote-counting software for the upcoming
election. And he said he was still waiting for a promised report
detailing how election officials planned to train vote counters.
</P>
<P>
   In its strongest statement yet, the OAS said Thursday it was
giving Fujimori's government until Monday -- after a nationwide test
of the election authority's new vote-counting software -- to make
necessary improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But Stein said there was ''an overwhelming need'' to ''postpone
the election.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot endorse the results if what happened in the first
round continues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-week postponement demanded by Toledo represents the
minimum amount of time the OAS has said is necessary to adequately
test the computer system and retrain vote counters.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said Thursday that the upcoming vote would be a simpler
matter than the April 9 election because it did not include
congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone who knows the slightest bit about mathematics would
know that it is a much simpler operation to count the votes of two
candidates,'' Fujimori said. ''It requires vigilance but it is no
reason to infringe on the functioning of the constitution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
