<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temperature Rising on China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supporters and opponents alike of a landmark
China trade bill are increasing the pressure on a dwindling number
of undecided House members in advance of next week's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides predicted a close vote, although supporters were
increasingly confident they would prevail. President Clinton
planned a five-minute Oval Office address to promote the measure on
Sunday, although not all TV networks planned to carry it live.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be tight. We're not there but we'll get there,'' House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the chief Republican nose counter
and a strong supporter of the bill, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week to go to the vote, sponsors appeared to be
within striking distance of the 218 votes they would need to
prevail if all 435 members vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., a top Democratic supporter, said
he expected that 70-75 of the House's 211 Democrats would vote for
the bill. Republicans were looking at about 140-145 GOP votes.
</P>
<P>
   The administration pledged to work hard through the weekend to
try to win more converts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not where we need to be. We have more votes to get,''
said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   A final vote was expected in the House on Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the measure in the more free-trade-minded Senate
appears assured. However, a heavy campaign against the bill in the
House by organized labor has seriously undercut Democratic support.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the bill grew this week after Republican leaders
agreed to support side legislation to protect American industries
from a surge in imports from China and for a permanent commission
to monitor human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would extend permanent normal trade relations to China
and ease the way for its entry into the 135-nation World Trade
Organization. It would end two decades of annual congressional
votes on China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the trade bill condemn China's human rights abuses
and suggest that increasing trade with China could cost American
jobs by flooding U.S. markets with low-cost goods. Supporters say
it will open China's vast markets to American companies and help
promote American values there.
</P>
<P>
   The vote ''will have profound implications for the free world's
trading system and the long-term growth potential of the American
economy,'' Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said on Thursday
during a rare appearance with Clinton in the White House Rose
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan had said the same thing the week before in a letter to
House Banking Committee Chairman James Leach, R-Iowa, but the White
House wanted him to do it again before the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know when Chairman Greenspan talks, the world
listens,'' Clinton said. ''I just hope the Congress is listening
today.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., an opponent, suggested that
normalizing trade with China could give China greater access to
sensitive U.S. technology and pose a serious national security
risk.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton on Thursday, Wolf asked the president to
direct the CIA to declassify information that bears on ''the
national security risk China poses to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
