<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Bill Pushes Retirees Health  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Military retirees would get better health care
coverage, improved access to prescription drugs and treatment in
all military hospitals under a major defense bill the House has
passed.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, approved 353-63 on Thursday, authorizes nearly
$310 billion, $4.5 billion above the president's request, for
weapons procurement, military readiness and personnel.
</P>
<P>
   It moves to improve the quality of life of military personnel
with a 3.7 percent pay raise, a subsistence payment of up to $500 a
month for poorer military families, including those on food stamps,
and funds to reduce out-of-pocket housing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Health care for service members and retirees is a focus of the
bill. In particular, the 1.4 million Medicare-eligible retirees and
family members who are entitled to prescription drug benefits but
can't get them because they live far from military bases would be
able to subscribe to a mail order service with an $8 co-payment.
</P>
<P>
   They also could use network retail pharmacies with a 20 percent
co-payment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, in a statement, applauded the extension of
prescription drug benefits and said it ''urges Congress to show
similar support for providing coverage to all Medicare
beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which now goes to the Senate, moves to improve
TRICARE, the HMO-like military health care plan for 20-year
retirees and dependents, by reducing limits on catastrophic
expenses, reimbursing travel expenses for those who must go more
than 100 miles to see a specialist and eliminating cost inequities
for family members living apart from military health facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 406-10 for an amendment by Rep. Gene Taylor,
D-Miss., that would put on a permanent and nationwide status a
demonstration project under which six military facilities have been
treating Medicare-eligible retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The base bill had provided only for an extension of the
experiment until more data could be collected, but Taylor argued
that people who made the service a career with the assumption they
would get a lifetime of free health care at military facilities
''don't need any more demonstration promises. ... They need the
promise that was made to them on the day that they enlisted to be
fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., argued that military hospitals don't
have the space or the training to treat a large population of
elderly veterans and that the demonstration project, meant to be
cost-neutral, has cost the Pentagon more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   By making what is called Medicare subvention permanent ''we're
taking a crippled program that has not been fixed and putting it on
the road to financial disaster,'' he said. His proposal to add
sites to the current demonstration program was defeated 323-95.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers approved by 218-201 an amendment offered by Rep. Ike
Skelton, D-Mo., to remove language in the bill at odds with an
agreement reached in January between President Clinton and the
governor of Puerto Rico on the future of Navy training on the
Puerto Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, growing out of protests against live ordnance
training on Vieques, permitted the Navy to resume training with
dummy bombs and promised a referendum on whether the Navy should
leave Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, however, would have barred the secretary of the
Navy from transferring the eastern end of the island from Navy
jurisdiction and allowed $40 million in economic aid to the people
of Vieques only when live-fire training was resumed on the range.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers voted 264-153 to end funds for U.S. ground troops in
Kosovo if the president by next April 1 doesn't certify that
European allies are paying their fair share in the peacekeeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4205.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Armed Services Committee:
http://www.house.gov/hasc
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0210 </TRAILER>
