<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Not Crucial For Presidency  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Never mind those national polls that show
George W. Bush slightly ahead of Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral system designed by the founding fathers makes it
almost impossible to predict November's outcome by national polls
alone since the battle is fought by separate elections in the 50
states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   And few average Americans have the time or inclination to sort
through the state polls to figure out which states are key for each
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people are worrying about having to mow their lawn or
pick up the kids at ballet or Little League, rather than who's
going to win Michigan,'' said political analyst Stuart Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, national polls often serve as the public's main
source of information about a presidential race, especially this
early.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates, their strategists and political analysts
watch a chess match involving the states, their voting histories
and local campaign issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't watch state by state, I look at the overall
view,'' said Robert Haydu, a 61-year-old businessman from St.
Augustine, Fla., who follows politics closely. For a more detailed
picture of the political landscape, ''I trust the good newspapers
and magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidency is decided by who can put together 270 electoral
votes. Each state has a share of votes based on population and
whoever wins a state claims all of its votes.
</P>
<P>
   National polls serve an important purpose, analysts say, by
providing insight on how candidates are doing with certain groups
like women or independents and on people's feelings about their
personal qualities and positions on issues, and by measuring broad
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''When a candidate is doing well or poorly, it usually shows up
across the board,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns acknowledge that the Republican Bush has had a
good two months with public opinion since the March primaries
settled the nominations. At that time, Democrat Gore had about
pulled even with the Texas governor after the bruising GOP contest
between Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain. Bush moved quickly to
the middle after his primary battle, while Vice President Gore has
kept up a steady mantra of criticism against his rival.
</P>
<P>
   A marked shift in the national polls, like the recent wave
showing Bush leading Gore, often signals that there is movement in
up to two dozen swing states, those that have been the most
competitive in recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a certain sense that a rising tide lifts all boats,''
said Charles Cook, editor of the Cook Political Report.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has led Gore in the vast majority of polls, Cook noted,
with most of Gore's leads or ties coming between the South Carolina
and Michigan primaries in late February, when McCain was strongest
and Elian Gonzalez dominated the news. Gore tried to capitalize on
the custody fight over the 6-year-old Cuban boy by arguing that the
case should be decided in family court as the Clinton
administration forcibly returned Elian to his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Americans felt the boy belonged with his father,
and many people viewed Gore's handling of the crisis unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
   In state polls, Gore leads in New York and California -- the two
largest states -- in several Northeastern states and his home state
of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads in Texas and Florida -- the next two biggest states --
many Southern states, scattered Western states and in several
historically competitive states like Ohio, Kentucky and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Both are locked in close races in battleground states like
Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey and New Mexico, as well as some
where Gore should be strong like Wisconsin, West Virginia, Oregon
and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads in 17 states that account for more than two-thirds of
the electoral votes needed to win. Gore leads in eight states with
fewer than half the needed votes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bush currently has the advantage in national polls,
Michigan State University political scientist David Rohde forecasts
a close election because of the lack of an incumbent and the strong
economy, which could help Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''The national polls and state polls are not dependable yet,''
said Rohde. ''The public really hasn't turned its attention to the
presidential race. We won't have the public really focused on the
race until after the (August) conventions.''
------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Will Lester covers polling and politics for The
Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0232 </TRAILER>
