<DOCNO> APW20000519.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barge Traffic Threatens Marine Life  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of nature's oldest and most
primitive-looking fish and a tiny, golden-brown freshwater clam
could be driven to extinction by the federal government's
transformation of the upper Mississippi River into a commercially
navigable waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service said Thursday that the agency in
charge of maintaining the nation's water transportation systems is
placing the future of the already endangered pallid sturgeon and
Higgins' eye pearlymussel in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   At fault, the service says, is the Army Corps of Engineers'
60-year-old system of 37 locks and dams on the Mississippi and
Illinois rivers, plus its dredging operations and navigation
channel training stations that make the once-rocky and meandering
river system passable for large, commodity-laden barges.
</P>
<P>
   The decision could have enormous implications for the fierce
battle over whether the corps should move ahead with a $1 billion
project to double the length of seven locks.
</P>
<P>
   Agribusiness companies say massive lock expansions are crucial
to keeping transportation costs low as grain exports -- and barge
traffic -- rise. Otherwise, they say, Midwestern products will not
be able to compete on the global market.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say that river's fragile ecosystem would be
further endangered by more large-scale changes. They applauded the
service's decision as bolstering that argument.
</P>
<P>
   The corps is expected to complete this year a $54 million study
into what should be done, but its initial conclusions appear to
favor the expansion. That study became even more controversial in
February with allegations that top corps officials rigged the data
to justify the costly construction.
</P>
<P>
   Several investigations into those charges are pending, including
by the Army inspector general, the National Academy of Sciences,
the General Accounting Office and at least four congressional
committees.
</P>
<P>
   In its ''biological opinion,'' the Fish and Wildlife Service
does not order any changes to the current operation of the
navigation system.
</P>
<P>
   But it was conducted primarily to provide a baseline for another
round of negotiations if new construction is proposed. That process
could call for more drastic remedies such as changing dredging
procedures or alterations to dams, and that could make the proposed
project too expensive to undertake.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the corps must protect the pallid sturgeon, a large
fish with a shovel-shaped snout and long feelers, by creating new
backwater habitats. The pallid sturgeon has been on the endangered
species list for 10 years, mostly because of the loss of a
free-flowing, diverse river.
</P>
<P>
   The corps already spends $19 million a year to improve the
health of the Mississippi. Service officials could not estimate how
much it may cost to help the pallid sturgeon recover.
</P>
<P>
   For the 3-inch pearlymussel, listed since 1976 and now being
virtually smothered by invasive zebra mussels, the corps must
relocate significant numbers of them out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Galford, a spokeswoman with the corps' Mississippi Valley
Division, said the agency had no comment, as it has not had enough
time to review the opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0238 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
