<HEADLINE> Hockey Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Friday, May 19:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas at Colorado (8 p.m. EDT). The Avalanche return home with
the Western Conference finals tied 1-1.
STAR:
Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Rick Tocchet, Flyers, had a goal and an assist, helping
Philadelphia defeat New Jersey 4-2 to take a 2-1 series lead in the
Eastern Conference finals.
SEEING STRAIGHT:
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Avalanche defenseman Adam Foote said Thursday that his
vision ''is absolute normal'' after being hit in his right eye by
the errant stick of Dallas forward Jere Lehtinen in Game 2 of the
Western Conference finals Monday. Despite the injury, Foote will
sit out Game 3 against the Stars tonight and does not know when he
will be cleared to return to the ice. If Foote returns, doctors
will require him to wear a visor for the remainder of the playoffs.
SITTING OUT:
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia center Daymond Langkow missed Game 3 of the Eastern
Conference finals against New Jersey on Thursday night because of a
concussion. Langkow, who hadn't missed a game since joining the
Flyers in December 1998, was hurt in a collision with Devils
defenseman Scott Stevens about a minute after scoring the winning
goal in the Flyers' 4-3 victory in Game 2 Tuesday night. ... New
Jersey center John Madden also missed the game and will be out 2-3
weeks after hurting his right knee late in the third period in a
collision with Philadelphia center Keith Primeau.
SCOUTING:
</P>
<P>
   The International Hockey League announced Thursday its first and
second All-Star teams, as selected by the league's coaches. Topping
the first team were defenseman Brett Hauer of Manitoba and left
wing Steve Maltais of Chicago, who were both chosen for a second
consecutive year. The Chicago Wolves had the most All-Star
selections with five.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''More than anything we just felt we had to show people that we
could play in this building. I just sensed that our guys the last
couple of days were focused for the challenge and we came up with a
huge effort.'' -- Philadelphia center Keith Primeau on the Flyers'
Meadowlands jinx after a 4-2 road victory over New Jersey in Game 3
of the Eastern Conference finals. Philadelphia had a 4-22-2 record
at Continental Airlines Arena over the last five years, and was
0-7-1 in its eight previous games there.
</P>
