<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers 4, Devils 2  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The Philadelphia Flyers are leading
New Jersey in the Eastern Conference finals because Brian Boucher
has elevated his game to the level of Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher made 27 saves as the Flyers took a 2-1 lead over the
Devils in the best-of-seven series with a 4-2 victory Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But just one of them turned the game around.
</P>
<P>
   With the Flyers leading 2-1 early in the second period, Patrik
Elias got a short-handed breakaway, and seemingly made all the
right moves to tie the game. He avoided Boucher's poke check and
seemed to get the goalie out of position with a move across the
net.
</P>
<P>
   All he had to do was slide the puck into the net.
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't count on was Boucher making like Hasek, a
two-time NHL MVP. Boucher flipped over from his stomach to his
back, threw back his glove hand and somehow stopped the puck from
sliding toward the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was his only chance to save that puck,'' said Elias, who
led the Devils with 35 goals this season. ''It was good sense on
his part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers stayed ahead and, a couple of minutes later, Rick
Tocchet scored his third goal in two games. Philadelphia, the team
everyone wrote off after losing Game 1, had its second straight
win.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Devils behind for the first time in the playoffs
heading into Game 4 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They have lost the momentum they gained in winning the opening
two rounds of the playoffs and Game 1 in Philadelphia on Sunday,
and they still have to figure out a way to beat Boucher, who had 35
games of NHL experience coming into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''That save he made was huge,'' Devils forward Randy McKay said.
''That would have tied the game up. It was a great save. He has
shown he is a quality goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet knew that before the playoffs started.
</P>
<P>
   ''In practice, when you beat 'Bouche' he always throws his arm
back, he never gives us,'' Tocchet said. ''Dominik Hasek does that.
You think you have him beat and he'll throw a limb out. He figures
eight of 10 times he won't get it, but the other two times he will.
Bouche got it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Devils goalie Martin Brodeur wasn't as good on a night he only
faced 21 shots. He had trouble handling two long shots to start the
game, and he never seemed to get comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Recchi beat him between the legs on a back-hander early in
the first period on a 2-on-1. Keith Jones scored on a rebound later
in the period -- one of two goals set up by Keith Primeau -- to give
the Flyers a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet's goal in the second period gave Philly a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the Devils narrowed the margin to 3-2 on Scott
Niedermayer's goal with 4:01 to play, Simon Gagne closed out the
scoring with back-hander after avoiding a poke check by Brodeur,
who didn't seem to move well on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the worst game I've played in the playoffs,'' said
Brodeur, who has now given up eight goals in the last two games
after giving up 16 in the first 11 playoff contests. ''I let the
guys down. I just didn't come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Larry Robinson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think this will go down as one of his better ones, but
he's been keeping us in most games,'' Robinson said. ''It's about
time we returned the favor. We had some opportunities and the other
kid played pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   While Brodeur will have to play better, the difference between
winning and losing in this series has been small.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did we make mistakes? Yes,'' said Claude Lemieux, who scored
the Devils' other goal. ''Did we make more mistakes than them? No.
Did we have as many or more chances than they did? Yes. The bottom
line is the kid had a great performance and we didn't bury our
chances.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils usually do that against the Flyers. The loss was only
the fifth in 29 games (22-5-2) against Philadelphia in the past
five years. It also snapped an eight-game winless streak (0-7-1)
here.
</P>
<P>
   The loss gives home-ice advantage back to Philadelphia, and the
Devils will have to win three of the final four games in the series
to advance to the Stanley Cup finals for the first time since 1995.
Philadelphia last went in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a desperate hockey game, no doubt about it,'' Devils
center Jason Arnott said of Game 4 on Saturday night. ''It's
do-or-die game. We have to go into it thinking we have to win the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers also have some concerns heading into the game.
</P>
<P>
   John LeClair was cut in the face by Brodeur's stick in the third
period and needed 36 stitches on the right side of his nose and
three under his eyelid.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair, who leads the Flyers with six playoff goals, plans to
play on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Devils, so does Boucher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
