<HEADLINE> Baseball Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Friday, May 19:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona at N.Y. Mets (7:10 p.m. EDT). The first-place
Diamondbacks visit New York in a rematch of last year's NL Division
Series.
STARS:
Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Mark McGwire, Cardinals, homered three times and had a
career-high seven RBIs, leading St. Louis over Philadelphia 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   -- Denny Hocking, Twins, was 5-for-6, including two doubles and a
two-run homer, as Minnesota beat Oakland 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   -- Alex Ochoa, Reds, had an RBI single with one out in the bottom
of the 10th inning, lifting Cincinnati over Pittsburgh 4-3.
SWAT HISTORY:
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Mark McGwire homered three times to pass Mickey
Mantle for eighth place on the career list in the Cardinals' 7-2
win over Philadelphia on Thursday night. McGwire has 539 homers,
Mantle had 536. Next up is Mike Schmidt at 548. It was the 64th
multihomer game of McGwire's career, breaking a tie with Willie
Mays for the second-most ever. Babe Ruth had 72.
SNAPPED:
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Stan Spencer won for the first time in 14 starts as
the Padres beat Florida 6-2 Thursday night. Spencer had not earned
a victory since his major league debut on Aug. 27, 1998, against
Philadelphia, going 0-8 with a 7.20 ERA in that span. ... Minnesota
ended a five-game skid with a 10-5 victory over Oakland.
SIDELINED STAFF:
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland pitchers Jaret Wright, Charles Nagy and Ricardo Rincon
were placed on the 15-day disabled list Thursday.
SWIPED:
</P>
<P>
   Florida stole 10 bases -- one short of the modern NL record -- yet
still lost to San Diego 6-2 Thursday night. The post-1900 NL record
of 11 was set by the New York Giants in 1912 and tied by St. Louis
in 1916. The modern major league mark of 15 was set by the New York
Highlanders, later the Yankees, in 1911. The last time an NL club
had 10 steals in a game was June 30, 1996, when Colorado did it
against Los Angeles.
STREAKING:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is 5-0 in extra-inning games and won for the ninth
time in 11 games after a 4-3, 10-inning win over San Francisco on
Thursday. ... Frank Catalanotto set a Texas record by reaching base
12 straight times, and extended his streak of consecutive at-bats
with hits to a team-record 10 in an 8-7 win over Baltimore.
STRUGGLING:
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has dropped 13 of 15, including an 8-7 loss to Texas
on Thursday night.
SLOPPY WEATHER:
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, rain washed away the Houston-Milwaukee
doubleheader, Colorado at New York, and Los Angeles at Chicago.
Detroit and Cleveland were in the top of the fourth when their game
was called as well.
SWINGS:
</P>
<P>
   Before striking out twice in Thursday night's 8-6 loss to
Arizona, Montreal's Vladimir Guerrero struck out just 12 times in
38 games.
STROLLING:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Ken Griffey Jr. walked four times in a 4-3,
10-inning win over Pittsburgh on Thursday.
STRONG START:
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Greg Maddux allowed two runs and six hits over seven
innings as the Braves defeated San Francisco 3-2 Thursday.
SIX IN A ROW:
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won their sixth straight and handed the Giants their
sixth consecutive loss, 3-2 Thursday.
SETTING AN EXAMPLE:
</P>
<P>
   While the Atlanta Braves have the best record in the majors,
28-12, their top farm team, the Triple-A Richmond Braves of the
International League, have the worst record in professional
baseball, 9-32.
STATS:
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Greg Maddux improved to 10-0 against the Giants in 10
starts with the Braves. ... Montreal second baseman Jose Vidro
hasn't committed an error through the first 38 games of the season
and has gone 43 straight games without an error, dating to last
season. ... St. Louis has homered in 36 of 40 games and is on pace
to hit 344, shattering the record of 264 set by the 1997 Seattle
Mariners.
SCOUTING:
</P>
<P>
   James Madison left fielder Greg Miller went 7-for-7 with three
home runs and nine RBIs -- all records -- as the Dukes outlasted
Richmond 24-21 in an elimination game Thursday in the Colonial
Athletic Association tournament.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, the thing I wanted to do was keep my head out of my
(rear), which is what I've been doing for the last week or so.'' --
Atlanta's John Rocker on pitching a perfect ninth inning in
Thursday's 3-2 win over San Francisco, after surrendering nine
hits, six earned run and five walks in his previous 3 1-3 innings.
SEASONS:
May 19:
</P>
<P>
   1910 -- Cy Young won his 500th game as the Cleveland Indians
defeated Washington 5-4 in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   1933 -- The Ferrell brothers -- Rick and Wes -- homered in the same
game for the only time in their careers. Rick hit his homer against
his brother.
</P>
<P>
   1960 -- Juan Marichal, in his first game with the San Francisco
Giants, pitched a one-hitter to beat the Philadelphia Phillies 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   1968 -- After hitting 10 home runs in six games, Frank Howard of
the Washington Senators was stopped at Detroit by pitcher Earl
Wilson, who won the game 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   1981 -- Pittsburgh's Jim Bibby gave up a leadoff single to Terry
Harper of the Atlanta Braves, then retired the next 27 batters for
a 5-0 one-hitter. Bibby also hit two doubles.
</P>
<P>
   1998 -- Mark McGwire hit three two-run homers against
Philadelphia. It was the second time this season and fourth time in
his career McGwire hit three homers in a game. McGwire became the
12th player to have two three-homer games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Today's birthday: Turk Wendell 33.
</P>
