<HEADLINE> NBA Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Friday, May 19:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami at New York (9 p.m. EDT). Another installment in one of
the NBA's fiercest rivalries, as the Knicks try to send this
Eastern Conference semifinal series to a seventh game.
SOARING:
</P>
<P>
   As the New York Knicks returned from Miami early Thursday
morning, a jet blast from the charter plane lifted coach Jeff Van
Gundy's car airborne and sent it hurdling over three other
vehicles. Also extensively damaged were Knicks guard Allan
Houston's 1997 Mercedes, assistant coach Brendan Malone's 1999
Lincoln, and the car belonging to the team's media relations
director. The four cars were driven onto the tarmac at Westchester
County Airport, near the team's suburban New York headquarters, as
the charter arrived at 3 a.m. EDT.
SINGLE NO MORE:
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers star Kobe Bryant confirmed he is engaged on
Thursday, but refused to identify his future bride. He did say,
however, she's not an athlete or actress. A member of the Lakers'
organization, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said Bryant,
21, is engaged to an 18-year-old woman from Orange County.
STATS:
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100 previous best-of-seven playoff series that have been
tied 2-2, the team that won Game 5 has gone on to win the series 84
times.
SEEKING A COACH:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's courtship of St. John's coach Mike Jarvis for
the Washington Wizards coaching job, now official with all the
appropriate people notified, became a long-distance affair Thursday
with the Red Storm coach back in New York and Jordan still in
Washington. As talks continued, it became clear Jordan will not
meet his self-imposed Sunday deadline for naming a new coach. A
team source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there were no
plans to announce a new coach until early next week.
STATUS:
</P>
<P>
   George Irvine wants to be the Detroit Pistons' head coach, and
the club wants to clear the ''interim'' from his title. However,
reaching contract terms has been anything but a slam dunk, Irvine's
attorney said Thursday. He did not elaborate on whether the
differences were over money, the contract's length or both. Pistons
vice president Joe Dumars told The Detroit News that the sides were
far apart, but the gap could be bridged.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''The difference with a guy like (Shaquille O'Neal) and maybe
Karl Malone is they have so much brute strength that it kind of
almost makes it unfair that they're going to also get the benefit
of the majority of the calls. But that's the way this league has
always been and always will be, and all you can really hope for is
some semblance of fairness.'' -- Portland guard Greg Anthony on
playing against O'Neal and the Lakers.
</P>
