<HEADLINE> 767 Engine Inspections Ordered  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration is
ordering U.S. airlines to conduct emergency inspections of 120
Boeing 767 aircraft after mechanics found damaged bolts in one
plane's engine pylons.
</P>
<P>
   Under the emergency airworthiness directive issued Thursday,
airlines must inspect their planes in five or 10 days depending on
when the specific jetliner was manufactured, said FAA spokeswoman
Alison Duquette. Seven U.S. airlines, including two cargo carriers,
are affected by the order.
</P>
<P>
   The planes were considered safe to fly and are not being
grounded, although it was unclear whether the five-hour long
inspections would disrupt any flights.
</P>
<P>
   The directive applies to the first 230 Boeing 767s manufactured
after production began in 1982, said company spokeswoman Liz
Verdier. The type of bolt causing concern was phased out in the
late 1980s and replaced with an improved version.
</P>
<P>
   However, many airlines have continued using the original bolts
without problems, Verdier said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the affected planes, 120 are operated by U.S. carriers
including American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Trans World Airlines,
United Airlines, US Airways, UPS and Airborne Express. The
directive doesn't apply to newer 767s used by these and other
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   While the planes operate worldwide, the FAA can only require the
inspection on U.S. carriers. Other countries normally follow the
U.S. lead in such inspection orders.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 767 operators have already begun inspections based
on early advisories from Boeing and the FAA, Verdier said. So far,
inspections of 20 additional aircraft have found no problems, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Boeing 767s two engines hangs beneath a wing on a
large pylon. Two smaller struts provide additional support to the
engine and each connects to the wing with two bolts, Verdier said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA issued the order after mechanics inspecting a 767 found
damage in three of the four bolts in the secondary supports for one
engine, Duquette said. One bolt had cracked and two had fractured.
She did not name the airline involved.
</P>
<P>
   The damaged bolts were made of a material, H-11 steel, and
appeared to have been unusually corroded.
</P>
<P>
   Under the directive inspectors must look for these types of
bolts and replace them if found, or perform an ultrasound
inspection to ensure they are not damaged, Duquette said. The
inspections will cost the U.S. fleet about $36,000, or about $300
per plane.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first 767 was delivered in 1982, about 900 have been
produced. The wide-bodied twinjet is the dominant plane on routes
between Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Three have been involved in fatal crashes -- a Lauda Air flight
in Thailand following mid-flight deployment of an engine thrust
reverser in 1991, a hijacking that ended when the plane ran out of
fuel and was ditched in the ocean and EgyptAir Flight 990, which
crashed into the Atlantic Ocean in October.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation investigators have not yet determined the cause of the
EgyptAir crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0315 </TRAILER>
