<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 03:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani: No decision announced at town hall meeting  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani expressed regret at
his handling of the fatal police shooting of an unarmed black man,
but offered no hint on whether he would continue his run for the
U.S. Senate in the face of treatment for prostate cancer and a
crumbling marriage
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't reached any conclusions. I'm going to try to reach
conclusions as soon as I can,'' he told MSNBC moderator Andrea
Mitchell at an hour-long town hall meeting broadcast nationally on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republican officials were invited to join Giuliani at
the 92nd Street Y on Manhattan's Upper East Side, where the town
hall was held. Meanwhile, a campaign aide was sent to Buffalo to
prepare for the state GOP convention, which will nominate a Senate
candidate in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Both developments fueled speculation that the mayor, who
announced his illness three weeks ago, might make a political
announcement Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Though the mayor offered no hints on his Senate plans, he did
answer a variety of other questions on topics ranging from crime to
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked frequently by Mitchell whether he regretted some of his
most controversial actions of the past year, the mayor said he had
made a mistake in his handling of the police shooting of Patrick
Dorismond, an unarmed black man killed in a recent scuffle with
undercover police.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was widely criticized for defending the police by
releasing Dorismond's police record to the public -- including
sealed details of a juvenile arrest. During the forum, Giuliani
said he was right to release the records, but also said he should
have been more understanding of the loss of a life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a mistake,'' he said. ''I should have also conveyed the
human feeling that I had, the compassion, the loss of the mother. I
think if I could do it over again, I would have tried to balance it
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Mitchell whether he has become more compassionate
because of his illness, Giuliani said ''something has to happen to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   In making a decision on treatment, Giuliani said he had
anticipated a different process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kind of approached it as if this was a big case, or a budget
decision,'' the former prosecutor said. But this decision he said,
''involves thinking about your life, mortality, the quality of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   One audience member asked Giuliani how he could expect others to
look up to him as a moral leader, in light of his recent
acknowledgment of a close relationship with another woman and his
plans to separate from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I would just ask people to take a look at me as a
human being,'' he responded. ''I'm not a religious leader ... I'm a
governmental leader, and its my public records and my public
actions and the things that I do as the mayor that you should
mostly be concerned about, and your moral concerns ... should be
with your own private life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was interrupted by applause several times from the 900-person
crowd. Tickets were $20 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the mayor was insisting that he had not made a decision,
his campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, stood nearby smiling -- a
marked contrast to his gloomy outlook last week when it appeared
the mayor would pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has repeatedly said his decision on treatment would
precede any announcement on whether he would stay in the Senate
run.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's three options for treatment are surgery, external
beam radiation and radioactive seed implantation. The 15-year
survival rate is 95 percent for surgery and 60 to 70 percent for
the two less invasive options.
</P>
<P>
   The past three weeks have been particularly rocky for the mayor,
both because of his cancer diagnosis and his announcement that he
would seek a legal separation from wife Donna Hanover. He went
public with the latter decision only after questions arose about
time he is spending with Manhattan divorcee Judith Nathan, a woman
whom he has called a ''very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover retaliated with a news conference in which she accused
her husband of previously having had a relationship with one of his
aides, a charge Giuliani has denied.
</P>
<P>
   At the forum Thursday evening, he said he ''has not always put
his family first,'' but declined to answer questions about Nathan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
