<HEADLINE> Kiwi Skipper, Tactician Quit Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- Russell Coutts, who skippered Black
Magic to a historic America's Cup victory in March, is quitting the
winning syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   As Team New Zealand announced Friday it contracted designer and
tactician Tom Schnackenberg and young helmsman Dean Barker for the
next defense, tactician Brad Butterworth announced that he and
Coutts were resigning.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is with regret and sadness I must announce we have taken
the most difficult decision to leave the Team New Zealand
organization,'' Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can assure you that our decision was made only after the
most intensive consideration and personal soul-searching. It is
certainly the hardest decision either of us has ever had to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth said the pair failed to come to terms with a new
management structure for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have reached the conclusion that we do not want to manage a
defense within the proposed structure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Peter Blake, Team New Zealand chief in two winning
campaigns, announced earlier this year that he was relinquishing
control of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Schnackenberg, Coutts and Butterworth had been expected to head
the new team.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in New Zealand suggested Coutts and Butterworth could
link with a yet-to-be named Swiss syndicate for the 2003 regatta.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were members of the team that wrenched the America's
Cup from Dennis Conner in San Diego in 1995 and returned for the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts skippered Black Magic to a 4-0 lead against Italian
challenger Prada in the best-of-nine final series off Auckland
before handing over the helm to Cup rookie Barker for the
series-clinching race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
