<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 04:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paraguay Subdues Minicrisis  </HEADLINE>
By PEDRO SERVIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Rebellious soldiers who rose up
against the government surrendered to authorities early Friday to
end a four-hour standoff, a Paraguayan army colonel said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Felix Dario Collante said that soldiers of the army's First
Division surrendered at 2:45 a.m. He refused to say how many turned
themselves in, but described them ''as a few active officers and a
retired general.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is totally under control,'' Collante said. He
said he ordered government tanks that had been called out to keep
the peace to return to an army base.
</P>
<P>
   Government spokesman Jaime Bestirred said Paraguayan President
Luis Gonzalez Macchi had imposed a 30-day state of emergency giving
him special powers to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayan media reports said 12 police officers had also been
detained. The officers were arrested in police headquarters,
according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Collante said three congressmen also had been detained, although
it was unclear what role, if any, they had played in the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The uprising began when army vehicles barreled through downtown
Asuncion and parked in front of the legislative building late
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press photographer saw three armored personnel
carriers take up posts outside the building and heard some shots
fired. A strong explosion could be heard after the start of the
rebellion, which Interior Minister Walter Bower said began around
10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of injuries or deaths, and power was cut
in Asuncion shortly after the tanks took up position. Some air
force planes were seen flying overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez Macchi appealed to Paraguayans to remain calm, telling
local radio: ''The crisis is under control.'' The heads of the air
force and navy, along with several army divisions, also publicly
expressed support for the president as Paraguayan television
broadcast developments into the early hours Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bower charged the rebellious soldiers were sympathetic to former
army strongman Lino Cesar Oviedo. But he did not elaborate on
details or say how many soldiers were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Marcelo Duarte, who was inside Congress at the time
that shots were heard, told local radio that at least two shots had
been fired at the building by the tanks outside.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the latest crisis for this landlocked South American
nation, which was last thrown into upheaval in March 1999 when
former president Raul Cubas was ousted and replaced by Gonzalez
Macchi after the shooting death of Vice President Luis Argana.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo, a former army general, is wanted by Paraguayan
authorities in connection with the assassination of Argana.
Authorities also said he has yet to complete a 10-year sentence for
a brief mutiny in April 1996 against former President Juan Carlos
Wasmosy.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo fled Paraguay after Cubas resigned and was granted
political asylum in Argentina, where he stayed before going into
hiding days before new Argentine President Fernando de la Rua took
office Dec. 10. At last report, he was claiming to be in a remote
area of Paraguay, making sporadic telephone contact with news media
and denouncing the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0426 </TRAILER>
