<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 19, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Allies Leave U.S. in Iran Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some of America's best friends split away to approve $232
million in World Bank loans to Iran, despite intensive lobbying by Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright. She made three arguments against the loans: That Iran
sponsors terrorism, has not adopted sound economic principles and should not be
rewarded while it conducts a ''show trial'' of 13 Jews on charges of spying for
Israel. The allies, including best-friend Britain and Germany, were not swayed,
and joined the majority of the 24-member bank executive board yesterday in
approving the loans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.H. Votes To Repeal Death Penalty
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- New Hampshire's governor promised to veto a bill that
would repeal the death penalty, something no state has done since the U.S.
Supreme Court allowed capital punishment to resume 24 years ago. Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen was expected to veto the bill as soon as she received it -- as early as
today. The state Senate passed the measure 14-10 Thursday, endorsing a House
vote taken in March. New Hampshire's Legislature is just the second to vote to
repeal the death penalty since the Supreme Court's decision in 1976.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peru's Toledo Won't Enter May Runoff
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's government says a presidential runoff election will
go forward on May 28, despite candidate Alejandro Toledo's decision not to
participate and a warning from the Organization of American States that it will
not endorse the vote. After the National Election Board rejected Toledo's demand
to push back the second-round vote until June 18, he called on supporters to
stage massive street protests this evening in Peru's major cities to force a
postponement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Stress May Help Women Live Healthier
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Women react to stress differently than men, turning to
their children and seeking out friends instead of using the ''fight-or-flight''
reflex, according to a study out today. The University of California, Los
Angeles study suggests that the ''tend-and-befriend'' pattern keeps stressed
women calmer. Researchers say the response also may help explain why women are
less vulnerable to drug and alcohol abuse and stress-related disorders such as
hypertension than men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Paraguay Subdues Minicrisis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Paraguay's president said his administration had
subdued a ''mini-crisis'' amid reports late yesterday that rebellious soldiers
and police had risen up against his government. But it was unclear whether the
crisis had ended, since armored carriers remained posted outside the legislature
in downtown Asuncion. There were no reports of injuries or deaths. An Associated
Press photographer saw three armored personnel carriers take up posts outside
the building and heard some shots fired.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giuliani Regets Way He Handled Police Shooting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani expressed regret yesterday for the
way he handled a recent police shooting of an unarmed black man, speaking at a
public forum at which he gave no hint whether he'll continue his run for the
U.S. Senate. The town hall meeting came three weeks after Giuliani revealed that
he has prostate cancer and said he didn't know if he would continue to seek the
Senate seat against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
3 Die in Pa. Pier Collapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A pier supporting a new open-air bar collapsed and
plunged into the Delaware River last night, killing at least three people and
injuring more than three dozen, hospital and city officials said. Three people
died, and 37 people -- including eight rescue workers who were hurt while trying
to pull victims from the debris-strewn water -- were taken to hospitals, said
Stephanie Franklin-Suber, the mayor's chief of staff. Identities were not
immediately released.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Variant of Love Bug Virus Spreading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A variant of the ''Love Bug'' computer virus has started
spreading, virus experts said yesterday, and while it may not spread as fast as
the original, it is much more destructive when it infects a computer. Computers
at several large companies were infected late yesterday, said Dave Perry,
spokesman at anti-virus software company Trend Micro Inc., in Cupertino, Calif.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks close lower today. The Nikkei shed 173.46 points
to close at 16,858.17.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rangers 8, Orioles 7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- David Segui hit a go-ahead, three-run homer that
capped a six-run sixth inning last night as the Texas Rangers rallied to beat
the Baltimore Orioles 8-7. Mike Lamb had three doubles and Frank Catalanotto had
three hits for the Rangers, who have won four straight and seven of nine,
putting themselves over .500 for the first time since April 15.
</P>
