<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Prime Minister Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's prime minister quit
today over a tax scandal that has further sullied the country's
political establishment, already reeling from a series of scandals.
</P>
<P>
   The downfall of Prime Minister Park Tae-joon came after a court
ruled this week that he had concealed ownership of properties to
avoid large tax payments. Though such concealment wasn't illegal at
the time, Park's action was considered unethical and he will be
required to pay back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am sorry to the government and nation that my personal moral
issue has caused controversy,'' said Park, a 72-year-old retired
army general who became prime minister in February.
</P>
<P>
   Park's resignation from his largely ceremonial post was unlikely
to affect President Kim Dae-jung's chief policies: economic reform
and engagement with communist North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Kim accepted Park's resignation and appointed Finance Minister
Lee Hun-jai to serve as acting prime minister, the president's
office said.
</P>
<P>
   Park's successor will be named next week. The prime minister is
second in line to the president, but has a limited role in making
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties and civic groups had called on Park to quit
and issue a public apology after a court said this week that he put
property valued at $5.3 million under the name of his private
treasurer to avoid paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The incident displays the moral hazards of this regime,'' said
Chang Kwang-keun, spokesman for the opposition Grand National
Party. ''The ruling camp must take special measures to restore its
morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Concealing ownership of property has since been criminalized.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prime Minister Park's bid to conceal his properties for tax
evasion cannot be tolerated on moral grounds, although he has no
legal responsibilities,'' The Korea Times quoted Citizens Action
Network, an advocacy group, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Two other scandals involving allegations of corruption in past
governments have surfaced recently, raising demands for higher
ethical standards for public office holders.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a Korean-American lobbyist is suspected of having
bribed government officials and politicians to help win French firm
GEC-Alsthom a $2.1 billion contract for South Korea's first
high-speed rail line in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In another scandal, a Korean-American lobbyist allegedly used
payments and personal contacts to help American firm Raytheon Co.
win a $230 million spy plane project in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists in both cases are under investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
