<HEADLINE> Death Penalty Sought For Rail Killer  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- To win a death sentence for the so-called
railroad killer, prosecutors are putting on mini-trials for eight
other slayings to which he has admitted.
</P>
<P>
   They are trying to stack up evidence that Angel Maturino
Resendiz, convicted Thursday in the slaying of a Houston-area
researcher, left a trail of death across three states over two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have here is a career burglar who developed a taste
for murder and rape,'' prosecutor Devon Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Following Thursday's verdict, the 41-year-old Mexican national
told the court outside the jury's presence he wanted to die by
injection. When pressed for a reason, he said he didn't want to
spend life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got some plans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Allen Tanner later said he did not know what
his client meant.
</P>
<P>
   In the death penalty phase, which was to resume today, jurors
must decide whether Maturino Resendiz is a threat to society and
whether there are mitigating factors against his execution. If they
reject the death penalty, he would face life in prison with no
possibility of parole for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz was convicted despite defense arguments that
he was insane when he raped and killed Claudia Benton in December
1998. He also has admitted to eight other slayings from 1997 to
1999, but prosecutors must offer proof of each crime to support a
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson opened the prosecution's penalty phase with details
from the June 15, 1999, slayings of George Morber, 80, and his
daughter, Carolyn Frederick, 51. They were killed in Morber's rural
Jackson County, Ill., trailer, about 100 feet from railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's husband, Donald Frederick, made the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw her feet (protruding from blankets),'' he testified
Thursday. ''I took my right hand and hit the wall to try to get
some arousal. Then I ran back and call the Jackson County
sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   Fingerprint and hair samples connect Maturino Resendiz to the
crime, investigators testified.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were expected to present evidence and testimony
about five more killings in Texas, then close with testimony from
the only known survivor of the two-year rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whom authorities have not identified, was left for
dead after being raped near some Lexington, Ky., railroad tracks.
She was the girlfriend of Christopher Maier, a 21-year-old
University of Kentucky student bludgeoned to death with a log,
allegedly by Maturino Resendiz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
