<HEADLINE> Nursing Home Defedants Plea Innocent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A former deputy state health commissioner
and a nursing home operator have pleaded innocent to federal
bribery charges that allege corruption in the Oklahoma nursing home
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Brent VanMeter and James R. Smart were arraigned Thursday, one
day after they were accused in a federal grand jury indictment of
bribery in connection with a state program that receives funds from
federal health care programs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Valerie Couch scheduled trial for July 10. Both
were released on their own recognizance. If convicted, they face up
to 10 years in prison and a fine of up to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're ready to defend this case,'' VanMeter's attorney, Mack
Martin, said. ''We are ready to get this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart and his attorney, Warren Bickford, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that on April 17, VanMeter, 46, agreed to
accept money from Smart to alter state Health Department records to
allow Smart's nursing homes to be compensated by federal programs
at a higher rate than he would otherwise receive.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Arlene Joplin said Smart, 43, is charged
''with offering and agreeing to give a bribe to Mr. VanMeter.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Dan Webber has said he expects additional
indictments to be returned in the investigation.
</P>
