<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 05:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Intervenes in China Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- After intervention by China's premier, European
and Chinese negotiators appeared to be nearing a deal today that
would clear Beijing's largest remaining barrier to joining the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Zhu Rongji, whose crucial intercession clinched a
similar market-opening deal with the United States in November, met
with European Union Trade Commissioner Pascal Lamy for about an
hour today. It was their first meeting in five days of talks this
week between the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to expectations that a deal was imminent, China's Foreign
Ministry called foreign news organizations to alert them that an
important announcement on the WTO talks would be made later at the
foreign trade ministry.
</P>
<P>
   But Lamy and Chinese foreign trade minister Shi Guangsheng
resumed negotiations inside the trade ministry, and an EU spokesman
sought to dampen speculation that the deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   ''The negotiations are ongoing and until negotiations are
completed there is no agreement,'' the spokesman, Anthony Gooch,
said. ''Any rumors about imminent signatures are premature.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a very delicate process and it's a delicate
moment,'' Gooch said. He added that Lamy would stay in Beijing as
long as it's ''constructive and necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's intervention came on the heels of two unusual meetings --
one Thursday night, the other today -- between Lamy and Shi, each
with their lead WTO negotiators. Their technical teams, which hash
out the details of proposals, were not included.
</P>
<P>
   Asked earlier about the hastily arranged Thursday night session,
the first in this round of talks, Gooch said: ''We are reaching an
important moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave no details but added: ''It's very hard to gauge as to
when and whether you are going to have a deal, let alone the
timing. It's extremely difficult to predict anything.''
</P>
<P>
   China and the EU have provided scant details of their
negotiations. The EU is seeking greater access to China's
telecommunications, financial services and automobile sectors -- on
better terms than the United States wrested from Beijing in
November.
</P>
<P>
   A deal would smooth China's way toward its goal of joining the
WTO this year. The 15-member EU is the largest of six remaining WTO
members yet to reach the separate market-opening agreements with
China that are necessary for Beijing's membership.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are taking place in the shadow of a debate in the U.S.
Congress over whether to grant China permanent low-tariff access to
the American market. Both Chinese and EU negotiators are trying to
leverage the timing of next week's congressional debate to their
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   A deal could sway undecided members of the U.S. House of
Representatives to support the permanent trade status and end the
annual reviews that China's critics favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0544 </TRAILER>
