<DOCNO> APW20000519.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beetles Mar California Church  </HEADLINE>
By JESSIE SEYFER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- It has survived catastrophic earthquakes
and made it through devastating fires, but California's oldest
intact church hasn't been able to escape its latest threat --
powderpost beetles.
</P>
<P>
   The insects have eaten through 200-year-old statues of saints,
left priceless wooden carvings crumbling and munched on treasures
dating back to when San Francisco was little more than fishing
villages and sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   The 209-year-old Mission Dolores chapel, now in the heart of San
Francisco's bustling Mission District, first showed signs of damage
about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been quite a shock,'' said Guire Cleary, the church's
curator. ''Hopefully the beetles will be gassed, but that still
doesn't conserve the statues. We can't undo the damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the ornate wall of wooden carvings and statues
behind the altar, Cleary says they have been ''eaten alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleary said over the past year the working-class parish scraped
together the $60,000 needed to fumigate the church, but he doesn't
know where it will get the money to restore the wooden statues and
facades. He estimated the cost between $750,000 and $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each one of the beetle holes -- and there are millions of them
-- needs to be injected with epoxy resin,'' he said. ''Financially,
it's currently completely out of the range of this parish.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Granett, a University of California entomology
professor, said it's likely the powderpost beetles -- named for
their ability to turn wooden posts to powder -- have been there for
generations with little exterior damage.
</P>
<P>
   He said the beetles crawl inside wood and eat their way out, and
it's possible they've been steadily gnawing away until now -- when
the damage is finally becoming apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Inspections of the beetle destruction have revealed another
artifact that Cleary says is in dire need of repair. Behind the
elaborate facade of the sanctuary is an 18th century mural that was
painted with vegetable dyes by the Ohlone Indians, San Francisco's
original inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's crumbling,'' Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   The church's main concern is preserving its wooden treasures,
from its California redwood roof to its statues, all of which bear
damage from the beetles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our last renovation was just a few years ago,'' Cleary says.
''And it looks like we're going to have to do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0600 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Judge Denies Starr Inquiry  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES JEFFERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal judge has rejected a request
for an investigation of former independent counsel Kenneth Star,
saying claims that he or his staff tried to suborn perjury or
engaged in misconduct in the Whitewater investigation are baseless.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut attorney Frank Mandanici and two former Starr
targets, Stephen A. Smith and Julie Hiatt Steele, challenged
Starr's prosecution of Whitewater figure Susan McDougal and Starr's
testimony before a House committee on President Clinton's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Their complaints fell to U.S. District Judge John F. Nangle
after all federal judges in the Eastern District of Arkansas
recused themselves from hearing the case.
</P>
<P>
   In an order Thursday, Nangle said Steele presented ''absolutely
no evidence that the OIC ever directly or impliedly asked her to
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he found no evidence that Starr or his office
attempted to suborn perjury from Smith and noted that Smith
acknowledged that Starr investigators never asked him to lie.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said Mandanici might merit discipline and sanctions
himself for violating his order against leaking matters related to
the case to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Mandanici said the judge had sealed his files but there was no
gag order in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm obviously disappointed and I disagree with his decision,
but until I actually read the order I can't comment further,''
Mandanici said.
</P>
<P>
   Mandanici filed his complaint in June 1999. By the end of the
year, he had been joined by Steele and Smith, a communications
professor at the University of Arkansas in Fayetteville. The three
asked for the appointment of an outside counsel to investigate
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   A former aide to Clinton when he was governor of Arkansas, Smith
pleaded guilty in 1995 to a misdemeanor stemming from Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury deadlocked in favor of convicting Steele on
charges that she obstructed Starr's investigation of allegations by
Kathleen Willey that Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   Starr decided not to retry Steele, who denied Mrs. Willey's
assertion that she confided the alleged advance to her friend hours
after it happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
