the European Union reached a market-opening trade deal today, clearing Beijing's
largest remaining hurdle to joining the World Trade Organization. European Union
Trade Commissioner Pascal Lamy and Chinese foreign trade minister Shi
Guangsheng, surrounded by their aides, signed the agreement and capped it with a
champagne toast after five days of arduous negotiations. The deal's most
immediate impact would likely be on a contentious debate next week in the U.S.
Congress on granting China much-sought permanent low-tariff access to the
American market. EU negotiators believed an agreement with Beijing would sway
wavering members of Congress into supporting China's permanent trading rights.
