<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 06:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan President Takes Office Sat.  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The worst-case scenario was that Chinese
missiles would rain down on Taiwan because the island's newly
elected president would rashly declare independence in the months
after his stunning victory.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened so far, and most experts say the
80-mile-wide Taiwan Strait that divides the longtime rivals should
remain calm for the near future. Although long-standing
disagreements are keeping them far from the bargaining table, both
are remaining cool-headed -- despite occasional flare-ups in
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, Taiwanese President-elect Chen Shui-bian takes
office, officially beginning a political era that could raise
tensions with China to new heights. Beijing will no doubt listen
closely to Chen's inauguration speech.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of war can't be ruled out, analysts say, and the
United States could quickly get dragged into a conflict. Just four
years ago, U.S. warships cruised to Taiwan when China tested
nuclear-capable missiles near the island's two main ports.
</P>
<P>
   Since the two sides split amid civil war 51 years ago, Beijing's
mission has been to reunify this democratic island of 22 million
people with the communist mainland. Independence for Taiwan has
been out of the question, and China has warned that it would wage
war if Taipei sought a permanent split or indefinitely delayed
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on its threats could be extremely reckless for China at
the moment. A war could torpedo Beijing's long campaign to join the
World Trade Organization, and would likely ruin China's chances of
getting permanent trade status with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''China has a lot of economic issues in the United States'
hands,'' said Lee Si-kuen, a political science professor at the
National Taiwan University.
</P>
<P>
   Many defense experts doubt that China has enough warships or
planes to successfully invade Taiwan. The massive Chinese army has
its roots in land-based guerrilla warfare and has never fought a
war that involves a complex naval landing.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Adm. Thomas B. Fargo, the U.S. Pacific Fleet
commander in chief, said in Hong Kong that invading Taiwan would be
an ''almost impossible military task'' for China.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pollack, a senior Asia specialist at the Rand Corp.
think tank, agreed. But he noted that history is full of conflicts
caused by miscalculations.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts point out that Beijing's goal would probably be
to simply frighten Taiwanese away from seeking independence. This
could be accomplished by firing a ballistic missile at an
unpopulated area, blocking a port or seizing one of Taiwan's
numerous outlying islands.
</P>
<P>
   Since Chen was elected March 18, Beijing has said peace talks
could begin if Taiwan would do one thing: Agree that the island is
an inseparable part of one China.
</P>
<P>
   A front-page editorial in today's Communist Party's People's
Daily newspaper repeated that demand.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taiwan is a part of China and Taiwan has only one future --
reunification with the mainland,'' the editorial said. ''This is a
very clear and non-negotiable issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has long been wary of Beijing's ''one-China'' principle
because it fears accepting that would mean admitting the repressive
Beijing government is the island's legitimate ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has refused to accept the principle as a precondition for
talks, but has said he would be willing to discuss it during a
summit, which he has said he would attend anywhere and at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Before Chen was elected, Beijing tried to warn voters away from
the former Taipei mayor, once a vocal supporter of Taiwan
independence. His Democratic Progressive Party still favors letting
Taiwanese voters decide whether the island should break away for
good. Chen has softened his stance, saying he would only hold such
a vote if China attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Since Chen's victory, Beijing has given him time to prove
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will listen to his words and watch his actions,'' Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said Tuesday, repeating a
phrase Beijing has been using the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who is succeeding retiring President Lee Teng-hui, has
been avoiding provocative language and has ignored threatening
rhetoric printed in China's state-run media.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the U.S. delegation attending Chen's inauguration,
Laura D'Andrea Tyson, today praised the president-elect's handling
of China relations in recent months. Tyson, an economist, served in
President Clinton's administration in 1993-96.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are really impressed at your approach of thinking through
this issue and talking to many people and treating it as a major
issue of establishing trust and dialogue,'' said Tyson, a business
professor at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0655 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 07:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A deadly storm system that punished the Midwest with
heavy rain
and high winds pushed east today, spawning thunderstorms from Texas
to New England. It was clear and mostly dry in the westerain half of
the nation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fast-moving storms ripped through Illinois late Thursday,
knocking out power to 100,000 customers and forcing the
cancellation of more than 100 flights at Chicago's two airports.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kemper, 69, of suburban Wilmette was killed when a tree
limb landed on his car, police said. Hundreds of trees were
reportedly down in Arlington Heights and Palatine, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 3 inches of rain fell in Michigan. Wind gusts of more
than 80 mph were reported in Indiana and Illinois, and torainadoes
were reported in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got rain. We got hail. We had wind,'' said Rhonda Daniels
at the Casey's General Store in Carlisle, south of Des Moines. ''We
were all kind of scared. It looked pretty bad out.''
</P>
<P>
   The severe weather arrived in the Northeast shortly before
sundown Thursday, with driving rain in New York City and powerful
thunderstorms in upstate New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and
Massachusetts. About 100 homes were damaged in the Poughkeepsie
area and more than 65,000 customers lost power across the region.
</P>
<P>
   By tonight, the cold front extending from New England to Texas
will move very slowly to the south, bringing powerful thunderstorms
to Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania and New Jersey south to Virginia and
the Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, strong storms were forecast in parts of Arkansas,
Louisiana, Texas and Mississippi. Otherwise, the central and
southerain Plains were expected to remain fair.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and calm conditions were also forecast for the Rockies, West
and the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Highs today were forecast to reach the 50s in New England and
the Great Lakes area; the 60s in the Northeast and Midwest; the 70s
in the Northwest, Plains and West; and the 80s and 90s in the
Southeast and Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The highest temperature reported in the continental United
States on Thursday was 100 degrees at Laredo, Texas, and Thermal,
Calif. The low was 24 at Alamosa, Colo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0701 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Opponents Hoild Protests  </HEADLINE>
By DUSAN STOJANOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Undeterred by what they say is a
brutal intimidation campaign, Slobodan Milosevic's opponents held
more demonstrations today despite police beatings of pro-democracy
protesters and new arrests of the Yugoslav president's critics.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred activists of the popular student group Otpor, or
Resistance, which has been specifically targeted by the government,
handed out leaflets in downtown Belgrade, protesting Milosevic's
latest crackdown against independent media and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 uniformed and plainclothes police checked their
identity documents, taking away at least one Otpor flag with a
clenched fist emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Six Otpor members were detained overnight, adding to hundreds
arrested in the past several days. Otpor -- accused by the
government of ''terrorism'' -- has gained rapid popularity because
many Serbs have been disappointed by bickering among traditional
opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes between police and demonstrators over the past two days
have left more than 150 people injured -- at least 30 seriously.
Tens of thousands have turned out in Belgrade and other cities to
protest police raids on the major nongovernment television station
and other media critical of Milosevic that have left them either
shut down or with their operations seriously impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police intervention was extremely brutal, they are trying
to frighten the citizens into stopping the protests,'' Goran
Svilanovic, one of the opposition leaders, told The Associated
Press today.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, hundreds of riot police fired tear gas and charged
at more than 10,000 protesters who massed in front of the
opposition-run city hall in Belgrade to protest the closure of the
nongovernment Studio B television.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters shouting ''Kill yourself Slobodan and save Serbia!''
threw stones and firebombs at the police, who dispersed the crowd
into smaller groups, then chased individual demonstrators through
nearby streets, hurling several to the ground and pummeling them
with rubber truncheons.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 terrified protesters sought refuge in the city
hall building. Those who could not push their way inside were
severely beaten. At least nine people were seen dazed with blood
streaming down their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The official Tanjug news agency said today that ''unrestrained
crowds'' and ''militants'' had attacked the police, who had to
intervene with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes marked the biggest escalation of tensions in years.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern city of Nis, which is also controlled by the
opposition, several hundred protesters gathered outside the city
hall attacked 14 deputies of Milosevic's ruling Socialist Party as
they were left the meeting, pelting them with sticks. Two of the
deputies were hospitalized, while the others were bruised.
</P>
<P>
   The incident added to the tension ahead of a rally planned in
Nis for this evening, along with similar gatherings in Belgrade and
other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing clashes, the influential Serbian Orthodox Church
appealed for an easing of tensions and called on the government to
halt the media crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's allies accused the nongovernment media and
opposition of working for American and NATO interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state has waited too long to face the evil, and there is
no more waiting,'' said Serbian Deputy Prime Minister Vojislav
Seselj. ''We won't allow American agents to come to power.''
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown began after the slaying of a prominent official
last Saturday, which authorities blamed on opposition parties and
Otpor.
</P>
<P>
   Dissent in Serbia has grown recently due to rising poverty and
state repression.
</P>
</TEXT>
