<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 07:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modified Seed Planted Accidentally  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Genetically modified seed that was accidentally
mixed with normal seed has been planted in Britain and Sweden,
countries where the use of such strains is still under study, their
governments say.
</P>
<P>
   The findings have created a dilemma over whether such crops must
be destroyed in keeping with stringent regulations over the
planting of genetically altered plants.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed seed, produced in Canada in 1998, contained about 1
percent genetically modified material, the British Ministry of
Agriculture, Fisheries and Food said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   About 22,000 acres were sown in Britain with affected stocks of
oilseed rape seed in 1999, and about 11,600 acres were sown this
spring, the ministry said. About 1.2 million acres are devoted to
oilseed rape across Britain each year.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish Board of Agriculture said it was alerted about
genetically modified seed by retailer Svaloef Weibull AB on Monday,
after tests in Germany revealed it.
</P>
<P>
   Board spokeswoman Anna-Clara Sjoestroem said today that nine
tons of oilseed rape seed containing some amount of genetically
altered material were imported last year and 3,000 acres were
planted. The resulting crop was sold.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 1,200-1,500 acres were planted using the seed. The
board expects to reach a decision next week on whether to destroy
the crop, Sjoestroem said.
</P>
<P>
   Baroness Hayman, a British junior agriculture minister, said the
government had consulted the Advisory Committee on Releases to the
Environment and the Food Standards Agency, ''and both confirmed the
view that there is no risk to public health or the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''However, the issue of seed purity is a serious one,'' she
added. ''The farmer and his customer do not expect to find that a
crop of conventional seed contains an unexpected or unacceptable
level of GM material.''
</P>
<P>
   Genetically altered crops are plants whose genes are manipulated
to produce characteristics such as resistance to pests. The British
government has sponsored trials designed to indicate whether such
crops pose a threat to the environment, but has not yet approved
any for commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   David Heath, a British Liberal Democrat lawmaker, said a strong
case existed for destroying the crops grown from the Canadian seed
''in exactly the same way that the experimental protocols for the
farm scale trials insist upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Gibson of the governing Labor Party said the agriculture
ministry must ''get a grip'' on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''They should have known that the public are very suspicious of
what's going on and they should have suspected that there would be
a mix-up of seeds -- it's almost inevitable,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no commercial use of genetically modified crops in
Sweden and cultivation of such plants requires special permission.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report from Swedish retailer Svaloef Weibull to
the government agriculture board on Thursday, Canadian supplier
Advanta Seeds believes the ''contamination'' took place through
crossing in the field during seed production, possibly spread by
bees or the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The genetically modified plants resulting from the seed do not
produce pollen, said Svaloef Weibull, so other plants will not be
affected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0718 </TRAILER>
