<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 19, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China, EU Reach Trade Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China and the European Union reached a market-opening trade
deal today after the Chinese premier intervened, clearing Beijing's largest
remaining hurdle to joining the World Trade Organization. European Union Trade
Commissioner Pascal Lamy and Chinese foreign trade minister Shi Guangsheng
signed the agreement after five days of arduous negotiations. ''This agreement
is in the fundamental interests of both parties,'' a smiling Shi said. The
deal's most immediate impact will likely be on a contentious debate next week in
the U.S. Congress on granting China much-sought permanent low-tariff access to
the American market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Deadly Storm System Pushes East
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A deadly storm system that punished the Midwest with heavy
rain and high winds pushed east today, spawning thunderstorms from Texas to New
England. Fast-moving storms ripped through Illinois late last night, knocking
out power to 100,000 customers and forcing the cancellation of more than 100
flights at Chicago's two airports. Richard Kemper of suburban Wilmette was
killed when a tree limb landed on his car. The severe weather arrived in the
Northeast shortly before sundown yesterday, with driving rain in New York City
and powerful thunderstorms in upstate New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and
Massachusetts.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Three Die in Pa. Pier Collapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rescue crews picked through tangled planks and floating
debris today, trying to determine why a pier supporting a new outdoor nightclub
collapsed into the Delaware River. Three people died and 37 others were injured,
including eight rescue workers hurt trying to pull victims out of the water.
About 40 people were on the pier when it plunged into the 30-foot-deep water
shortly yesterday evening. A canvas tent over the pier also collapsed,
blanketing many people who fell about eight feet into the dark, murky water and
bringing down the back walls of an adjacent dance hall.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Atlantis Lifts Off on Fourth Try
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Atlantis and seven astronauts
blasted off today on a mission to fix the international space station,
succeeding finally on their fourth launch try. Atlantis rose from its seaside
pad at 6:11 a.m. as the space station sped over Bulgaria. The shuttle is
expected to catch up with the station early Sunday. Four of the six
electricity-generating batteries on the space station have failed or are
failing. Replacing them is NASA's No. 1 priority.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic Opponents Hold Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Undeterred by what they say is a brutal
intimidation campaign, Slobodan Milosevic's opponents held more demonstrations
today despite police beatings of pro-democracy protesters and new arrests of the
Yugoslav president's critics. Several hundred activists of the popular student
group Otpor, or Resistance, which has been specifically targeted by the
government, handed out leaflets in downtown Belgrade, protesting Milosevic's
latest crackdown against independent media and opponents. Six Otpor members were
detained overnight, adding to hundreds arrested in the past several days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Variant of Love Bug Virus Spreading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A new virus is eating its way through computers, and this
one is smarter and more destructive than the worldwide ''Love Bug'' plague that
inspired it, experts say. While the ''Love Bug'' was given away by the
''ILOVEYOU'' subject line of the e-mails that carried it, the new virus changes
subject lines every time it is sent. It also destroys most of the files on the
computers it infects. The virus was detected at several large companies late
yesterday. The subject line of an infected e-mail starts with ''FW: '' and
includes the name of a randomly chosen attachment from a previous e-mail on an
infected computer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks ended lower today with the Nikkei shedding 173.46
points to close at 16,858.17.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McGwire Hits 539th Home Run
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mark McGwire broke ties with Mickey Mantle and Willie
Mays, homering three times and setting a career high with seven RBIs last night
in the St. Louis Cardinals' 7-2 win over the Philadelphia Phillies. McGwire is
eighth on the career list with 539 homers, three ahead of Mantle. McGwire's 64th
multihomer game broke a tie with Mays for the second-most ever. Babe Ruth had
72. McGwire broke a tie with Mantle in the first inning when he hit a three-run
drive off Curt Schilling. McGwire hit a two-run homer in the second inning to
make it 5-0. He added a two-run shot in the eighth off Wayne Gomes for No. 539.
AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN 
</P>
