<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 19, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Variant of Love Bug Virus Spreading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An anti-virus software company says thousands of computers
at several large companies have been infected by a virus that uses the same
mechanism as the ''Love Bug'' virus, but is much more destructive and has a
different source code. While the ''Love Bug'' was given away by the ''ILOVEYOU''
subject line, the new virus changes subject lines every time it is sent. The
subject line of an infected e-mail starts with ''FW: '' and includes the name of
a randomly chosen attachment from a previous e-mail on an infected computer.
''Each time the virus spreads, it mutates itself to evade detection,'' Symantec
Corp., an anti-virus software maker in Cupertino, Calif., said yesterday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Trade Deficit Sets Record in March
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit widened to an all-time high of
$30.2 billion in March as a record foreign oil bill overwhelmed a rebound in
American exports of farm products and autos. The deficit with China narrowed
slightly but the trade gap with Japan rose to its highest level this year. The
Commerce Department reported that the overall deficit increased by 5.1 percent
from a revised February figure of $28.7 billion. The trade deficit continues to
be the one glaring exception to the nation's current economic prosperity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China, EU Reach Trade Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China and the European Union reached a market-opening trade
deal today, clearing Beijing's largest remaining hurdle to joining the World
Trade Organization. The deal's most immediate impact will likely be on a
contentious debate next week in the U.S. Congress on granting China much-sought
permanent low-tariff access to the American market. EU negotiators believe an
agreement with Beijing would sway wavering members of Congress into supporting
China's trading rights.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Three Die in Philly Pier Collapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rescue crews today are trying to determine why a pier
supporting a new outdoor nightclub collapsed into the Delaware River, killing
three people. Thirty-seven more were injured, including eight rescue workers
hurt trying to pull victims out of the water. Authorities say they don't believe
anyone is still missing. About 40 people were on the pier when it plunged into
the 30-foot-deep water yesterday evening. A canvas tent over the pier also
collapsed, blanketing many people who fell about eight feet into the water.
Eleven people remain hospitalized this morning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Second Big Game Winner To Claim Prize
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A suburban Chicago family has stepped forward to claim the
other half of last week's record-setting $363 million Big Game jackpot, lottery
officials say. That winning ticket was sold at a Lake Zurich, Ill., convenience
store. The Daily Herald of Arlington Heights today identified them as Joe and
Sue Kainz of Tower Lakes, owners of the Wild Onion Brewing Co. in Lake
Barrington. The couple's three children -- Michael, 34; Patrick, 29; and John,
26 -- all work for the family microbrewery, the newspaper said. The winners are
expected to be announced today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Madonna's Boyfriend Reportedly Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Madonna's boyfriend was arrested and charged with allegedly
attacking a man outside the pregnant star's London home, a British news agency
reported today. Film director Guy Ritchie, 31, was charged with assault causing
actual bodily harm and was released on bail, said Press Association, the British
news agency. An initial court hearing was scheduled for June 1. Press
Association said Ritchie allegedly attacked a 20-year-old man after returning
with Madonna from a night out at 1 a.m. Wednesday. The news agency said the man
had been waiting outside the couple's home.
</P>
