<HEADLINE> Two Bombs Explode in Estonia Store  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLINN, Estonia (AP) -- Two bombs exploded about six hours apart
today in a department store in the city center, injuring four
people, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The first bomb went off at 4:45 a.m., a few hours after a man
speaking Russian phoned security officials at the Stockmann store,
threatening to set off a bomb in the building if he did not receive
$114,000, the Baltic News Service reported, citing emergency
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was injured in that blast, but a second bomb went off
about six hours later, also in the store's delicatessen on the
first floor, security police spokesman Hannes Kont said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers were in the building when the second bomb went off,
but the injuries were not serious, said Hannu Penttila, deputy
managing director of the Stockmann group.
</P>
<P>
   The man reportedly first called the department store's security
at 3 a.m., telling them there was a bomb in the building. The
Rescue Department's bomb squad searched the store but failed to
find anything suspicious, BNS said. The same man called back,
threatening to set off an explosive device if he did not get the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Penttila declined comment on the phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no idea who is behind these bombs. We have had no
arguments, no problems, since we started our operations in
Estonia,'' Penttila said.
</P>
<P>
   Stockmann is the leading department store in Finland. The store
in the Estonian capital, which opened in 1993, is its
second-largest after the flagship store in Helsinki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
