<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N.: Thousands of Eritreans Flee  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Thousands of people are fleeing Eritrea for
neighboring Sudan, while Eritrean officials report more than half a
million people inside the country have fled invading Ethiopian
troops, the U.N. refugee agency said today.
</P>
<P>
   Sudanese and U.N. officials estimate that between 6,000 and
20,000 Eritreans arrived in Sudan on Thursday, said Ron Redmond,
spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. Among them
are Eritrean soldiers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's official Al-Anbaa newspaper reported that some 50,000
Eritrean refugees crossed the border Thursday and thousands more
are expected to cross in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of fighting, which began May 12, has evolved
from an initial Ethiopian occupation of Eritrean positions on the
western front along the disputed 620-mile frontier to a full-scale
invasion of uncontested Eritrean territory.
</P>
<P>
   The government in the Sudanese border town of Kassala, which
borders Eritrea, has formed several emergency committees to deal
with the situation, Al-Anbaa added, quoting a security source.
</P>
<P>
   The World Food Program appealed for $12 million to help some
330,000 people displaced inside Eritrea by renewed fighting with
Ethiopia. They expect to ask for more money as the number of
displaced people rises, WFP spokeswoman Christiane Berthiaume said.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea says Ethiopia's military campaign has driven more than
500,000 Eritreans from their homes or the makeshift camps where
they were sheltered -- a figure Berthiaume said was ''quite
plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR staff were already positioned along the border before the
war reignited because the agency was preparing to repatriate
160,000 Eritrean refugees, some who have been in Sudan for 30
years. The new Eritrean refugees are being taken to the camps that
house those refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The latest crisis overshadowed efforts to help people suffering
from the prolonged drought on the Horn of Africa region, where WFP
estimates that some 16 million people are at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the urgency right now are those people that have
displaced by the renewal of the fighting,'' Berthiaume said. ''The
emergency is there now. We have to put our priority there. That
doesn't mean that meanwhile we're not thinking of the drought
victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0915 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Kills 125 in West Timor  </HEADLINE>
By HEATHER PATERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Massive floods sweeping through the
lowlands of Indonesian-ruled West Timor have so far claimed at
least 125 lives and are spreading to East Timor, U.N. officials
said today.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the dead are East Timorese women and children who fled
the violence last September in their territory, said Jake Morland,
spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Kupang,
the capital of West Timor. The refugee camps are on the western
side of the heavily guarded border.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not have reports in casualties in East Timor, but it
doesn't mean there are no casualties, as areas are virtually cut
off,'' said Bernard Kerblat, chief of operations of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was impossible to travel farther than 30 miles
by road out of the East Timor's capital of Dili. Several bridges
have collapsed. Mudslides washed away many of the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''These roads are not designed, not built well enough, to handle
the sheer amount of traffic they are being used for,'' said Matt
Everitt of Timor Aid, in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Severe flooding in the southern Betun region has affected
100,000 people in West Timor, with the areas of east and west
Malacca among the worst hit, Kerblat told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is rapidly worsening, he said. People have been
left without reliable water supplies and are running out of food.
There are also fears of an outbreak of cholera.
</P>
<P>
   Monsoon rains had been drenching the region for weeks, but
flooding first began earlier this week, said Jake Morland,
spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Kupang,
the capital of West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   About 250,000 East Timorese fled to West Timor at the height of
violence that engulfed their country last September. At the time,
pro-Indonesian militias went on a rampage following a
U.N.-sponsored vote in which the overwhelming majority of East
Timorese supported breaking away from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the refugees have long since returned, 90,000
people -- mostly with family ties to the militias -- remain in the
squalid camps near the border.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has allowed U.N. aircraft to operate freely for at
least one week in its airspace, and the United Nations intends to
send humanitarian aid to stranded refugees on the western side of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Three U.N. helicopters from East Timor had departed to help
evacuate people to higher ground, Morland said. The helicopters
will have a member of the Indonesian military and an interpreter on
board.
</P>
<P>
   ''Authorities here have welcomed the assistance, they are going
to be working alongside the Indonesian authorities and all the
international organizations here,'' said Morland.
</P>
<P>
   Ten trucks filled with plastic sheeting and other emergency
supplies have left Dili for West Timor, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''So far, 1,435 people have been evacuated from the southern
Belu region, and it's still raining,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government in West Timor is recovering bodies and
working to repair roads to allow emergency assistance to reach
isolated communities, Morland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
