<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubble From Philippine Blast Probed  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- A grenade blast in the violence-wracked
southern Philippines injured two people today, as negotiators hoped
to start formal talks with Muslim guerrillas holding 21 Western and
Asian hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The grenade exploded near a police station in Isabela, the
capital of southern Basilan province, vice Gov. Abdulaziz Balamo
said. Those injured had been inside the police station, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Balamo said he suspected the Abu Sayyaf rebels holding the
hostages were responsible. ''They are having a hard time now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, meanwhile, searched for clues in earlier blasts
in a busy market on the island of Jolo, where the hostages are
held, and in a bakery on the main southern island of Mindanao,
which killed at least eight people Thursday and injured at least
55.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the near-simultaneous timing of Thursday's
explosions led them to suspect they were the work of rebels
fighting for a separate Islamic state in the predominantly
Christian Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is possible that this is a diversionary tactic of the Abu
Sayyaf guerrillas,'' Jolo police chief Muhammad Alamia said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses saw three men throw grenades from the second floor of
the public market, Alamia said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the grenades exploded in a rice stall and the third in a
crowded alley, he said. Seven people were killed and at least 36
others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Another blast at almost the same time in the city of Zamboanga
on Mindanao island killed one woman and wounded at least 19 other
people, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the Zamboanga City police bomb squad, Bayani
Gucela, said the explosive was a ''very powerful homemade bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf snatched their hostages -- including three
Germans, two French, two Finns, two South Africans, a Lebanese,
nine Malaysians and two Filipinos -- on April 23 from Malaysia's
Sipadan Island and took them to Jolo, about an hour away by boat.
</P>
<P>
   Libyan envoy Abdul Rajab Azzarouq said today that formal talks
would start Saturday or Sunday and could take days. All three
negotiating sites on Jolo island proposed by the rebels are fine
with the government, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Formal talks have been delayed by clashes between the rebels and
troops and by frequent changes in the government negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine President Joseph Estrada, meanwhile, was due back in
Manila tonight after cutting short a state visit to China to deal
with the bombings and flooding elsewhere in the Philippines, Press
Secretary Ricardo Puno said.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf also are holding about eight Filipino hostages on
nearby Basilan island, the site of today's grenade attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf rebels are the smaller and more radical of two
separatist groups battling the government in the impoverished
region.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people have been displaced by rising violence
in Mindanao since last month, when the army attacked a 10-mile
stretch of highway held for five years by the larger rebel group,
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front. The MILF pulled out of peace
talks, but indicated Wednesday they are willing to return to the
negotiating table on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   A medical team that visited the hostages at the Abu Sayyaf
hide-out treated ailing German Renate Wallert, 57, whose freedom is
to be the first topic of negotiations. She continues to have high
blood pressure and has severe back pain that makes it difficult for
her to walk, said Nelsa Amin, Jolo's chief government doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said they also treated several rebels with bullet
wounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
