<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wen Ho Lee Case Said Poorly Handled  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A highly classified Justice Department report
concludes that the FBI failed to provide enough resources and
supervision to the Wen Ho Lee spy case and focused so narrowly on
the Los Alamos scientist that it may have missed other national
security breaches, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The findings of the internal review conducted by federal
prosecutor Randy Bellows were presented to Attorney General Janet
Reno in the past week and echo prior congressional findings about
the government's investigation into possible espionage at its
nuclear labs.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Justice Department have battled for months in public
over whether the department's decision to decline an electronic
surveillance warrant for the Lee case hampered agents' work.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellows report, according to officials who have seen it,
concludes that the department should have approved the warrant
requested several times by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   But it adds that the FBI did not provide all the information it
possessed that might help the department make the decision, the
officials told The Associated Press, speaking only on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman John Collingwood declined comment late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials added that the report concludes FBI agents spent
so much time fighting for the surveillance warrant that they missed
the opportunity to more quickly search Lee's work computer, where
they say they belatedly found evidence he downloaded prized nuclear
secrets from secure lab computers.
</P>
<P>
   Bellows concludes the FBI did not need the warrant to conduct
the search because Lee had no reasonable expectation of privacy on
a government computer, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy focus on Lee also kept the bureau from considering
other possible China espionage suspects and other possible leaks of
national security secrets, the report added.
</P>
<P>
   After months of suggestions that Lee would be indicted for China
espionage, the scientist was charged in December with lesser
offenses of removing nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos lab with
no suggestion he gave them to China.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who is awaiting trial, has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press first reported in December that documents
showed the FBI began to doubt more than a year ago that Lee had
given China one of America's most prized nuclear secrets as
originally feared, but did not begin to refocus its investigation
to other possible suspects until late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellows report, the officials said, blames the FBI for not
providing enough leadership and resources to the espionage
investigation in its early stages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 0956 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crews searching Delaware River after fatal nightclub-pier collapse  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN POET
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rescue crews sifted through tangled dock
planks, deck furniture and floating debris today to determine why a
pier holding a new open-air nightclub collapsed into the Delaware
River, plunging dozens of people into the murky water.
</P>
<P>
   Three people died and 37 people were injured in Thursday night's
accident at the nightclub Heat, a waterside bar which opened this
month adjacent to the historic Moshulu ship-turned-restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ''One (patient) told me that they were standing there and
suddenly the floor gave out, the lights went out, and they were in
an ice bath,'' said Dr. Bartholomew Tortella of MCP Hahnemann
University Hospital, who treated victims and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard boats continued to search the water overnight and
closed down the river to all traffic between the Schuylkill River
and the Benjamin Franklin Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not found any additional people,'' U.S. Coast Guard
Capt. Gregory Adams said today.
</P>
<P>
   City police and fire crews called off their part of the search
until today because of the threat of a thunderstorm. They returned
to the scene this morning along with city building inspectors. The
Army Corps of Engineers was also on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Officials did not believe any people were missing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern at this point is really to make sure that when
people come out here tonight to visit some of these other piers
that people are safe,'' Fire Commissioner Harold Hairston said
today.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Street was in South Carolina attending the medical
school graduation of his nephew, spokeswoman Barbara Grant said
today. Street issued a statement this morning calling for the city
to inspect all the piers along the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said city officials were assessing the situation to
determine if Street should immediately return to the city.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 people were on the pier when it dropped into the
30-foot-deep water at about 8:25 p.m. A canvas tent over the pier
also collapsed, blanketing many people who fell into the water and
bringing down the back walls of a dance hall connected to the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Debris from the tent, collapsed building and pier -- which was
still unstable overnight -- hampered rescue efforts along the rest
of the dock area, which is about eight feet above the water level.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was all pancaked in there, the walls fell down on the
floor, then the ceiling, you had all kinds of deck furniture, and
kitchen equipment,'' injured Philadelphia firefighter Joe Whoriskey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whoriskey, who received a tetanus shot and antibiotics for
slashes and cuts, said rescue workers wore wetsuits in the water
but had to feel for victims with their feet since they couldn't see
through the dark, murky water. Seven other rescue workers also
suffered scrapes and bruises from pulling people out of the
debris-strewn shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 37 people injured, all but 9 were treated and released
with minor injures by early today. Identities of the victims were
not immediately released.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were in fair condition at Hahnemann University
Hospital, a spokeswoman said. A woman was in serious condition at
the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania; a woman was in fair
condition and a man in good condition at St. Agnes Hospital. Two
women were in stable condition and a man was in guarded condition
at Thomas Jefferson Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   One man said his sister-in-law, DeAnn White of the city's
Germantown section, was among the dead. He said White was at the
club for an office party for employees of the aquarium in Camden,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was too young,'' Earl Gill said about his sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   A hostess at the restaurant, Eve McCarney, said workers had been
replacing some floorboards on Wednesday but did not do any major
structural repairs. She arrived for work Thursday night after the
accident and was standing with police and fire crews.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard a loud crash, and then all hell broke loose. I went
straight down ... then I was just trying to fight my way up,'' said
bartender Joseph Capaci, 28, of Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   ''It went down so quick, people were just running,'' said Julie
Morgan of Haddonfield, N.J., who was pulled out of the water and
was sitting on the back of a police car with police blankets draped
over her after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The pier is about one-quarter the size of a football field,
behind the restaurant. The section that collapsed was along the
back wall of the ballroom facing the deck, said Stephanie
Franklin-Suber, the mayor's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The pier is owned by Portside Investments Inc. and Heat and the
restaurant are owned by HMS Ventures Inc., said Joe Martz, the
city's managing director. Martz said the owners, not the city, are
responsible for inspections of the pier.
</P>
<P>
   The adjacent restaurant is built into the 394-foot-long Moshulu
tall ship, a turn-of-the-century German cargo ship that has been
converted into an upscale restaurant. The Moshulu, which won a 1939
race among grain carriers for the fastest time from Australia
around Cape Horn to Europe, opened along the Philadelphia
waterfront in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a pier collapsed on the New Jersey side of the
Delaware River, submerging at least five vehicles and causing about
$10 million in damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
