<HEADLINE> Blackhawks May Name Suhonen Coach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Blackhawks will make Toronto
assistant Alpo Suhonen the NHL's first European-born head coach,
several newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Smith, the Blackhawks' manager of hockey operations,
declined to confirm the reports. But the newspapers, including the
Chicago Tribune and Chicago Sun-Times, said sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity told them Suhonen has reached contract terms
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Suhonen, to be introduced Monday as the new coach, replaces
Lorne Molleken, fired earlier this month. Suhonen, of Finland, will
be the Blackhawks' 33rd coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''All that's left is the announcement,'' one source familiar
with the negotiations told the Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Suhonen interviewed with Smith last weekend near
Boston, then met with Hawks president Bill Wirtz and other
management figures in Chicago, both papers reported.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement will be delayed until next week because Suhonen
has personal commitments in Toronto, and Smith will be at his home
in Martha's Vineyard until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This won't be the first time Suhonen has coached in Chicago. He
coached the International Hockey League's Chicago Wolves in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said it makes no difference that Suhonen has never been an
NHL head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even these big-name coaches were head coaches in the NHL for
the first time at some point,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Suhonen has a difficult task. The Blackhawks haven't made the
Stanley Cup playoffs since 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
