<HEADLINE> Precede BUFFALO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Police seized heroin and cocaine valued
at $175,000 and arrested 17 people in a multi-agency raid on a
suspected drug ring that operated out of a smoke shop.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs, targeted for sale in Rochester and Buffalo, were
transported here from New York City and southern Florida, U.S.
Attorney Denise O'Donnell said. In all, 18 people were sought on
distribution conspiracy charges but one was still being hunted.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said heroin use has been on the rise in upstate New
York. ''This really is a substantial narcotics roundup,
particularly one involving heroin,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-month investigation that culminated in Thursday's raids
was carried out by an array of federal, state and local police
agencies, notably the federal Drug Enforcement Agency and the New
York National Guard's counter drug unit.
</P>
<P>
   A stolen handgun was seized, along with $100,000 in cash. Police
said the drug ring operated out of Perla Blanca Smoke Shop and an
adjoining barber shop and auto repair business.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell identified the ring leader as Julio Perez, also known
as ''Pito.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the suspects could get up to 10 years to life in
prison and fines totaling more than $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   On May 3, police infiltrated three cocaine rings in the
Rochester region in a yearlong operation that netted 22 suspected
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The gangs were all based in Rochester, shipping in drugs from
New York City, the Midwest and other sources and distributing them
throughout the city and outlying regions, including Genesee and
Orleans counties in rural western New York, authorities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
