<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Gives $6M To Fire Relatives  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- The families of the six firefighters
killed in a warehouse blaze will each receive $1 million from a
charity fund despite the risk the foundation may be violating tax
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester Telegram and Gazette Charitable Foundation has
received more than $6.4 million from 43,000 donors since the Dec. 3
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of the money came from companies and charitable
groups, which benefited from the fund's tax-deductible status. As a
nonprofit corporation, however, the foundation is bound by Internal
Revenue Service rules in disbursing the money to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The law is designed to ensure that such organizations, in
exchange for favorable tax treatment, help a large segment of the
community and not just a small, specific group.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were in a Catch-22,'' said Harry Whitin, a foundation
trustee and editor of the Telegram and Gazette newspaper. ''We
needed the tax deductibility in order to attract the donations, yet
the tax deductibility became a restriction on the eventual
disbursement of the funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitin said the IRS could sanction the newspaper if it has
violated any rules.
</P>
<P>
   A committee that includes members of the firefighter's families
will decide how to spend the remaining money, which continues to
flow into the fund, Whitin said.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters died after two became lost in a burning
warehouse while searching for homeless people. Four more
firefighters went in to find them, and they all perished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1014 </TRAILER>
