<HEADLINE> U.S. Rev. Meets N. Korean Officials  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The Rev. Franklin Graham, a son of
U.S. evangelist Billy Graham, met Friday with North Korean
officials, the North's media said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham had a warm talk with Kim Yong Dae, a vice parliamentary
speaker, said the North's foreign news outlet, KCNA.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Kye Gwan, a vice foreign minister who is North Korea's chief
negotiator with the United States on nuclear and other issues, sat
in at the meeting at Mansudae Assembly Hall in the capital of
Pyongyang, KCNA said.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Graham recalled the ''intimate ties'' that
existed between his father and the late North Korean President Kim
Il Sung and pledged efforts to promote ties between the United
States and North Korea, KCNA said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham arrived Monday. The North's media gave no further
details, including the length and purpose of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's father visited North Korea several times in the late
1980s and early 1990s. The senior Graham met the late North Korean
leader during his 1994 visit.
</P>
