<HEADLINE> Palestinians Turn Down Israel Offer  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- In its largest offer so far, Israel has
proposed that the Palestinians take control of 90 percent of the
West Bank, a senior Palestinian official said before peace talks
resumed today. He said the offer was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke late Thursday on condition of anonymity,
said the offer was made -- and turned down -- during last week's
round of talks in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank today, hundreds of Palestinians hurled stones
at Israeli troops who fired tear gas and rubber-coated steel
pellets in several clashes. In one march, demonstrators burned an
effigy of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   At least 19 demonstrators were hurt by rubber bullets, including
one who was in serious condition with a head injury.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian police pushed back the demonstrators in most areas
to keep down the friction, an apparent response to Barak's warning
today that he would not hand over three West Bank villages next to
Jerusalem, as promised, if there was a flare-up. Newspaper reports
said the villages could be handed to the Palestinians as early as
Sunday if there were no major disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian activists have said today and Saturday would be
''days of rage'' over Israel's refusal to release more Palestinian
security prisoners at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, marches pressing for freedom for the 1,650
Palestinian security prisoners escalated into Israeli-Palestinian
gun battles that killed three Palestinians in the worst violence in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden, meanwhile, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
resumed talks today on the outlines of a peace treaty. A U.S.
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said some progress
has been made in previous talks in Sweden, led by Israeli Public
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and Palestinian Parliament Speaker
Ahmed Qureia.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's round, Israel offered to give up 90 percent of
the West Bank but did not present a map or say whether the land
would be handed over in one or several stages, the Palestinian
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Israel offered to withdraw from 80 percent
of the West Bank, with 66 percent to be handed over with the
signing of a peace agreement and 14 percent after a test period of
several years. Under the Israeli proposal, the Palestinian entity
would consist of several blocs linked by roads, tunnels and
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian official said the most recent Israeli offer
provided for greater contiguity of Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office refused comment today.
</P>
<P>
   After Muslim noon prayers today, groups of several hundred
marchers each walked from West Bank towns toward nearby Israeli
army positions, hurling stones at the troops. In most locations,
Palestinian police tried to push back the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank town of Qalqiliya, Palestinian security men
wielding clubs prevented marchers from reaching the nearest Israeli
position. In the town of Ramallah, demonstrators burned a Barak
effigy and a U.S. flag, then headed to a traffic circle on the
outskirts of town that was the scene of a four-hour gun battle on
Monday. About 200 protesters threw stones at soldiers who fired
rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Israel would link its handover of three villages near
Jerusalem -- Abu Dis, Izzarieh and Sawahra a-Sharkieh -- to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's ability to quell violent
protests this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (the handover) will be implemented only when we will see
that the needed steps were taken by the Palestinians to correct
what happened this Monday,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's parliament narrowly approved the transfer of the
villages earlier this week, despite objections by the hawkish
opposition and several members of Barak's coalition. Hard-liners
said the withdrawal will weaken Israel's hold over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said in an interview published today in the Israeli daily
Haaretz that he made a mistake in refusing to hand over the three
villages earlier. ''I could have handled it better if I'd
transferred them earlier,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
