<HEADLINE> Va. Gov. Attacks Museum Exhibit  </HEADLINE>
By BOB LEWIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Virginia's governor says a photographer's
sexually graphic slide show had no place in a state-owned art
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Gilmore objected to the presentation by Sally Mann in a
letter this week to officials at the Virginia Museum of Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of her 90-minute lecture May 10, Mann showed
pictures that included depictions of oral sex, genitalia and young
girls urinating, according to witness accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Richard Woodward, the museum's interim
director, Gilmore said he was ''shocked and dismayed that this type
of exhibit occurred on state owned property.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration learned of the presentation after verifying
the claims of someone who had attended it and anonymously wrote to
Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by e-mail Thursday if any museum patrons complained, Mann,
who lives in Lexington, responded: ''Never has anyone objected. To
the contrary, the images have been lauded.'' She declined to speak
by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to Gilmore, Woodward said he had given
copies of the governor's letter to the museum's board of trustees
and promised new guidelines for reviewing exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Mann's 1992 book, ''Immediate Family,'' depicted her children --
nude in some pictures -- and prompted protests at bookstores that
carried it.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani condemned an
exhibition that included a painting of a black Virgin Mary adorned
with elephant dung at the Brooklyn Museum of Art. He threatened to
freeze $7 million in public funding for the museum. The issue went
to court and the two sides reached a settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
