<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK, US Slash Breast Cancer Deaths  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Improved treatments in the last 10 years have
pushed breast cancer death rates down by about 25 percent in the
United States and Britain among young and middle-aged women,
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Already 60,000 deaths have been avoided in the two countries
because of the treatments, chemotherapy and tamoxifen, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit goes to the drug tamoxifen, taken by about 1
million women worldwide, said Sir Richard Peto, a professor of
epidemiology at Oxford University who headed the study, published
this week in The Lancet medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first time that improvements in the treatment of
any type of cancer have ever produced such a rapid fall in national
death rates,'' according to Peto, who said he examined the largest
collection of existing evidence on cancer therapy so far assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ''They really are remarkable trends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While ''a lot of things contribute, I think the key one is
tamoxifen,'' Peto said, adding that it's much too sudden a drop to
be due to changes in the causes of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and the United States were studied mostly because they
had the most current, detailed statistical information and because
they were among the first to use tamoxifen, Peto said.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of other Western countries would show they already
are starting to see a similar trend, said Dr. Kent Osborne,
director of the breast center at Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston, who was not connected with the study.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne agreed with Peto that breast cancer screening, which
only started to become widespread in the 1980s, has not been around
long enough to cause the death rates to drop.
</P>
<P>
   Peto said death rates will continue to decline once the benefits
of screening emerge and other countries begin to more widely use
tamoxifen.
</P>
<P>
   His analysis showed that breast cancer deaths will be down 24
percent in Britain overall, compared with the late 1980s, before
chemotherapy and tamoxifen became widely available. It indicated
that the disease would result in 13,000 deaths this year instead of
17,000.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that among British middle-aged women, who have
benefited from tamoxifen, deaths will be down by a slightly greater
figure, but details of actual numbers were not available.
</P>
<P>
   The United States will experience a 20 percent drop in the
breast cancer death rate overall, with about 40,000 women dying of
the disease this year, Peto said. If treatment methods were at
their pre-1989 stage, 50,000 would die this year, he said. But
among young and middle-aged women, deaths will be down 25 percent
this year -- 21,000 will die instead of 28,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is slightly ahead, probably because tamoxifen was
invented there and used there first, Peto said.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer is particularly problematic because remnants may
remain after a tumor has been cut out and can cause a recurrence of
cancer years later.
</P>
<P>
   There are three main treatments after surgery. Radiotherapy
targets the remnants of cancer lurking in or near the breast.
Chemotherapy is a cocktail of cell-killing drugs, and tamoxifen and
other hormonal drugs block hormones from nurturing the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen alone has been found to head off one in six
recurrences and cut the risk of relapse by more than one-third. It
also halves the risk of a new cancer occurring in the other breast,
according to Peto's analysis, which examined the largest-ever
collection of existing evidence on cancer therapy.
</P>
<P>
   While tamoxifen fights cancer, it also can cause womb cancer and
blood clots in the lungs. But using the drug for five years does 30
times more good than harm, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   For every 1,000 women who take it, tamoxifen leads to 80 fewer
deaths from breast cancer, two more deaths from womb cancer and one
more death from blood clots in the lungs, it found.
</P>
<P>
   Chemotherapy seems to work as well as tamoxifen in young women,
but only about a third as well as tamoxifen in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   When the two are used together, the chances of survival are even
better.
</P>
<P>
   Radiotherapy, the oldest treatment, prevents about two-thirds of
recurrences, but has yielded only a 1 percent decrease in the
overall death rates. While it works well in clearing up rogue bits
of cancer in the breast, it also increases the risk of heart
attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, radiotherapy has reduced the death rate from breast
cancer by 5 percent since the late 1980s, but has increased the
rate of death from other causes by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This radiotherapy effect is certainly not going to explain the
trend,'' said Jack Cuzick, a professor of mathematics, statistics
and epidemiology at the Imperial Cancer Research Fund in London,
which funded the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Death rates from lung cancer have plummeted, but that has mainly
been due to people quitting smoking. Cervical cancer rates have
also fallen, but mostly because of early detection.
</P>
<P>
   While improved treatment has led to better survival in rare
cancers such as Hodgkins disease and childhood leukemia, none of
the other major cancers have benefited as much as breast cancer,
Peto said.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the breast cancer deaths prevented will be
among women aged between 20 and 69, the research found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver ally on coup attempt: I believe this is over  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A powerful ally of state Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver said today that he believed the attempted coup
against the speaker by former Assembly Majority Leader Michael
Bragman had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ''From my end, I believe this is over,'' Assemblyman Roberto
Ramirez, who is also the Bronx Democratic chairman, told Albany's
WROW-AM radio this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a top aide to Silver said one of Bragman's biggest
supporters, Queens Democratic Chairman Thomas Manton, a former
congressman, had reached out this morning to Silver in an attempt
to make peace with the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Manton nor Silver could be reached immediately for
comment on that.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman did not immediately return telephone messages left for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan Democrat Silver retaliated Thursday against supporters
of the ongoing coup attempt by Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, the leader of the Assembly majority's more conservative
upstate wing, called the moves by his fellow Democrat
''intolerable'' and accused Silver of having a leadership style
that was ''secretive and aloof.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch said her boss was solidly in
control.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, supporters of the Manhattan Democrat were working
the telephones furiously behind the scenes in an attempt to turn
back the Bragman challenge.
</P>
<P>
   That effort appeared to pay off, at least to some extent, when
Ramirez announced Thursday night that he was backing Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am absolutely, unequivocally, 100 percent behind Speaker
Sheldon Silver,'' Ramirez said, adding that the 10-member Bronx
Democratic delegation to the Assembly appeared to be in agreement
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman went public with his coup attempt on Wednesday, saying
he planned to formally make his move Monday when the Assembly
reconvenes. Silver immediately stripped Bragman of the majority
leader's title.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Silver stripped two veteran members of the Assembly
of their committee chairmanships for supporting Bragman. In losing
their chairmanships, Martin Luster of Ithaca and Ronald Tocci of
Westchester County also lost the $12,500 stipends that go with the
posts.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman called it an attempt to intimidate Assembly members that
would backfire and bring him even more support. The Syracuse-area
Democrat said it was also a sign Silver was ''absolutely
panic-stricken.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sitting here this morning with 50 rock-solid (Democratic)
votes,'' he added. That would give the majority leader the
advantage within the 98-member Democratic majority in the
150-member house that will decide on Bragman's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, neither Bragman nor Silver would release lists of
their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman did charge that in the current leadership battle Silver
''has surrounded himself with paid lobbyists and other
non-legislators who are seeking to influence members on how to vote
on this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman's charge came as several powerful New York labor union
leaders, including state AFL-CIO President Denis Hughes, issued a
statement saying ''a divisive battle for the speakership at this
time is counterproductive.'' The statement did not specifically
endorse Silver.
</P>
<P>
   But just minutes later, a revised statement was issued by the
same labor leaders in which the claim that a leadership battle
would be counterproductive was removed. A spokesman for Hughes said
the first statement had been issued in error. The second statement
took no position on the wisdom of having a leadership fight.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman indicated he was being supported in his effort by state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as I am concerned, Carl and I are partners,'' Bragman
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said he was not helping either Silver or Bragman and that
when Assembly members called asking for advice, ''I'm telling them
that they've got to make a decision about what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George Pataki offered a similarly neutral stance
when current state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno moved
successfully to oust Ralph Marino as the GOP leader of the Senate
over the Thanksgiving Day weekend in 1994. At the time, the Pataki
statement was viewed by many Republicans as the go-ahead for GOP
senators to join the revolt against Marino.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the current situation was different. ''I'm not the
governor. I don't have that kind of influence ... I'm not involved.
It doesn't help me to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall, who is preparing for a run for governor in 2002, is the
only black ever elected to statewide office in New York and has
great sway with the Assembly's black lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the battle between Silver and Bragman stems at least in
part from the former majority leader's backing of McCall's
gubernatorial effort over federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo's
possible run for the job his father, Mario Cuomo, lost to Pataki in
1994. Silver has been widely seen as a Cuomo supporter.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation Thursday that should it be evident by
Monday that Silver doesn't have the votes to remain as speaker,
some other Assembly Democrat from New York City may step forward to
challenge Bragman for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a Democratic speaker of the Assembly from
outside New York City in more than 80 years. Should Bragman get the
job it would mean the city wouldn't have one of its own in the room
when Pataki, Bruno and the Assembly speaker negotiate budget deals
and other major issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 1038 </TRAILER>
