<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frost Seeks Funds, Mulls China Vote  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, the third-ranking
Democrat in the House, is pressing the Clinton administration to
pay for modernizing a defense plant in his district as he ponders
how to vote on a controversial China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman, Tom Eisenhauer, said there was ''no quid pro quo
here'' and the request was one of several factors that Frost is
considering as he makes up his mind on the China vote.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhauer declined to provide an estimate for the cost of the
modernization, and said Frost fears the plant, which provides 5,000
jobs, may be closed if the work isn't done.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the issue has been reviewed at strategy sessions on the China bill.
Frost has discussed the issue with President Clinton, and met in
his Capitol Hill office on Tuesday with Rudy de Leon, the
second-ranking official at the Pentagon, they added.
</P>
<P>
   Frost's request concerns a Northrop Grumman Corp. defense plant
in Grand Prairie, Texas that once was a Navy facility.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the jobs at the facility are union, and it is the
largest single employer in Frost's congressional district,
according to Eisenhauer.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plant's work, he said, is on military aircraft,
including the C-17 and B-2, while part of it is production of
civilian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Serving his 11th term in the House, Frost is chairman of the
Democratic Caucus, the third-ranking post in the party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   He also is one of a dwindling group of Democrats counted as
uncommitted on the China trade measure, which is scheduled for a
vote in the House next week.
</P>
<P>
   As a former chairman of the House Democratic Campaign Committee,
Frost has ties to organized labor, which opposes the China measure.
As a veteran lawmaker from Texas, he often has voted for trade
bills in the past, including the North American Free Trade
Agreement in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
