<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cannes Films Cover Varied Topics  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France (AP) -- Twenty-three films are competing at Cannes
for the ultimate prize, the Palme d'Or, to be awarded Sunday. But
there are countless others showing in screening rooms large and
small all over this Riviera festival.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many to be glimpsed this week were a loving tribute to
Gregory Peck by a top documentary maker, and Kenneth Branagh's
lighthearted take on Shakespeare's ''Love's Labor's Lost,'' to the
tunes of Gershwin and Cole Porter.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''A Conversation With Gregory Peck''
</P>
<P>
   It's rare, to say the least, for the aggressive pack of
photographers at Cannes to quiet down in respect for a celebrity.
Shouting out the names of stars is, after all, how they do their
job. But there wasn't a sound to be heard but the clicking of
shutters when Gregory Peck had his photo call.
</P>
<P>
   It was proof that despite the hot young stars taking bows here,
a true movie legend like Peck always gets the most respect.
</P>
<P>
   The audience erupted in cheers when the 84-year-old actor
entered a screening of ''A Conversation With Gregory Peck,'' a
documentary by Barbara Kopple.
</P>
<P>
   Kopple won Oscars for both ''Harlan County USA'' and ''American
Dream.'' Then she turned her lens on Woody Allen for ''Wild Man
Blues,'' a close-up portrayal of Allen's European tour with his
jazz band.
</P>
<P>
   Her new film provides a glimpse into Peck's daily life, which he
now fills by traveling the country in a one-man show about his
career.
</P>
<P>
   The film was produced with Peck's daughter, Cecilia, and doesn't
pretend to be critical. But for Peck fans, it's a welcome look at a
star whose old movie clips, liberally displayed here, can still
evoke sighs.
</P>
<P>
   Included are scenes with Audrey Hepburn in 1953's ''Roman
Holiday,'' where she plays a princess on a goodwill tour of Europe,
and he the newspaperman in search of a scoop who falls for her
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Peck recalls how he insisted the newly discovered Hepburn
receive above-the-title billing -- telling producers the film would
make Hepburn a big star and he would look pretty silly with only
his name at the top.
</P>
<P>
   In the documentary, Peck tells the story of how he met his wife,
Veronique, a French reporter assigned to interview him. There's
also an amusing dinner scene with French President Jacques Chirac
in Paris -- testament to the kind of access Kopple had -- in which
the French leader tells Peck that if he'd met Veronique first,
''you wouldn't have had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Peck retorts: ''You're modest, aren't you. I like that
in a president.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Love's Labor's Lost''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Branagh obviously loves Shakespeare, but it might be
less known that he loves singing and dancing, Cole Porter,
Gershwin, and Fred and Ginger. He's decided to put them all
together in a musical version of ''Love's Labor's Lost,'' one of
Shakespeare's lesser-known comedies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love musicals,'' he says. ''They're silly, simple, escapist.
The boy gets the girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Branagh's cast list, one might be taken aback by the
thought of Alicia Silverstone reciting the bard's words in the role
of a French princess. But Branagh says he wasn't looking for actors
who sounded Shakespearean.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's genuine, natural and light,'' he says of Silverstone.
''And I defy people to tell me she doesn't know what she's
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Branagh said in an interview, he has all his actors
read their lines in rehearsal, then paraphrase them in their own
words, to make sure they understand.
</P>
<P>
   The film might disappoint purists but should please musical
comedy fans, with numbers like ''I Get a Kick Out of You,'' ''Cheek
to Cheek,'' ''They Can't Take That Away From Me,'' and ''There's No
Business Like Show Business.''
</P>
<P>
   The dancing, particularly, is joyful, and it's done not by
professional dancers but by the actors themselves (the singing,
too). Adrian Lester lets loose his dancing talent, especially in a
routine that has him climbing, Astaire-like, up and over chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh also stars, and Nathan Lane is a very funny vaudevillian
clown.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers may have trouble sorting out the winding plot. But
the energetic musical numbers and the spirit of silliness should go
a long way toward making up for that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1420 </TRAILER>
