<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 160; Nasdaq Off 143  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices fell broadly today, with investors still
nervous about the impact that higher interest rates will have on
corporate earnings and stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 159.69 at 10,617.59.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 31.69 at 1,405.52, and the Nasdaq composite
index was off 143.19 at 3,395.52.
</P>
<P>
   As they've done for most of this week, investors refused to buy
into a market facing higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve raised rates for the sixth time since June
on Tuesday, pushing the federal funds rate -- the interest that
banks charge each other for overnight loans -- to 6.5 percent, the
highest level in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed indicated that inflation remains a risk, which raised
expectations among investors that the central bank was not yet
done.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits by increasing the cost of borrowing
money.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of fear out there,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.
Louis. ''People are concerned and worried about how high interest
rates will go ... and this market will be volatile until there is
evidence on the table that the Fed will not derail the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be scouring new economic data in the coming weeks
to see if the Fed's actions are slowing the economy. The first
piece comes next Thursday, when the Commerce Department issues its
preliminary report on first-quarter gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a news vacuum right now and there are no earnings
stories to talk about for months, so there is nothing to fuel the
market,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are vulnerable to interest rate
fluctuations, fell today. Merrill Lynch dropped 6} to 102 5/16,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter fell 5 1/16 to 69| and Lehman Brothers
lost 4 1/16 to 81|.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also came under some selling pressure today.
Cisco fell 2] to 53, Intel lost 5\ to 118 11/16 and Apple Computer
dropped 5 1/16 to 95 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks were mostly higher today, benefiting from the
escalating cost of crude oil. Crude prices surged above $30 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, and were
hovering slightly below that level in trading today.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron rose 2| to 93{ and Exxon Mobil rose 11/32 to 81 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 575.59 million
shares, up from 540.34 million shares on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively higher volume was tied to today's double-witching
expiration of stock and index options. Volume has been lower than
normal for about two weeks as many investors drop out of the market
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 12.59 at 478.36.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
