<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs School of Americas Change  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers are giving a new life to a
controversial Army school that trains Latin Americans in combat
techniques, giving the facility a new name rather than closing its
doors.
</P>
<P>
   On a 214-204 vote during consideration of a defense bill, the
House rejected a measure to shut down the School of the Americas at
Fort Benning, Ga., for at least 10 months while alleged human
rights violations are investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the training facility will stay open. But the Defense
Department instead of the Army will oversee it if the Senate takes
the same route. In addition, a board of academics and members of
Congress would monitor the conduct of the 54-year-old school, which
would be renamed the Defense Institute for Hemispheric Security
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Joe Moakley of Massachusetts, the primary
sponsor of the measure rejected Thursday by the House, said the
reforms ''amount to little more than a new coat of paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley contends some of the school's graduates, which include
former Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega and El Salvador assassin
Roberto D'Abuisson, developed terrorist techniques during training
at Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the school said it shouldn't be judged by its bad
apples.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Unabomber went to Harvard, and we're not talking about
closing down Harvard because he committed those atrocities,'' said
Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a protest group called SOA Watch has found new
reasons to rally against the facility. Four years ago, the Pentagon
acknowledged that training manuals used at the school recommended
bribery, blackmail, threats and torture against insurgents. The
manuals were destroyed in 1991 after an internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we take joy in this partial victory, we will continue to
move ahead in the struggle to close down this new-named school,''
said Roy Bourgeois, a founder and co-director of the protest group.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois' group almost got its wish last year when the House
narrowly approved a bill to cut off the school's funding. But that
measure lost out in a conference committee with senators, and the
funds stayed intact.
</P>
<P>
   The school graduates about 1,000 students each year -- about
one-tenth of the Latin American soldiers trained in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to improve its image, the School of the Americas
now offers courses in civil rights. Similar courses would be
mandated under the proposed congressional reforms, which have
President Clinton's support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1430 </TRAILER>
