<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Puts Land in Reserve Program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government on Friday accepted nearly 2.5
million acres of land into the Conservation Reserve Program, which
pays farmers to take environmentally sensitive land out of
production for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Montana had 263,629 acres approved, the largest amount of any
state. Texas was next with 197,297 acres, followed by Washington
with 195,621, North Dakota with 181,688, Iowa with 178,997 and
Kansas with 154,422.
</P>
<P>
   About 31.4 million acres are currently enrolled in the program,
including 420,000 on which CRP contracts are expiring Sept. 30. The
2.46 million acres accepted by the Agriculture Department Friday
will push the program's total enrollment to 33.5 million acres on
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum enrollment for the program under law is 36.4 million
acres.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an investment in protecting our environment that will
last for years,'' said Vice President Al Gore. ''The land enrolled
will result in cleaner water and create vitally needed habitats for
wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Land put in the program must be planted with trees, grass and
other cover. In exchange, farmers are guaranteed payments for 10 to
15 years. The average annual payment for the acreage accepted in
the new enrollment will be $52.76 per acre, slightly above the
historic average of $50.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers offered 3.5 million acres in the latest sign-up period.
The offers are evaluated according to the cost and environmental
benefits of not farming the land.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA: http://www.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
