<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supply Clerk Made Parachute Jump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) -- An apparent clerical error sent a supply
clerk with the 82nd Airborne Division out the door of an airplane
on his first parachute jump without any formal training.
</P>
<P>
   Army Spc. Jeff Lewis, who landed unhurt, said he was just doing
what a good soldier is supposed to do -- following orders.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 23, made the jump Feb. 22 at Fort Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Army said I was airborne-qualified,'' Lewis said Thursday.
''I wasn't going to question it. I had a job to do, and I had to
believe in what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. James Marshall, an 82nd spokesman, said officials will try
to make sure it doesn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was promoted from private first class to specialist a few
weeks after his jump. He graduated from Airborne School on May 5
and will make his first ''official'' jump with the 82nd Airborne in
June.
</P>
<P>
   All 15,000 soldiers in the 82nd Airborne must undergo parachute
training at the three-week Airborne School at Fort Benning, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   But when Lewis, a reservist who enlisted for active duty, signed
in at Fort Bragg in December, his records showed he was already
jump-qualified.
</P>
<P>
   So with freshly sewn airborne wings on his chest and an 82nd
patch on his shoulder, Lewis decided to ''go with the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his jump, Lewis attended a one-day refresher class for
airborne-qualified soldiers who have not jumped in at least six
months. But the class is not meant as a crash course in how to
parachute.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis stepped out of the aircraft with the wrong foot, and his
equipment got twisted up. But he remembered what the jumpmasters
had said at the refresher class and kicked his feet, getting the
canopy open.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Lewis got nervous and told his platoon
sergeant what he had done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
