<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels: UN Can Investigate in Congo  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Congolese rebels on Friday rejected a
human rights report accusing them of raping and killing civilians
and burying women alive, instead blaming such outrages on mobs that
suspected the women of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Human Rights Watch said in a report Tuesday
that the rebels and allied Rwandan army units opposed to Congolese
President Laurent Kabila were punishing civilians for allegedly
supporting their enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the rights group said, the rebels and their Rwandan
army allies attacked civilians on Feb. 5 in the village of Kilambo,
tying up the men and raping their wives in front of them, then
killing 30 of them.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident, the rebels buried several women alive in
South Kivu province last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel spokesman Kin-Kiey Mulumba denied the allegations and said
outsiders were free to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're ready to secure the area for an investigation
immediately,'' he said. ''If the responsibility of our soldiers is
established, we will punish them accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulumba said the women who were buried alive were killed by an
angry mob after they were suspected of witchcraft. Such incidents
are not uncommon in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   He said the rebels were not present in the remote village at the
time of the killings and arrived on the scene later.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda has already rejected the report.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Garreton, a Chilean lawyer who is the U.N. human rights
investigator for Congo and who has in the past accused both sides
of killings and torture, did not immediately comment on the rebels'
invitation to investigate the latest allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan Hutu militiamen, who fled Rwanda in fear of reprisals
for the 1994 genocide of more than 500,000 people there, are
accused of most of the attacks against civilians, including
imprisonment of Congolese women as sex slaves, the Human Rights
Watch report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
