<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Agency Expands GM Probe  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal safety agency has expanded its
investigation of some General Motors Corp. cars with reported
steering problems.
</P>
<P>
   GM recalled several models three years ago because the bolts
that hold the engine cradle in place were corroding, which could
separate the steering system. It limited the recall to 14 states
with weather conditions that would cause corrosion, but complaints
have continued to come in from other states.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said Friday
that further investigation is needed to determine if the recall was
adequate. The agency said that there have been 200 complaints about
the problem, including reports of 32 crashes and 11 injuries.
</P>
<P>
   GM spokesman Greg Martin said the automaker is cooperating with
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is certainly a routine follow-up on the part of NHTSA,''
Martin said. ''We are confident that we have a well-defined vehicle
population as included in the initial recall.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will examine 1989 to 1991 model years of the
Chevrolet Lumina, Lumina APV and Monte Carlo, the Buick Regal, the
Oldsmobile Cutlass and Silhouette, the Pontiac Grand Prix and Trans
Sport. There are about 677,000 of the cars on the road.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA also announced Friday that it has upgraded its
investigation of nearly 1.3 million Ford Explorers from model years
1991 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 106 complaints that the spare tire has dropped
from under the vehicle onto the road because the cable failed to
hold it in place. NHTSA said one accident has been reported and in
six other cases, the wheel dropped off and damaged vehicles
following the Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA opens any safety investigation with a preliminary inquiry
in which the government and manufacturer exchange paperwork,
including any complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation then can be upgraded to an engineering
analysis, as in the case of the Explorer and GM cars, during which
engineers study parts to see if they are defective. An
investigation eventually can lead to a recall.
</P>
<P>
   Recalls included in the monthly report issued Friday were:
</P>
<P>
   --1999-2000 Ford Explorer and Mercury Mountaineer; wipers can
fail and affect visibility, increasing the risk of a crash. There
are 208,903 of the vehicles on the road. The company has notified
vehicle owners and dealers will fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   --1997-2000 Chevrolet Corvettes; the seat belt can get jammed.
There are 71,569 of the cars on the road. Affected owners have been
notified and dealers will make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   --1996-1997 Chevrolet Express and GMC Savana; fuel may leak and
could start a fire. There are 109,239 of the vans on the road. GM
has not yet decided on a remedy, NHTSA said.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA also announced that it has opened the following
investigations:
</P>
<P>
   --1995-1996 GM C/K Trucks, Sierra, Suburban, Yukon and Tahoe; 10
complaints of wires breaking in the headlight high-low control
circuit, which can make the headlights fail. There are about 1.7
million of the vehicles on the road.
</P>
<P>
   --1996-2000 Audi A4; 32 reports of malfunctioning brakes in wet
conditions, including one crash. There are an estimated 105,000 of
the vehicles on the road.
</P>
<P>
   --2000 Jeep Wrangler; one complaint that the drivers side air bag
is not properly attached to the steering wheel, which could mean it
won't deploy in a crash. It is unknown how many of the vehicles are
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Highway Traffic Safety Administration site:
http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
