<DOCNO> APW20000519.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, his political ambitions
derailed by prostate cancer and a nasty split with his wife, today
abandoned his Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to think the core of me was in politics. It isn't,''
Giuliani told a City Hall news conference, folding his campaign
before ever officially announcing its start. The stunning decision
ended three weeks of intense speculation over his viability as a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've decided that what I should do is to put my health
first,'' he said. ''... This is not the right time for me to run
for office.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank God that it gives me really another 18 months to be
the mayor of New York City,'' he said. In those 18 months, an
unusually reflective Giuliani said, he hoped to heal any divisions
created during his six years in City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about whether the 55-year-old mayor would quit the
Senate race almost instantly followed his April 27 cancer
disclosure. Giuliani had said that his candidacy would be
contingent on his choice of treatment options -- a decision that he
still has not made.
</P>
<P>
   But that candidacy took another hit last week with his
announcement that he was discussing a legal separation from his
wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover. Hanover retorted with her own
bombshell, publicly suggesting he had an affair with a former
staffer. At the same time, the mayor was flaunting a relationship
with a third woman, Judith Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's announcement to a packed City Hall news conference
made no mention of either his wife or Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said his decision followed a sleepless night, but
expressed hope that his pulling out was ''all for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know that I'd be able to campaign the way I should,''
said Giuliani, citing his upcoming cancer treatment. ''I don't know
that in August or September that I'd be able to continue the way I
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he broke the news to Republican leaders by phone,
and pledged his support to likely GOP nominee Rick Lazio, a Long
Island congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, long a political animal, told reporters that he had a
revelation that spurred his announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I woke up this morning and said, 'There are more important
things in life,''' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, campaigning in Brooklyn, offered no comment when made
aware of reports that the mayor was backing out. ''I have no
control or say over what happens on the other side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The married mayor, shortly after the cancer announcement, went
public with confirmation that he was seeing his ''very, very good
friend'' Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP mayor said later that he and Hanover were discussing a
formal separation, although he apparently went public with the news
before telling his wife. Hanover's spokeswoman said today that she
had hired a matrimonial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But while the double-barreled revelations about Giuliani's
health and his marriage made for huge headlines, polls taken after
the mayor's announcements showed he was still running about even
with the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders must now scramble to find a replacement
candidate in the 10 days before their May 30 convention in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders, including Gov. George Pataki, had passed the
word that their favored replacement candidate to challenge the
first lady was U.S. Rep. Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said for several days that he would make no statement
about his intentions until Giuliani had made his decision. The
congressman, who has about $3.5 million in his campaign bank
account, had been preparing to run for the Senate until August when
Pataki endorsed the mayor's bid and asked Lazio to suspend his
effort. Lazio did so.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King has said he is interested, but he alienated
party leadership with his support of Sen. John McCain in the
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Giuliani told an hour-long town hall meeting
broadcast nationally that he regretted some of his most
controversial actions of the past year. He specifically
acknowledged a mistake in his handling of the slaying of Patrick
Dorismond, an unarmed black man killed in a recent scuffle with
undercover police.
</P>
<P>
   ''I should have also conveyed the human feeling that I had, the
compassion, the loss of the mother,'' Giuliani said. ''I think if I
could do it over again, I would have tried to balance it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Mitchell whether he has become more compassionate
because of his illness, Giuliani said ''something has to happen to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   In making a decision on treatment, Giuliani said he had
anticipated a different process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kind of approached it as if this was a big case, or a budget
decision,'' the former prosecutor said. But this decision he said,
''involves thinking about your life, mortality, the quality of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's three options for treatment are surgery, external
beam radiation and radioactive seed implantation. The 15-year
survival rate is 95 percent for surgery and 60 to 70 percent for
the two less invasive options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 1622 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Joins Wife at Hospital  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair joined his pregnant
wife, Cherie, at a London hospital Friday, prompting speculation
that she was about to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Blair, 45, who is expecting their fourth child, was
admitted to Chelsea and Westminster Hospital in the afternoon. In
the evening, she was joined by the prime minister who raced past
crowds of waiting reporters and television crews in a
chauffeur-driven car.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Blair's due date is May 24. She was admitted to the same
hospital for tests on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Blairs have not said whether the child is a boy or a girl,
nor have they dropped any hints about names -- though Mrs. Blair has
said she would like to have a girl, which would balance the family
at two boys and two girls.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Blair's Downing Street office refused to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1625 </TRAILER>
