<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cash Hard To Find in Paris  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN GECKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Bewildered tourists and fed up French people
scoured Paris for ATM machines with cash on Friday, and the French
train and subway systems began accepting checks and credit cards
for fares as little as 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   On the 11th day of a strike by armored truck guards, the search
for cash required wits and wile.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are giving me checks for their morning newspaper. We
can't refuse, we'll lose the sale,'' said Jean-Louis Grimal, a
newsstand owner who said business was down 20 percent since the
strike began, causing people to think twice before sparing small
change.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by a string of holdups that have left 11 security guards
dead in the past five years, the armored truck guards are demanding
hazardous-duty pay of $208 a month and other benefits for what they
insist is a high-risk job.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for the guards and their employers were to
return to the negotiating table Saturday with an arbitrator
appointed by the government. Negotiations broke off Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In cities around France, armored truck guards held protests
Friday. ''Striking for a Salary of Fear'' read a banner unfurled by
several hundred guards protesting in Paris. In suburban Nanterre,
guards held a silent march in memory of a colleague who died last
week after an armed attack.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, people around the capital, faced with empty automatic
teller machines, were scrambling for money ahead of the weekend,
when most banks are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Many merchants were demanding exact change as their own supplies
of bank notes ran low, and most lowered their limits for payment by
check and credit card.
</P>
<P>
   A manager at the Monoprix supermarket chain said the majority of
customers were abandoning cash for credit, making it likely that
the chain's payment to credit card companies would set a record
this month, since stores pay a surcharge for each purchase put on
credit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to cost us a lot more money this month,'' said the
manager, Marilyn Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on and ATM machines across the city turned up
empty, some people were panicking.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight-year-old Alice Barrey rushed into a supermarket
near her jewelry shop on the Champs Elysees after a fruitless
search for an automatic teller machine with cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please tell me you take credit cards,'' she said. ''I have
people coming to dinner tonight and have no money in my wallet.''
She needed onions and butter.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force Maj. Karen Groth, on a three-day holiday from her
base in Ramstein, Germany, said she would have changed money before
departing, even at a lower exchange rate, had she known about the
problems with automatic teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   ''We waited to change money, because you get a better rate at
the ATM -- well, usually,'' Groth said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 148; Dow Off 150  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell broadly today as investors
resolutely refused to buy into a market facing rising interest
rates. Technology stocks, among the market's most highly valued
issues, led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 150.43 to 10,626.85.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 148.10 to 3,390.61.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 30.26 to 1,406.95.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,960 down, 934 up and 483 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 850.53 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.
804.14 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 10.51 to
480.44.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Federal Reserve raised interest rates,
investors continued moving away from the stocks seen as most
vulnerable in the current market environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of fear out there,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.
Louis. ''People are concerned and worried about how high interest
rates will go ... and this market will be volatile until there is
evidence on the table that the Fed will not derail the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve raised rates for the sixth time since June
on Tuesday, and indicated that inflation remains a risk. The Fed's
warning raised expectations among investors that more increases are
on tap later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they
cut into corporate profits by increasing the cost of borrowing
money.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are vulnerable to interest rate
fluctuations, fell today. Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
and Lehman Brothers were all lower.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also came under some selling pressure. Cisco
and Apple Computer dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell. Earlier this week, the company lowered its
previously reported first-quarter earnings by a penny and its
revenue by $28 million. Intel disclosed the revision in documents
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' eagerness to punish Intel betrayed their nervousness
about owning expensive stocks while escalating interest rates could
compromise corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Valuations in the technology sector got so stretched at the
start of this year,'' said Jim Weiss, deputy chief investment
officer for equities at State Street Research and Management Co. in
Boston. ''The rotation away from technology will continue as people
are looking for more diversification and some more defensive
elements.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks were mostly higher today, benefiting from the
escalating cost of crude oil. Crude prices surged above $30 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, and were
hovering slightly below that level in trading today.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron and Exxon Mobil rose.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be scouring new economic data in the coming weeks
to see if the Fed's actions are slowing the economy. The first
piece comes next Thursday, when the Commerce Department issues its
preliminary report on first-quarter gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, stocks are unlikely to advance, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a news vacuum right now and there are no earnings
stories to talk about for months, so there is nothing to fuel the
market,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Volume topped Thursday's quiet pace due to today's
double-witching expiration of stock and index options. Volume has
been lower than normal for about two weeks as many investors
dropped out of the market to debate the Fed's future course of
action.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
