<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilians Flee Advancing Ethiopians  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZRON, Eritrea (AP) -- Tens of thousands of Eritrean civilians
fled advancing Ethiopian troops and the government struggled to set
up camps to house and feed them Friday, a week after Ethiopia
launched an all-out offensive to end a two-year border war with its
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. and Eritrean aid officials said Eritrea, a country of 4
million people in the Horn of Africa, was hovering on the edge of a
humanitarian tragedy: The more than half million people escaping
fighting in western Eritrea added to a drought crisis that already
threatened 300,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted evacuees, mostly women and children, tumbled out of
trucks Friday to stake out a patch of soil away from the rapidly
advancing front, which lay about 60 miles to the east. One evacuee,
14-year-old Abdullah Ali, sat surrounded by 3,000 other uprooted
Eritreans in a camp that has gone up overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know where my parents are,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning Ethiopian offensive caught Eritreans by surprise,
splitting families as they fled. Ali rushed home when Ethiopian
warplanes roared over Akordat last weekend, but found no one there.
He fled the town 35 miles north of Barentu, then boarded a bus
evacuating panicked Eritreans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were playing soccer when the Ethiopian planes started
bombing. I left without my parents,'' said Metker Gebrhiwe, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Ali and Metker are just two of the 550,000 Eritreans the
state-run relief agency says have been forced from their homes by
the onslaught of Ethiopian troops, artillery and warplanes that
began May 12. The latest round of fighting over the 620-mile border
began when Ethiopia retook a piece of disputed territory Eritrea
had seized in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, the government denied any
intention of taking over recognized Eritrean territory. ''Ethiopia
had no designs on sovereign Eritrean territory in 1993, and it does
not have such designs now,'' an official statement said, referring
to the year of Eritrea's independence from Ethiopia after a 30-year
guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   By midday Friday, 15 trucks and buses brimming with fleeing
Eritreans had already arrived at this 2-day-old camp stretched
across a desolate, rocky swath of land 10 miles north of Keren.
Naizei Woldenu, a regional aid official, said the camp would reach
its 30,000 capacity within days.
</P>
<P>
   With Ethiopian forces already in control of Barentu and Akordat,
Keren -- 50 miles north of the capital, Asmara -- displayed all the
trappings of a front-line city. Eritrean troops in camouflage
streamed through the streets. The manager of the main hotel was
said to have locked the doors and left. Account holders crushed at
bank doors to withdraw their money to stock up on food, or to
prepare to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The enemy could attack at any time,'' Ibrahim Osman said as he
fought to hold his ground among the crowd gathered in front of the
local branch of the Commercial Bank of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Goiton Berke arrived in Keren three weeks ago from Phoenix,
Ariz., to visit his hometown. He ended up consoling his mother and
sisters after his brother, an Eritrean soldier, was killed this
week by an Ethiopian artillery round.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are scared to death. We don't know anything,'' Berke said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Ethiopian state television said Ethiopian aircraft
had bombed a military training center in western Eritrea near the
Sudanese border as Ethiopian troops consolidated their control over
Barentu. Barentu had been an important command and control center
for the Eritrean army.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the Eritrean government on
the latest bombing report. On Thursday, the Ethiopians said they
hit targets near Eritrea's Red Sea port of Massawa.
</P>
<P>
   In Keren on Friday, scores of dust-covered trucks spilling over
with sandal-shod soldiers trundled through town, away from the
front and toward Asmara. The troop trucks were interspersed with
flatbed trucks carrying missile launchers, tanks, heavy artillery
and mobile radar units. They were headed south toward a second
front.
</P>
<P>
   In the barren settlement camp in Zron, meanwhile, the new
arrivals started to slowly piece together a routine, hoping their
stay wouldn't be long. The able-bodied lined up to help unload
trucks of wheat from the United States, dates from Saudi Arabia and
milk powder from the Netherlands, while others washed clothes and
stretched them over bushes to dry under the glaring sun.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know when, but I'll go home,'' 14-year-old Abdella
Adris said as he joined the queue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1637 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor abandons Senate campaign  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, his political ambitions
derailed by prostate cancer and a nasty split with his wife, today
abandoned his Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to think the core of me was in politics. It isn't,''
Giuliani told a City Hall news conference, folding his campaign
before ever officially announcing its start. The stunning decision
ended three weeks of intense speculation over his viability as a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've decided that what I should do is to put my health
first,'' he said. ''... This is not the right time for me to run
for office.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank God that it gives me really another 18 months to be
the mayor of New York City,'' he said. In those 18 months, an
unusually reflective Giuliani said, he hoped to heal any divisions
created during his six years in City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about whether the 55-year-old mayor would quit the
Senate race almost instantly followed his April 27 cancer
disclosure. Giuliani had said that his candidacy would be
contingent on his choice of treatment options -- a decision that he
still has not made.
</P>
<P>
   But that candidacy took another hit last week with his
announcement that he was discussing a legal separation from his
wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover. Hanover retorted with her own
bombshell, publicly suggesting he had an affair with a former
staffer. At the same time, the mayor was flaunting a relationship
with a third woman, Judith Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's announcement to a packed City Hall news conference
made no mention of either his wife or Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said his decision followed a sleepless night, but
expressed hope that his pulling out was ''all for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know that I'd be able to campaign the way I should,''
said Giuliani, citing his upcoming cancer treatment. ''I don't know
that in August or September that I'd be able to continue the way I
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he broke the news to Republican leaders by phone,
and pledged his support to likely GOP nominee Rick Lazio, a Long
Island congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, long a political animal, told reporters that he had a
revelation that spurred his announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I woke up this morning and said, 'There are more important
things in life,''' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking after Giuliani's announcement, said she had
wished the mayor a speedy recovery in a phone conversation. She
said little about the effect of his withdrawal on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''This campaign is not about me or any opponent,'' Clinton said
at a brief news conference. ''I am not going to talk about politics
or ... the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The married mayor, shortly after the cancer announcement, went
public with confirmation that he was seeing his ''very, very good
friend'' Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP mayor said later that he and Hanover were discussing a
formal separation, although he apparently went public with the news
before telling his wife. Hanover's spokeswoman said today that she
had hired a matrimonial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But while the double-barreled revelations about Giuliani's
health and his marriage made for huge headlines, polls taken after
the mayor's announcements showed he was still running about even
with the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders must now scramble to find a replacement
candidate in the 10 days before their May 30 convention in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders, including Gov. George Pataki, had passed the
word that their favored replacement candidate to challenge the
first lady was U.S. Rep. Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said for several days that he would make no statement
about his intentions until Giuliani had made his decision. The
congressman, who has about $3.5 million in his campaign bank
account, had been preparing to run for the Senate until August when
Pataki endorsed the mayor's bid and asked Lazio to suspend his
effort. Lazio did so.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King has said he is interested, but he alienated
party leadership with his support of Sen. John McCain in the
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Giuliani told an hour-long town hall meeting
broadcast nationally that he regretted some of his most
controversial actions of the past year. He specifically
acknowledged a mistake in his handling of the slaying of Patrick
Dorismond, an unarmed black man killed in a recent scuffle with
undercover police.
</P>
<P>
   ''I should have also conveyed the human feeling that I had, the
compassion, the loss of the mother,'' Giuliani said. ''I think if I
could do it over again, I would have tried to balance it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Mitchell whether he has become more compassionate
because of his illness, Giuliani said ''something has to happen to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   In making a decision on treatment, Giuliani said he had
anticipated a different process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kind of approached it as if this was a big case, or a budget
decision,'' the former prosecutor said. But this decision he said,
''involves thinking about your life, mortality, the quality of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's three options for treatment are surgery, external
beam radiation and radioactive seed implantation. The 15-year
survival rate is 95 percent for surgery and 60 to 70 percent for
the two less invasive options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 1638 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carvey Sues Doctor for Artery Error  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- It was no laughing matter when comedian
Dana Carvey came out of open-heart surgery and found out a doctor
had operated on the wrong artery.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember just lying in my bed just sobbing,'' Carvey said
Thursday in San Francisco Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Carvey, 44, was testifying in his $7.5 million lawsuit against
the San Francisco surgeon who made the mistake during double bypass
surgery in 1998 to clear a blocked artery. Carvey has since
recovered after getting the blockage removed by angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   He sued surgeon Elias Hanna last year to recover damages for the
six months he spent recovering, saying he turned down offers to do
commercials, a television series and a spot on ''Hollywood
Squares.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna's defense lawyer contended Carvey has an ''unusual
anatomy'' and that his blood vessels were in atypical positions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1640 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor abandons Senate campaign; Lazio throws hat in ring  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
