<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Drop Fuel Efficiency Plan  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats dropped plans Friday to
challenge a Republican-written ban on raising auto fuel efficiency
standards, worried that a vote would have torn vulnerable
incumbents between their traditional labor and environmentalist
backers.
</P>
<P>
   The election-year decision angered environmental groups, who
have been vainly trying to repeal the prohibition ever since
Republicans pushed it into law in 1995, when they took control of
Congress. It has been re-enacted annually ever since as part of a
routine transportation spending bill that President Clinton has
never vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're extremely disappointed in the Republican leadership for
putting this rider in the bill again, and in the Democratic
leadership for apparently discouraging their members from trying to
strip it,'' said Gene Karpinski, executive director of the U.S.
Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Becker, director of the Sierra Club's global warming
project, said the club is ''outraged'' that Republicans were
backing the restrictions again, and ''profoundly disappointed that
the Democratic leadership didn't fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Olver, D-Mass., had prepared an amendment to this
year's transportation measure that would have stripped language
forbidding the government from even studying changes in the
standards.
</P>
<P>
   But the House approved the overall bill by 395-13 Friday, with
Olver never offering his amendment. Olver said he decided to hold
his fire after talking with ''a lot of different people,''
including House Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The environmental, labor communities are usually very strongly
pro-Democratic,'' he said in an interview. ''To end up dividing
them at this point, I think that's not a good political move.''
</P>
<P>
   Olver and others said that in particular, Democrats from
Michigan and other midwestern, automobile industry states would
have been forced into an uncomfortable position had a vote
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came as the House prepared to vote next week on
granting permanent normal trade relations to China, which is also
causing deep splits among Democrats. Party leaders believe that one
such wrenching issue this election year is enough, said aides
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A vote may have also put pressure on Vice President Al Gore, the
likely Democratic presidential candidate. Defeat of the effort
seemed certain, but it may have attracted enough votes for the
House to sustain a presidential veto -- more than one third of the
voting members. In that case, Gore may have come under conflicting
pressures over whether to urge Clinton to sign or veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Congress set the corporate average fuel economy, or
CAFE, standard at 27.5 miles per gallon on new passenger cars and
20.7 mpg for light trucks. But with growing concerns about air
pollution and the growing popularity of sports utility vehicles,
which get low gasoline mileage, some lawmakers have begun pushing
for higher requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, in the only vote so far challenging the GOP
restrictions, the Senate voted 55-40 against reconsidering them.
The Senate has yet to write its version of this year's bill.
</P>
<P>
   A letter to Clinton asking him to ''work with Congress'' to
improve fuel efficiency requirements had the signatures of 107
House members on Friday, including 12 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Among those lobbying to retain the current restrictions were the
National Association of Manufacturers and the Ford Motor Co., which
used its internal website to urge employees to write lawmakers to
keep existing standards.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to congressional leaders, White House budget
chief Jack Lew said the administration ''strongly opposes'' the ban
on higher requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter did not threaten a veto of the $55 billion bill,
which contains money for airport, road and mass transit projects in
every state and is hugely popular among lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that discussions involving Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., Olver and others had occurred over the last two
days. They said that among those urging that the vote not occur was
Rep. Debbie Stabenow, D-Mich., who is challenging Sen. Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., for his seat this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Stabenow said in an interview that she opposed having the vote,
but said she has already said publicly that the ban should remain
in place for another year.
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ''It's always difficult in Michigan because the
auto industry is so important, yet you also have a very strong
environmental presence.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4475.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
