<HEADLINE> Commissioner Johnson Leaves SEC  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Norman S. Johnson, a member of the Securities
and Exchange Commission, formally resigned his position Friday in a
letter to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC had announced Johnson's intention to leave in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''I leave the SEC secure in the knowledge that the interests of
our nation's investors and markets are in the very capable hands of
my colleagues, all of whom were appointed by you,'' he said in a
letter to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Johnson, a Republican appointed by Clinton,
leaves a vacancy on the five-member commission, which regulates
securities markets, mutual funds and investment companies.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 69, plans to return to Utah, his home state. Although
his four-year term expired in June 1999, he could have stayed in
office until the end of Congress' current term.
</P>
<P>
   Before his appointment, Johnson had a 30-year career as a
securities attorney in private practice in Salt Lake City.
</P>
</TEXT>
