<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anglicans, Catholics Discuss Union  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Anglican and Roman Catholic bishops concluded a
week of prayer and dialogue Friday by announcing plans for a joint
commission to further explore the possibility of unification.
</P>
<P>
   The closed-door meeting was chaired by Anglicanism's spiritual
leader, Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey, and Cardinal Edward
Cassidy, president of the Vatican's Pontifical Council for
Promoting Christian Unity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt it was the logical outcome of this meeting,'' Cassidy
said of the commission. ''By the end of the year we hope to be set
up and running.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither leader offered any specifics on how the
millions of Anglicans and Roman Catholics around the world would be
affected by the commission's decisions, Carey said the changes
could be felt at local congregations in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jane Doe and John Doe want to know what the cash value is of
all this,'' Carey said. ''It is to stimulate the quest, to raise
the expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said unification is unlikely to take place in his
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Among the obstacles to unification will be dealing with the
place of women -- who are not eligible for ordination as Catholic
priests -- and determining how power would be distributed in a
unified religion, bishops from both faiths said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have challenges, serious challenges that we have to face,''
Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   This week's series of seminars and one-on-one discussions among
the bishops took place in a Catholic retreat in a posh neighborhood
near Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   A public service at St. Michael's Cathedral in downtown Toronto
on Wednesday evening drew more than 1,000 people to hear the church
leaders address issues that have been at the heart of the
400-year-old split between Anglicans and Catholics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
