<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone OKs Jesse Jackson Visit  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Three days after warning Jesse
Jackson to stay away from Sierra Leone, the government said Friday
the U.S. envoy is now welcome to visit the troubled West African
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who visited neighboring Liberia on Friday, is touring
West Africa in a bid to calm tensions in Sierra Leone and win the
freedom of about 330 U.N. peacekeepers held captive by
Revolutionary United Front rebels. No clashes were reported Friday
between government forces and the rebels, and there were no signs
of progress in negotiations to free the peacekeepers, who have been
held for more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson caused a stir last week when he said rebel leader Foday
Sankoh should be included in reconciliation efforts in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's forces have killed and maimed tens of thousands in
almost nine years of civil war. The rebel chief is widely blamed
for breaking last July's peace accord and plunging the country back
into conflict this month. He was captured Wednesday and remains in
government custody.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Sama Banya was quoted on state radio Tuesday as
saying Jackson should not come to Sierra Leone because of the
sympathy he expressed for Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   But several days after he was first quoted, Jackson issued a
statement saying his earlier comments apparently had ''been
misunderstood in Sierra Leone and elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to make it clear that Foday Sankoh and the RUF
alone are responsible for the current crisis in Sierra Leone,'' he
said in the statement. ''In my comments, my purpose was not to
compare the RUF and the ANC. There is no equivalence between the
two. My intention was merely to note that the ANC became a part of
the political process.'' He also suggested that Sankoh may have
forfeited his role in the Sierra Leone peace process.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Jackson on Friday, Banya said: ''the government
would welcome him today if he came.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The government had wanted that clarification (of Jackson's
comments) and he's done so,'' Banya said.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of Freetown, many residents despise Sankoh for
the atrocities committed by his rebels: killing, raping and cutting
off hands, legs, lips and ears of defenseless civilians. Some
expressed resentment toward Jackson for his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jesse Jackson is insensitive to the suffering of the Sierra
Leonean people,'' said George Khoryama of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's itinerary has changed repeatedly, and it was not clear
when he might seek to visit Sierra Leone. Part of his delegation
may visit Sierra Leone without him, according to a State Department
official in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The entire delegation plans to stop in Mali and Guinea over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The tour by Jackson, who is serving as President Clinton's
special envoy, has attracted media attention in the region, though
the United States is not playing a central role in peace efforts in
Sierra Leone. No American troops are among the U.N. peacekeepers,
and the United States has not sought to intervene directly between
the factions here.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. forces are still seeking to establish order in Sierra
Leone almost three weeks after the rebels began taking peacekeepers
hostage, launching attacks on U.N. and pro-government forces and
sending terrified residents streaming into Freetown to avoid
anticipated rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the U.N. Security Council voted to increase the size
of the peacekeeping contingent in Sierra Leone from 11,100 to
13,000. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is expected to call for
an eventual increase to 16,500, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Sierra Leone's government said it was
investigating the actions of Sankoh and his RUF fighters. The
government has not said what it intends to do with the rebel chief.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where culpability is found, we will take the appropriate
action,'' presidential spokesman Septimus Kai Kai said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have not indicated how they will respond to Sankoh's
detention. In 1998, Sankoh was sentenced to death for treason, and
his rebels subsequently invaded Freetown, killing thousands before
they were driven out of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
