<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Settle With Jewish Siblings  </HEADLINE>
By CLARE NULLIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The Swiss government will pay $118,000 to a Jewish
brother and sister whose parents were gassed by the Nazis after
Switzerland kicked the family out during World War II, the Finance
Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry said it will pay Charles and Sabine Sonabend in an
out-of-court settlement to cover their costs from a legal battle
with the government. Ministry officials stopped short of calling
the payment ''compensation,'' apparently fearing that might
encourage claims from other Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Finance Minister Kaspar Villiger said he would meet the
Sonabends on Tuesday to express ''the sympathy and regret of the
government'' -- a move hailed by the Sonabends' lawyer as more
important than the cash offer. ''My clients see themselves as
representatives of all the other Holocaust refugees in
Switzerland,'' lawyer Marc Richter said.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by Germany, Nazi-occupied France and Nazi-allied
Italy, neutral Switzerland took in nearly 30,000 Jews during World
War II. But, fearing that it would be swamped by refugees or
provoke Germany's ire, it repelled an equal number to face almost
certain death.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the instances of anguish the policy caused, the plight of
the Sonabends is the best documented.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1942, the Sonabends decided to use their considerable
wealth to escape mass deportations of Jews from Nazi-held Belgium.
Simon Sonabend -- a prominent watch retailer -- paid smugglers to get
him, his wife Laja, 11-year-old Charles and 15-year-old Sabine from
Brussels into Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were confident,'' Charles Sonabend later told a historian
who documented the case for Swiss federal archives. ''We had
arrived in Switzerland and were saved.''
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to the Sonabends, Swiss authorities had issued a
confidential order closing the border to Jews. The family was
arrested promptly after arriving. Simon Sonabend was thrown into a
border town prison, while his wife and children were put in a
nearby convent.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss police records note how Laja Sonabend ''collapsed to the
floor in a dead faint'' during an attempt to bundle the family into
a car for transportation to the border. ''The children were
screaming for help,'' the records said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of local people took to the streets to protest the
deportation, but to no avail. Soon after the Sonabends were taken
across the border, they were traced by German authorities and
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Laja Sonabend were gassed at Auschwitz. The children
survived: A Jewish group managed to smuggle them to Paris, where
they spent the rest of the war in hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Charles now lives in London and his sister in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are satisfied that it's the best result we could have
obtained,'' said Richter, the Sonabends' lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1726 </TRAILER>
