<HEADLINE> Asst. Miami Police Chief Quits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The assistant Miami police chief who caused a furor
in City Hall by riding with federal agents during the raid to seize
Elian Gonzalez has quit the force.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. John Brooks, a 25-year police veteran, will become a
Broward County sheriff's captain.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' involvement in the armed raid last month triggered the
firing of the city manager and the resignation of its police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials in the predominantly Cuban-American city had
said that they didn't want Miami police to take part in any
government effort to seize the boy, and they were shocked to see
Brooks sitting in the passenger seat of the van that carried Elian
away.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Brooks rode along so officers on duty at the house
would realize it was an official action. Police on the scene had
only a moment's notice of the raid, and vehicles in the caravan
carrying the federal agents were unmarked.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need talented leaders with guts, vision and integrity,''
Brooks' new boss, Sheriff Ken Jenne, said in a statement Friday.
''I know that John will meet every challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
