<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrat Asked To Join GOP Group  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It turns out that the Republican Senatorial
''Inner Circle'' isn't as exclusive as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kent Conrad, a North Dakota Democrat, received an
invitation this week from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott to join
the circle, made up of people who donate at least $1,000 a year to
the National Republican Senatorial Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter sent to Conrad's home, Lott told Conrad he was
nominated by GOP senators to serve as one of 40 members from
Washington, D.C., in the ''exclusive'' Inner Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, I invite you to accept this honor and help Republican
members of the United States Senate advance our powerful national
agenda of lower taxes, less government and common sense values,''
wrote Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really am honored by this,'' a chuckling Conrad said Friday.
''To have my colleagues get together and nominate me for their
inner circle.... I don't think I'll be sending them any money.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad said he thanked Lott for the letter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''OK,'' Lott said, ''what letter, Kent?'' On hearing the letter
invited Conrad to join the group and attend the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia this summer, Lott said, ''You have to
wonder about these lists,'' Conrad recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Roy, a Republican Senatorial Committee spokesman, said
Conrad got the letter ''because we are eternal optimists and we
still had him in the undecided column.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This shows you how a big a tent the Republican party is,''
joked Lott spokesman John Czwartacki.
</P>
</TEXT>
