<DOCNO> APW20000519.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Atlantic City, MGM Grand calls it quits on one casino plan  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Some land speculators got rich.
Others held out too long. As for the tiny Roman Catholic church at
Oriental and New Jersey avenues, which stood in the way of the
casino plan, it accepted a buyout and disbanded after 91 years.
</P>
<P>
   The handwriting was on the wall: Casino giant MGM Grand Inc. was
coming to town, planning a $750 million to $1 billion casino on a
desolate 35-acre site near Showboat Casino Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it turns out the Monopoly-style maneuvering may have all
been for naught: MGM Grand, which spent four years and more than
$35 million assembling land for its project, is apparently planning
to cash in its chips on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company will take over a site owned by Mirage
Resorts Inc., which it is in the process of buying.
</P>
<P>
   MGM Grand officials weren't commenting on the change-of-heart,
which was reported by The Press of Atlantic City. James Murren, its
president, did not return telephone calls to his office Thursday
and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes, it seems like this town is snakebitten,'' said
Stuart Wiser, director of redevelopment for the city. ''At least
this one wasn't our fault, though.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials feared this in March, when MGM Grand announced it
would buy out Mirage in a $6.4 billion shocker.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, still pending, means that Mirage is walking away from
its plan to build a Las Vegas-style megacasino in the marina
district. It was Mirage, and chairman Stephen Wynn, who had
triggered renewed interest in Atlantic City and persuaded the state
to help finance a $330 million road-and-tunnel connector improving
access to the marina district site where it planned to build.
</P>
<P>
   MGM plans to assume control of that project and give up on its
so-called Uptown project, which has been little but trouble since
it was announced in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Property owners who had bought parcels years ago on speculation
immediately began jacking up the asking prices. MGM Grand bought
land that had been selling at $30 per square foot for $100 per
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the city stepped in, declaring a nine-acre area within
MGM's project site in need of redevelopment, a precursor to eminent
domain proceedings. That prompted a lawsuit by Joseph Zoll, 58, a
Media, Pa., businessman who owned about 200 parcels of land around
the city, some of them in the MGM area.
</P>
<P>
   Zoll lost in court, but later sold to MGM and helped persuade
other holdouts to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Shalom Dai, a New York businessman who was asking $1,000
a square foot for his two MGM-area parcels. The city condemned his
properties and was in the process of seizing them, through eminent
domain, when the MGM-Mirage deal broke.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked to Shalom Dai and tried to bring him in with Joe and
the rest of us,'' said Zoll attorney George Miller. ''I talked to
his lawyer and I talked to him. He believed he was going to get
$1,000 a square foot. Now, with no project, I don't know what his
property is worth,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The condemnation will continue, even if MGM is no longer
interested, said Wiser.
</P>
<P>
   Others went quietly. Holy Spirit Church, at Oriental and New
Jersey avenues, accepted a $3.7 million buyout from MGM. It held
its last Mass in September and was recently razed.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials have no regrets, though.
</P>
<P>
   ''The parish had been experiencing a decline in the number of
parish families for a period of time,'' said Andrew Walton, a
spokesman for the Diocese of Camden. ''That certainly was a
consideration in the Diocese's decision to close the parish,'' he
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Oriental Avenue, the canceled casino came as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once they knocked the church down, I really thought they were
coming,'' said Hastings Payne, 66. ''I figured if they put a casino
there, this part of town would start to look better. It doesn't
look too good now.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, city officials still had not been notified by MGM
Grand that the casino project was off.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expected it,'' said Louis Toscano, a spokesman for Mayor
James Whelan. ''From our perspective, it makes a lot of sense.
Those plans (in the marina district) are a lot further along than
Uptown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
