<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 150; Nasdaq Down 148  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell broadly Friday as investors
resolutely refused to buy into a market facing rising interest
rates. Technology stocks, among the market's most highly valued
issues, led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of fear out there,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.
Louis. ''People are concerned and worried about how high interest
rates will go ... and this market will be volatile until there is
evidence on the table that the Fed will not derail the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 150.43 to 10,626.85. For
the week, the Dow gained 17.48 points thanks to powerful rallies on
Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also fell Friday. The Nasdaq composite
index dropped 148.31 to 3,390.40, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
fell 30.26 to 1,406.95.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Federal Reserve raised interest rates for
the sixth time since June, investors continued moving away from the
stocks seen as most vulnerable in the market's current environment.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fed announced its action on Tuesday, it also indicated
that inflation remains a risk. The warning raised expectations
among investors that more rate hikes are likely later this year -- a
negative trend for stocks because higher rates raise borrowing
costs and cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are particularly vulnerable to interest
rate fluctuations, fell Friday. Merrill Lynch fell 5{ to 103 9/16,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter slid 5\ to 69 7/16 and Lehman Brothers
lost 3 13/16 to 81~.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also came under pressure. Cisco Systems fell 1
15/16 to 53 7/16 and Apple Computer dropped 6} to 94.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell 6 1/16 to 117~. Earlier this week, the company
lowered its previously reported first-quarter earnings by a penny
and its revenue by $28 million. Intel disclosed the revision in
documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' eagerness to punish Intel betrayed their nervousness
about owning expensive stocks while interest rates are rising.
</P>
<P>
   ''Valuations in the technology sector got so stretched at the
start of this year,'' said Jim Weiss, deputy chief investment
officer for equities at State Street Research and Management Co. in
Boston. ''The rotation away from technology will continue as people
are looking for more diversification and some more defensive
elements.''
</P>
<P>
   But oil stocks were mostly higher, benefiting from the rising
price of crude oil. A barrel of crude surged above $30 a barrel on
the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, then fell back to $29.89
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron rose 2 7/16 to 93 5/16 and Exxon Mobil rose 19/64 to
81}.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be scouring new economic data in the coming weeks
to see if the Fed's actions are slowing the economy. The first
piece comes next Thursday, when the Commerce Department issues a
preliminary report on first-quarter gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, stocks are unlikely to advance, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a news vacuum right now and there are no earnings
stories to talk about for months, so there is nothing to fuel the
market,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Composite volume on the New York Stock Exchange came to 1.06
billion shares, topping Thursday's quiet pace due to the
double-witching expiration of stock and index options. Volume has
been lower than normal for about two weeks as many investors
dropped out of the market to debate the Fed's future course of
action.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 11.25 to
479.70.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.0 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index tumbled 2.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
fell 3.0 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 4.0 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
