<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Agrees To Stop Training  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR ZIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Shaken by a spate of religious
killings in recent weeks, Pakistan has asked Afghanistan's Taliban
ruling militia to stop training Pakistani religious militants and
the Taliban have agreed, Pakistan's interior minister said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan issued the request during meetings this week with the
Taliban's Interior Minister, Mullah Abdul Razzak. According to his
Pakistani counterpart, Moinuddin Haider, Razzak promised the
Taliban would put an end to the training, although he refused to
give more details.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the Taliban had denied allowing training camps on
their soil.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many Pakistanis who have trained in Afghanistan indulge in
crimes when they return home,'' Haider said. ''We don't want any
Pakistani belonging to any religious group or sect being trained in
Afghanistan. We want to put an end to this.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, more than 20 Shiite Muslims have been killed in
separate attacks throughout the country. The assailants are
believed to have been extremist Sunni Muslims, although no arrests
have been made.
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, which is dominated by Sunni Muslims, most people
live peacefully with their Shiite Muslim brethren. But a small
minority on each side are heavily armed, and the two sides
regularly clash.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, who are Sunni Muslims, have been accused of
harboring and training Muslims militants from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's most wanted militants -- Osama bin Laden, who
is accused of masterminding the deadly bombings of U.S. embassies
in Africa in 1998 -- also lives in Afghanistan. Washington says he
runs an international terrorist network from the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have refused hand over bin Laden to the U.S. or a
third country for trial. They say bin Laden is not carrying out any
activities on their soil.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has asked Pakistan to help convince the Taliban to
hand over bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan is one of only three countries to recognized the
Taliban and is considered one of their greatest allies. But Haider
said Pakistan's influence on the Taliban is limited and at best
Islamabad could get the two sides talking.
</P>
<P>
   Another big concern for Pakistan is the use of Pakistani
territory to transit narcotics produced in Afghanistan to Western
markets. Afghanistan is the world's largest producer of opium, the
raw material used to make heroin, according to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have agreed to reduce production by one-third,
Haider said. But the Taliban say they need foreign assistance to
put an end to the opium production. The Taliban also say that want
Western countries to reduce the demand for heroin, Haider said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1816 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Denounces Opponents  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic pledged
Friday to defend Yugoslavia against ''enemies'' trying to break up
the country, as opposition groups staged more protests demanding an
end to a government crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing violence following two days of police attacks on
pro-democracy demonstrators, opposition leaders urged more than
5,000 supporters at a rally in Belgrade for restraint and peaceful
resistance to the regime.
</P>
<P>
   ''No television and no power is worth a single human life,''
declared Vuk Draskovic, a key opposition leader who joined the
protests on Friday after a two-day absence. ''I beg you to
understand we can only fight state terrorism by peaceful
resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The government on Wednesday took over Belgrade's opposition-run
Studio B television and radio, triggering pro-democracy activists
to launch a series of protests that have led to several arrests and
the injury of more than 150 people in clashes with police.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright openly
challenged officials of Milosevic's regime to break with him and
join the pro-democracy forces.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke during a joint press briefing with Portuguese Foreign
Minister Jaime Gama.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agreed that officials in Serbia face a choice,'' she said.
''They can stand for the freedom and the rights of all Serbs, or
they can prolong Milosevic's rule by participating in the
oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said they discussed ways that the United States and the
EU ''can make clear our solidarity and increase our support for the
courageous men and women who are demanding their rights in the
cities and towns across Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, several hundred activists from Otpor, or
Resistance, a popular student group which has been targeted by the
government, handed out leaflets in downtown Belgrade decrying the
president's crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 police stopped them to check their documents, taking
away at least one Otpor flag with the group's signature clenched
fist emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of riot police fired tear gas Thursday and charged at
over 10,000 protesters who lobbed stones and fire bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police intervention was extremely brutal, they are trying
to frighten the citizens into stopping the protests,'' said Goran
Svilanovic, an opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who had been absent from the demonstrations, returned
to the capital Friday saying he had contacted top Russian and Greek
officials over the crisis in Serbia. Both Moscow and Athens --
traditional allies of Belgrade -- have joined numerous other
countries and international organizations in condemning Milosevic's
latest attack on dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic seemed unimpressed. In a statement Friday, he said the
government would stand firm ''despite joint efforts by Yugoslavia's
enemies abroad and at home who are trying to break up the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the enemies were using ''armed and media aggression,
terrorism, sanctions, and treason'' by those who serve foreign
interests within the country -- an apparent reference to the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president's statement adds to fears of growing
violence in Serbia, where the government has launched the harshest
crackdown yet against opponents, following the slaying last week of
a top official which the authorities blamed on the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic dispatched his police chief, Vlajko Stojiljkovic, to
the southern, opposition-run city of Nis where about 10,000 people
gathered Friday evening for an opposition rally.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions in Nis were high following an incident on Thursday when
a group of pro-government city officials was mobbed by opposition
supporters in front of the city hall. Two members of the ruling
Socialist Party were reported injured.
</P>
<P>
   Stojiljkovic has pledged to ''root out terrorism and violence,''
and to do everything so that Nis will ''remain a peaceful city,''
the state-run Tanjug new agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1822 </TRAILER>
