<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rudolph Giuliani's marriage: the Achilles heel of a tough man  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani never mentioned the
tumult in his marital life when he ended his campaign for the U.S.
Senate on Friday. Instead, he dwelled on the need to get the best
treatment for his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But news of his crumbling marriage has been as much in the
public mind as reports on his health since he revealed his cancer
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was the mayor who let loose the opening salvo in a
tit-for-tat exchange with his wife that decimated their union.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor first mentioned he had a ''very, very good friend''
after reporters spotted him escorting around town a divorced
45-year-old Upper East Sider, Judith Nathan. Then he announced that
he and wife Donna Hanover were talking about a separation.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover, an actress and television personality, quickly let it
be known that his public statement was made without her knowing it
was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Looking in shock, a teary-eyed Hanover said she had tried to
keep the marriage together, then accused the 55-year-old mayor of
having had ''a relationship'' earlier with his press aide, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas. Giuliani and his former aide both denied the
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than two weeks framed the end of a marital saga that
began 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday -- before the mayor pulled out of the Senate race -- a
spokeswoman for the 50-year-old Hanover confirmed reports that she
had hired a high-powered divorce lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover, a Naval officer's daughter, and her husband, a federal
prosecutor, met on a 1982 blind date.
</P>
<P>
   After a whirlwind romance, they made the perfect power couple,
with a newborn son in tow. Putting her career on hold, Hanover
became a model first lady for the nation's largest city, and an
upbeat, supportive wife and mother.
</P>
<P>
   For about 14 years, the marriage appeared to hum on
harmoniously.
</P>
<P>
   Then, starting about two years ago, the couple was rarely seen
in public together.
</P>
<P>
   Calling their troubles ''very, very painful,'' the mayor said
last week, ''For quite some time, it's probably been apparent that
Donna and I lead, in most ways, independent and separate lives.''
</P>
<P>
   She had picked up on her acting career, appearing in soap operas
and a movie, and hosting several television shows.
</P>
<P>
   And they followed a delicate dance of official schedules that
landed them at different venues. She was not at his side for the
1997 mayoral re-election campaign, saying she was focusing on
raising their two children, Andrew, 14, and Caroline, 10.
</P>
<P>
   From Gracie Mansion, the mayor's residence, the official
response to the separate goings-on was -- silence.
</P>
<P>
   This week's public pummeling finally broke open the
whisper-filled shell that protected them from the media glare. And
New York's aggressive tabloids, which until now played a spicy
guessing game, had a field day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rudy's Gal 'Pal' Never Far Behind,'' said the New York Post,
which added in a column that Giuliani ''did not base his career on
his brilliance as a family man.''
</P>
<P>
   And his wife ''has made a career distancing herself from the
mayor,'' said columnist Andrea Peyser.
</P>
<P>
   Even the reserved New York Times got into the marital fray.
''Why are men so beastly?'' asked Maureen Dowd in her column.
</P>
<P>
   With the mayor out of the Senate spotlight, his marital affairs
may soon start to disappear from front pages. Still, the sudden
public vulnerabilty of a politician known for his stiff upper lip
keeps fueling fascination with his life.
</P>
<P>
   New York magazine was going to press with a cover story titled
''Rudy's Loves.''
</P>
<P>
   The subtitle suggested that Giuliani had an Achilles heel worthy
of Greek drama, asking: ''Tough? Definitely. Mean? Sometimes.
Love-struck? Who knew?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 1845 </TRAILER>
