<HEADLINE> Rowland announces public safety appointment  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A semi-retired Superior Court judge who
conducted the grand jury investigation into Hartford police
corruption was nominated Friday as the state's next Commissioner of
Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Judge Arthur L. Spada, 68, is the fifth public safety
commissioner appointed by Gov. John G. Rowland. He will succeed
world-renowned forensic expert Henry Lee, who announced his
retirement last month.
</P>
<P>
   Spada, who starts the $129,000-a-year job on June 1, will run a
department that includes the divisions of state police and fire,
emergency and building services. Spada will serve on an interim
basis until confirmed by the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Art Spada has distinguished himself as a member of the
Superior Court,'' said Rowland. ''I have every confidence that
Judge Spada will make an outstanding commissioner and live up to
the proud traditions of the Connecticut State Police.''
</P>
<P>
   He will oversee about 1,100 state troopers and inherit a new
police communications system. The $80 million project is replacing
the 60-year-old radio system that has dead spots in some part of
the state. Some barracks started using the new system late last
year. It is expected to be in place statewide by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Spada is best known for conducting the grand jury into Hartford
police corruption in the mid-1990s. A total of eight officers were
indicted; two have been acquitted at trials.
</P>
<P>
   A Hartford native, Spada earned a law degree from the University
of Connecticut School of Law in 1957. Gov. Ella Grasso appointed
him to the Superior Court in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am honored that Governor Rowland has nominated me to this
position,'' Spada said in a news release issued by the governor's
office. ''I have always had the highest respect for the men and
women of the Department of Public Safety and I look forward to
leading an organization with a national reputation for
excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee announced his retirement last month, and said he wants to
focus his efforts on unsolved murders, including the slaying of
JonBenet Ramsey. Lee also plans to step down as head of the state
crime lab, a position he has held for 19 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 1901 </TRAILER>
