<DOCNO> APW20000519.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Battle Over FCC Rules Rages  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A battle in a federal appeals courts pits
privacy groups and the telecommunications industry against the
FBI's efforts to modernize its electronic surveillance capability
against drug dealers, terrorists, spies and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of cell phones and other advances in the field of
wireless communications, the Federal Communications Commission has
upset the ''fragile balance'' between the right to privacy and the
needs of the FBI, a coalition of industry and advocacy groups
argued Wednesday in the U.S. Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition wants a three-judge panel to direct the FCC to
scale back new rules on information telecommunications companies
must be capable of providing law enforcement without a wiretap
warrant. By September 2001, the companies must be able to supply
the FBI:
</P>
<P>
   --The location of cellular phone users.
</P>
<P>
   --Any digits dialed after a call is connected such as numbers for
credit cards, bank accounts or call forwarding instructions.
</P>
<P>
   --''Packet-mode communications,'' a product of the fast-changing
telecommunications industry that contains both the voice content of
phone calls and the phone numbers involved in the call.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition says the FCC rules go beyond a 1994 law requiring
telecommunications carriers to help law enforcement agencies
conduct legally authorized electronic surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   But the government says privacy rights are being fully
protected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Information revealing the approximate location of wireless
callers ... is no different from the location information that
results from the detection of a telephone number in the landline
system,'' the FCC replied in written arguments filed with the
appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   However, Theodore Olson, one of the lawyers in the coalition,
said in an interview Friday that ''locating the person making the
phone call converts cellular phones into government tracking
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson represents the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association and the Center for Democracy and Technology, two groups
in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Technology problems are colliding with the needs of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy groups want the FCC to require companies to ''strip
out'' the content portion of phone calls from the ''packet-mode
communications'' before they're turned over to the FBI in instances
where there is no wiretap warrant. The industry says it will be
expensive and technically difficult to separate pieces of the
''packets.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No one seems to agree as to how difficult or how expensive it
would be,'' said Olson. ''The technology hasn't yet caught up with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department told the appeals court that law
enforcement won't access any information it isn't entitled to, an
argument that the coalition said fails to meet constitutional
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once a surveillance device becomes a vehicle for the
acquisition of content'' of phone calls, ''it becomes subject to
the Fourth Amendment, whatever label or name it is given,'' the
coalition said in court papers. ''A fishing license cannot become a
license to drain the ocean to catch a fish.''
</P>
<P>
   In written arguments to the court, the Justice Department said
that ''contrary'' to the privacy groups' ''suggestion, law
enforcement has no desire to intercept the content portion'' absent
a wiretap warrant.
</P>
<P>
   If a telecommunications company ''has the technical ability to
strip out content from the packet stream ... that is perfectly
acceptable to law enforcement,'' said the Justice Department. ''The
privacy interests identified'' in the FCC's order ''are adequately
protected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1909 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Fujimori Continues Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's steel-fisted president, Alberto
Fujimori, continued on the campaign trail for re-election Friday,
battling against a contender who has refused to participate in a
May 28 runoff, alleging fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a growing political crisis, Fujimori flew to
Huanuco in the central Andes for a campaign rally as his supporters
assailed Alejandro Toledo, a U.S.-educated economist, for his
decision to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Tudela, Fujimori's running mate, called Toledo and his
allies ''complainers, cry babies... who play at politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo demanded on Thursday that the National Election Board
push back the runoff date from May 28 to June 18 so that there
would be time to eliminate the irregularities that marred the first
round. Hours earlier, a commission of election monitors from the
Organization of American States also sought a postponement.
</P>
<P>
   The board, controlled by Fujimori appointees, rejected the
request.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department supported the OAS request for a delay
and regretted Toledo's decision to withdraw as well as the election
board's ''hasty ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Branding Fujimori a dictator, Toledo called Friday for peaceful
street protests across Peru to force a delay in the runoff. But he
warned that he would not take part in a delayed election if the
irregularities were not corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ''The moment has arrived to stand up to the dictatorship,'' he
shouted to the roars of supporters at a street rally in Lima
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern fishing port of Chimbote police had to use tear
gas to drive back demonstrators who threw bottles and rocks at a
Fujimori campaign rally. Police formed a human barrier to keep the
protesters from Fujimori when he arrived from Huanuco.
</P>
<P>
   Romulo Munoz, a member of the election board, said Friday that
Toledo still had not made the written formal request to have his
name withdrawn from the May 28 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional experts agreed that Peruvian electoral laws do
not provide for a candidate to withdraw after elections have been
called and predicted the National Election Board would allow the
runoff to take place over Toledo's objections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government is going to continue with the idea of the May
28 election,'' said political analyst Fernando Tuesta. ''What it
will produce is a seriously damaged government.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Toledo was refusing to take part in the runoff, he gave
every indication of still being on the campaign trail with his call
for massive street protests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are continuing our campaign ... until the day when a clean
election is carried out,'' Toledo said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo urged Peruvians to boycott the May 28 vote to discredit
the result, but political experts said a widespread boycott was
unlikely because voting is a legal requirement. Those who fail to
vote must pay the equivalent of a $40 fine, a large sum in a
country where the minimum wage is less than $120 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with foreign correspondents Friday, Toledo said,
''We're aware that voting is obligatory. Let's see if they can
collect fines from 5 million Peruvians.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 11 million Peruvians voted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said Toledo apparently was aiming to
discredit Fujimori's election to a third five-year term through
widespread street protests at home and international pressure from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that the objective of Mr. Toledo's declarations is to
undercut the legitimacy of an eventual triumph,'' said Anibal
Quiroga, a constitutional expert.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Julio Carrion agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Toledo has realized that to beat this guy he has to force a
political crisis,'' he said. ''Fujimori is not somebody who sticks
to constitutional rules or any sort of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But discrediting Fujimori's government may be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   David Scott Palmer, an expert on Peru at Boston University,
notes that half of the electorate supports Fujimori because of his
success in fighting leftist guerrillas and eliminating annual
inflation that exceeded 7,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We overlook the fact that he really does have a genuine base
of support. When you reduce extreme poverty by 50 percent in the
poorest districts of the country, that's serious stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said OAS members would have difficulty reaching a
consensus on imposing serious sanctions against Fujimori's
government.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it would come to that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 1936 </TRAILER>
