<DOCNO> APW20000519.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Promoted to Majors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Todd Greene, released by the Anaheim Angels in
spring training, is back in the major leagues with the Toronto Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays purchased Greene's contract from Triple A Syracuse
on Friday. The outfielder hit .297 with seven home runs and 14 RBIs
with Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered the Angels' catcher of the future, Greene has
battled shoulder problems during the last few years. He says he can
no longer catch regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Greene hit .243 with 14 homers and 42 RBIs last season. He spent
eight years in the Angels' organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I hadn't hurt my shoulder I'd still be catching there,''
said Greene, who had a torn labrum. ''I can still catch, just not
everyday. I'm in the major leagues so I'll do whatever they ask me
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays also purchased the contract of RHP Darwin
Cubillan. To make room, Toronto optioned shortstop Chris Woodward
and designated left-hander Eric Gunderson for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   To clear a spot on the 40 man roster the Blue Jays designated
third baseman Casey Blake for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Cubillan was 3-0 with three saves and a .40 ERA for Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward appeared in just one game for Toronto. Gunderson was
0-1 with a 7.11 ERA for the Blue Jays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
