<HEADLINE> Colombia Peace Conference May Go On  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A peace conference suspended by
President Andres Pastrana after a gruesome killing by alleged
guerrillas will now probably be allowed to take place, a government
peace negotiator said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Envoy Fabio Valencia said the government is inclined to believe
rebels' claims that they had nothing to do with the deaths Monday
of a 53-year-old woman and a policeman who tried to remove a bomb
from around her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's largest rebel army, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC, said Thursday it was being wrongly blamed for
the deaths in a botched extortion attempt in central Boyaca State.
</P>
<P>
   The killings angered the South American country and prompted
Pastrana to suspend a late-May conference in rebel-held southern
Colombia to which 21 countries were invited for discussions on
battling illegal drug crops.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana had said the suspension would be in effect pending the
results of an investigation into the ''necklace-bomb'' killings.
</P>
<P>
   But in his remarks Friday, Valencia said the government may
allow the peace conference to go forward even before prosecutors
complete their inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're in conversations, in principle you have to believe
the other side,'' the negotiator said.
</P>
<P>
   That Colombians immediately suspected the rebels in the killings
is hardly a surprise. The FARC regularly uses threats, violence and
kidnapping to extort money from fellow Colombians.
</P>
<P>
   The group has not been known, however, to attach sophisticated
bombs to its victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
