<HEADLINE> Orioles-Rangers Game Postponed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Friday night's game between the Texas
Rangers and Baltimore Orioles was postponed due to heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   The game will be made up as part of a twi-night doubleheader on
Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has won four straight and seven of nine, moving over .500
(21-10) for the first time since April 15 (6-5).
</P>
<P>
   ''We're hot so we look forward to getting out there every day,''
Rangers outfielder Jason McDonald said. ''Hopefully, this rain will
let up and we'll be able to play tomorrow. But at the same time, a
lot of the guys who play regularly need a day off, so this will
help them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had played 17 games without a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could say that the off-day will help keep us on the streak
by giving us some rest,'' outfielder Chad Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas manager Johnny Oates said his team could benefit from the
rainout by giving two hot-hitting Rangers an extra day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto, batting .576 (19-for-33) with 10 hits in his
last 12 at bats, had been removed from Texas' lineup on Friday
night due to a recurring groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   And designated hitter David Segui, who began Friday fifth in the
league with a .351 average, had dizzy spells prior to the game.
Segui has had the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing you can do about it so why worry?'' Oates
said. ''The only headache is playing extra games in September. But
you can't control the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's Rangers starter, Esteban Loaiza, was rescheduled
to pitch Saturday night against the Orioles. Darren Oliver,
Saturday night's scheduled Rangers starter, will pitch Sunday night
instead of Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Clark could start Tuesday night in Kansas City if Kenny Rogers
isn't ready. Rogers has been slowed by a strained posterior capsule
in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's scheduled starter, Jason Johnson, will be skipped in
the rotation, moving to a long relief role. Mike Mussina will make
his scheduled start for the Orioles on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're used to pitching every five days, so this keeps them
lined up,'' Orioles manager Mike Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he has no problem with being skipped.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm fine with it as long as I get some innings (out of the
bullpen),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has lost 13 of 15 and is 6-18 since April 22.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Texas sent OF Gabe Kapler to Triple-A Oklahoma on medical
rehab assignment. Kapler was placed on the 15-day disabled list on
May 4 with a partially torn muscle in his upper right quadriceps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
