<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
People Work Harder, More Often To Pay for Basics: Report
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- We're pinched for time, money and fun, and it
might not get any better.
</P>
<P>
   People have to work harder and more to pay for the basics and
maintain a quality of life similar to their parents' generation,
says a report released today by the Vanier Institute of the Family,
a non-partisan national research organization based in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Most families, on average, needed to work a year and a half to
cover annual living expenses, says the report, based mainly on the
most recent figures from the 1996 census.
</P>
<P>
   That means either both parents must work or one put in about 65
to 80 hours a week for food, clothing, shelter, education and
recreation, said Alan Mirabelli, executive director of the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   If you lived in Toronto or Vancouver, two incomes were an
absolute necessity, suggests the report. If you lived in Kelowna,
British Columbia, or Sudbury, Ontario, one and half salaries might
get the average family by. And in Atlantic Canada, one salary and a
bit should have done the trick.
</P>
<P>
   The average family income for Canada in 1997 was $55,628, the
report says, citing Statistics Canada. Among the provinces, the
average ranged from a high of $61,110 in Ontario to a low of
$40,630 in Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   The time parents have to work to keep a family going wasn't a
surprise to Judith Maxwell, president of the Canadian Policy
Research Networks Inc., an independent, non-profit think-tank.
</P>
<P>
   She says overwork, combined with the inevitable hurrying of
children off to child care, school and other activities, causes
parents a tremendous amount of stress and worry and could affect
children later in life.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Historic Meeting Between Catholics, Anglicans
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSAUGA, Ontario (AP) -- A historic meeting between the Roman
Catholic and Anglican churches closed Friday with the creation of a
commission to study how to unite the two churches after a 466-year
rift.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is considered the first formal step toward
official harmony between the churches, although no one would
speculate Friday when Anglicans and Catholics might become one.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long it might be before the world's one billion
Catholics and 100 million Anglicans would worship in a single
church, Most Rev. George Carey, Archbishop of Canterbury, said
cryptically: ''How long is a piece of string?''
</P>
<P>
   This week, 26 Anglican and Roman Catholic bishops from 13
countries spent five days at the Queen of Apostles Renewal Center
poring over 35 years of ecumenical dialogue between the churches in
an effort to pinpoint exactly what it is that still keeps the
churches apart.
</P>
<P>
   Before unification, the churches would have to agree on the
ordination of women.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Federal Database Skirts Moral Questions: Privacy Watchdog
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The federal government appears to be missing the
point of serious concerns about its massive databank tracking the
lives of Canadians, the privacy commissioner suggested Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Human Resources Minister Jane Stewart and her officials said
this week that the database, holding up to 2,000 details about each
of 33.7 million Canadians, is a research tool that's secure and
legal.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the point, says commissioner Bruce Phillips, who
revealed the existence of the database Tuesday and publicized his
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who's been talking with Human Resources about the
issue for two years with no resolution, says the very existence of
the comprehensive, permanent database is ''inherently
problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt the database is legal, but it may ''not reflect
the spirit of the Privacy Act, the principles of the Privacy Act or
the objective of the Privacy Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is uncomfortable the database was created before its
research uses were spelled out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Secondly, there is absolutely no element of consent anywhere
in the database ... No effort has been made to obtain personal
consent.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
Family of Woman Shot by RCMP Questions Role of Police, Native
Leaders
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- It's troubling RCMP were allowed to
investigate the fatal shooting of an aboriginal woman by one of
their own officers, says the victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   And native leaders should share some of the blame for conditions
that led to the shooting of Connie Jacobs and her nine-year-old son
Ty, said Jacobs' sister Christina Applegarth.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found it disturbing the RCMP would have been allowed to
investigate these matters when it was their officers and indirectly
a force they controlled -- the tribal police -- that were directly
involved in the events,'' Applegarth said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, there may be nothing that another police force
might have found, but it would have been one less crucial factor to
speculate about.''
</P>
<P>
   Applegarth made scathing remarks Friday about the way police and
aboriginal leaders dealt with the shooting on a reserve near
Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Goodson released his final report Thursday from a
year-long, million-dollar inquiry into the deaths. The two were
killed by RCMP Const. Dave Voller on March 22, 1998, on the Tsuu
T'ina reserve just west of Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Voller exchanged gunfire with Jacobs, 37, after a child
apprehension went wrong. Ty was standing behind his mother and was
hit by the shotgun blast. Voller has been cleared of any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Judge Hands Three-year Term to Man Convicted in BioChem Bomb Case
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- A three-year prison term was handed Friday to a
man convicted of planting bombs at BioChem Pharm. Inc. buildings in
a failed bid to manipulate the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Thresh, 25, was found guilty on one stock-fraud charge
and two explosives charges. Justice Jean-Guy Boilard issued the
sentence after a guilty verdict by a Quebec Superior Court jury.
</P>
<P>
   Thresh's wife, Carole Perron, 30, who is more than eight months
pregnant, was acquitted on one stock-fraud charge.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution argued the couple cooked up the clumsy bomb plot
hoping to drive down the price of BioChem's stock and then benefit
from it on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs weren't prepared properly, the court was told. Nobody
was injured, but the buildings were damaged when the bombs went off
in Montreal and nearby Laval on Nov. 25, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The North American stock exchanges halted trading in BioChem
stock immediately after the bombings, and the price stayed steady
when trading resumed.
</P>
