<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Klansmen Appear in Court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Two former Ku Klux Klansmen charged with
murder in the 1963 church bombing that killed four black girls made
in initial appearance in court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Blanton Jr., 61, of Birmingham, and Bobby Frank
Cherry, 69, of Mabank, Texas, appeared in Jefferson County District
Court before District Judge Pete Johnson. They had turned
themselves in Wednesday after being charged.
</P>
<P>
   Both were shackled and handcuffed as they were brought into
court amid heavy security. A second hearing was set for June 30.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by Johnson whether he understood the charges against
him, Cherry said: ''Yes, but I didn't know anything about the
bombing until it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanton and Cherry were each charged with eight counts of murder
-- two counts covering each of the four girls slain in 16th Street
Baptist Church on a Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   One count was for intentional murder and the other involved
''universal malice'' because the bomb was placed where it could
have killed any number of people.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton and Cherry are being held without bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
