<HEADLINE> Malaysian Meets With Rebel Leader  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Malaysia's ambassador held a jungle
meeting with a leader of Islamic rebels who have held 21 Western
and Asian hostages for nearly a month, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Manzoor Hussein Arshad met with an Abu Sayyaf rebel commander on
Thursday near the site where the captives are being held on the
southern Philippine island of Mindanao, two former rebels who
escorted him said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place on a forested mountainside where the
hostages are held, as hundreds of armed men stood guard, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign governments were also considering independent
efforts to free the hostages out of growing frustration over the
slow start of negotiations, a government official said. The
hostages themselves have urged their governments and international
organizations to step in.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf snatched three Germans, two French, two Finns,
two South Africans, a Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos
on April 23 from Malaysia's Sipadan Island and took them to Jolo,
about an hour away by boat.
</P>
<P>
   But security considerations for formal talks, delayed by clashes
between the rebels and troops and by frequent changes in the
government negotiating team, have been a sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're preparing the ground for the meeting, which will take
place tomorrow or the next day,'' Libyan envoy Abdul Rajab
Azzarouq, one of the negotiators, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with the Abu Sayyaf, the smaller and more extreme of the
two Muslim separatist groups, could take days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people have been displaced by rising violence
in Mindanao since last month, when the army attacked a 10-mile
stretch of highway held for five years by the larger rebel group,
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front. The MILF pulled out of peace
talks, and said Friday it is considering the government's offer to
return to the table on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is also holding about eight Filipino hostages on
the nearby island of Basilan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
