<DOCNO> APW20000519.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans grapple with Giuliani-less campaign  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- With Mayor Rudolph Giuliani out, New York
Republicans were left Friday searching for a new giant killer to
take on Hillary Rodham Clinton in the state's U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Most attention focused on Rep. Rick Lazio, a little-known Long
Island politician who quickly picked up the endorsement of Gov.
George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN's ''Larry King Live,'' Pataki said New York
Republicans had plenty of qualified potential replacement
candidates, but ''clearly the best would be Rick Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Friday that he was ready to back Lazio, if he was
the GOP choice. Just minutes after the mayor pulled out of the
race, Lazio announced in Washington that he was jumping in.
</P>
<P>
   One veteran New York pollster said Giuliani's departure from the
race had to be good news for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''All things being equal, I don't think she should be doing
cartwheels, but maybe a few handstands,'' said Lee Miringoff, head
of Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Miringoff said Giuliani's departure would give the first lady a
good shot at picking up suburban, Jewish and independent voters who
had been leaning toward Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Other independent pollsters disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as he (Lazio) catches up to her in name recognition,
he catches up to her,'' predicted John Zogby. ''I think very soon,
you're going to see them tied.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you can say it's all over and she's going down
to Washington as the senator,'' said Maurice Carroll, director of
the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown Pataki -- who already killed one Democratic
political giant, three-termer Mario Cuomo, in the 1994 governor's
race -- as the strongest potential Giuliani alternative.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki said again Friday that he wouldn't enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not running. I've said that for months,'' he said. ''I
appreciate people being encouraging, but I'm not going to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Republicans were convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Pataki's for the asking,'' said Nelson Warfield, a New
Yorker who served as Bob Dole's presidential campaign press
secretary in 1996. ''I think he will ponder asking.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Pataki has passed the word to other GOP leaders
that he wants Lazio to become the candidate. The word seemed to
have gotten around.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republican Party is going to coalesce around him in about
3.2 seconds,'' said Kieran Mahoney, a veteran New York political
operative who counts Pataki among his clients. ''Everybody I've
talked to is for Lazio, and I've talked to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, also a Long Island Republican, said Friday that
he would seek the nomination, but conceded that if Pataki ''decides
to anoint Rick,'' the race would be over.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are facing a fast-approaching deadline. The party's
nominating convention is May 30 in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   While Miringoff and others said Giuliani's departure would boost
Clinton, Republicans scoffed at that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rudy Giuliani's departure paves the way for Hillary Clinton's
defeat,'' Warfield said, citing the mayor's high negatives in most
polls. ''Without the Rudy haters, Hillary Clinton's vote-base is
much weaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the races changes and becomes about Hillary again and
that's the strongest asset we've ever had,'' Warfield added.
</P>
<P>
   And while Lazio is relatively unknown at the moment, Mahoney
said that should not be a handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a guy named George Pataki who wasn't that well known
in 1994,'' the veteran GOP operative recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Both Warfield and Mahoney said raising money should not be a
major problem for whoever runs against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Giuliani proved there was a tremendous amount of anti-Hillary
money out there nationally that will come flooding in to whoever
the Republican nominee is,'' Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be a fully-funded race,'' Sen. Mitch McConnell, head
of the National Republican Senatorial Committee, pledged.
</P>
<P>
   ''In one sense, it's a more difficult race for Hillary Clinton
than it was before, because now it's all about her, and that always
works to her disadvantage,'' McConnell added.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage Lazio may have is that he has strong ties to the
state's Conservative Party. No Republican running for statewide
office in New York has won since 1974 without Conservative Party
support. Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long had refused to
back Giuliani because of the mayor's support for abortion rights
and his closeness Liberal Party boss Raymond Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Long said Friday that he wasn't going to jump immediately behind
Lazio and that the congressman would have to ''win the endorsement
of the party's leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Rudy caused me this problem for 14 months,'' Long said. ''You
think I'm going to solve it in 14 hours?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 2128 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
