<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supporters Predict China Trade Win  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders and Clinton
administration trade allies seized on a new pact between Europe and
China on Friday to predict a House victory next week on the China
trade bill. Under pressure from fellow Democrats, President Clinton
canceled his plan to pitch the deal on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., chairman of the House Rules
Committee, and other supporters claimed new momentum, citing both
the China-European Union agreement and a bipartisan
leadership-backed side plan for a watchdog commission to monitor
human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be able to have the votes necessary for a strong
victory,'' Dreier said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on a fund-raising trip to Philadelphia and Chicago,
abruptly canceled a five-minute, televised Oval Office address on
behalf of the legislation that he had scheduled for Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decided to abandon the speech after talking with House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and other congressional Democrats
during his flight to Chicago, said White House spokeswoman Jennifer
Palmieri.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been talking with them for the past couple of days about
what's the most productive way to get votes on this,'' Palmieri
said. ''They've advised us that they don't think that the Oval
Office address is the most productive way to get votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, D-Mo., an opponent of the legislation, had been asked
by some in his party to deliver a televised response to Clinton's
address. A senior White House official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said some of the members who had urged Clinton to make
the speech changed their minds Friday, saying they felt the address
would raise the stakes for the legislation and ''make it more
divisive and high profile than it needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC and CBS had said they would not carry the address. ABC said
the network had already covered both sides of the issue on its news
programs, and CBS said the speech amounted to lobbying. NBC, CNN
and FOX had said they would carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said the vote remains close and predicted a weekend
of hard lobbying. The bill is supported by the business community
and opposed by labor, environmental and some veterans' groups.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would establish permanent normal trade relations with
China, scrapping 20 years of annual reviews. It would also enable
American companies to benefit fully from a market-opening deal
reached by the United States and China last November.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claimed new converts, although supporters appeared to
have won more.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Dreier announced that his committee --
which sets ground rules for floor debate -- will meet Tuesday,
followed by House debate Wednesday and a vote either late Wednesday
or on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The side legislation, by Reps. Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Doug
Bereuter, R-Neb., would set up a legislative and executive branch
commission to monitor human rights in China and establish a
mechanism for protecting U.S. companies from surges in Chinese
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier said he hoped everything could be handled in one package,
with a single vote. However, such an approach could bring
difficulties in the Senate, where leaders want to keep the trade
bill and the side legislation separate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, where passage of the China trade bill seems assured,
was waiting for the House to act first.
</P>
<P>
   Five formerly undecided House members -- Democrats John LaFalce
of New York, Thomas Sawyer of Ohio and Diana DeGette of Colorado;
and Republican Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas -- announced their
support.
</P>
<P>
   ''Closing the door on China will not improve human rights in
China. It would be a step back,'' DeGette said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., announced his support,
saying he believed that ''in the long run, engagement will foster
democracy and significantly improved living standards in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., told reporters he was still officially
undecided but ''leaning to yes.'' Earlier, Rep. Chet Edwards,
D-Texas, announced he was switching from undecided to ''yes'' and
Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., indicated he was likely to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents claimed three new converts to the ''no'' column: Reps.
Robert Andrews, D-N.J.; Rod R. Blagojevich, D-Ill.; and Karen
McCarthy, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., a leading opponent,
told reporters, ''As bad as our trade deficit with China is today,
it will grow even worse if we approve a permanent trade deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents need about 70-75 Democratic votes, and Rep. Robert
Matsui, D-Calif., the top Democratic head counter, said ''we're
well on our way'' to that range.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters welcomed the news that the 15-member European Union
had finished negotiating a market-opening pact with China on
Friday, removing the last obstacle to China's long-sought entry in
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tim Roemer, D-Ind., said it ''is further evidence that we
need to pass this agreement ... We know that if we don't pass this,
that the Europeans will take advantage of reduced tariffs and added
access to the Chinese markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade concessions that China gives to any one country to gain
entry to the WTO must be extended to all other WTO members. But for
the U.S. to gain such benefits, Congress must grant China permanent
normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 2142 </TRAILER>
