<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressBill Cox:
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMARILLO, Texas (AP) -- Author-journalist Bill Cox, a former
columnist and city editor for the Amarillo Globe-News, died Friday
in Houston. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   He was news director at an Amarillo radio station, an editor of
an Amarillo weekly, and held various jobs with the News-Herald in
Borger, the Odessa American and the Lamesa Press-Reporter. He also
was managing editor of The West Texas Register, official
publication of the Catholic diocese of Amarillo
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, Cox joined the Globe-News' editorial staff. He
became city editor in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ''Born Bad,'' was published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, two sons, and three daughters.
Randy Hammericksen:
</P>
<P>
   MEDFORD, Ore. (AP) -- Randy Hammericksen, a sports columnist and
former sports editor of the Mail Tribune newspaper, died Thursday
after suffering a stroke and brain aneurism. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   He worked at the Oceanside (Calif.) Blade-Tribune, Corvallis
Gazette-Times and Eureka (Calif.) Times-Standard before joining the
Mail Tribune in 1987 as sports editor. He became the newspaper's
primary sports columnist in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, Hammericksen is survived by eight children.
John C. Sawhill:
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- John C. Sawhill, who helped the Nature
Conservancy become the world's largest private land conservation
group, died Thursday of complications from diabetes. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Sawhill was president and chief executive of the organization
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, the Nature Conservancy protected more than 7
million acres in the United States and two weeks ago announced the
$37 million acquisition of Palmyra Atoll in the Pacific Ocean. The
organization also grew to 1.1 million members and increased its
network of holdings to 1,300 private nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Sawhill previously held senior energy positions in the Nixon,
Ford and Carter administrations and served as president of New York
University. He also served on the boards of a variety of corporate
and nonprofit boards.
John Sullivan:
</P>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- John Sullivan, a television personality
who became known for his down-home profiles of Kentuckians, died
Thursday of cancer. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was recognized throughout the central and eastern parts
of the state for his ''Sullivan's Travels'' on WKYT-TV, featuring
people like a blind man who caned chairs, a man who ran a one-watt
radio station and a 55-year-old woman who went back to school and
got not only her GED, but bachelor's and law degrees as well.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for WEKY radio in Richmond and later, Eastern
Kentucky's FM radio station, WEKU.
</P>
<P>
   He was later hired by WKYT, where he hosted an early-morning
show called ''Town and Country.'' He began the ''Sullivan's
Travels'' features in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is survived by his wife, a son and two stepdaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 2215 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0277 </DOCNO>
