<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Gov. Signs Four Gun Bills  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN K. PAULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Gov. Bill Owens signed four gun bills Friday,
saying that while the new laws might not have prevented the
Columbine High School shootings, they could have allowed for more
charges to be filed.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws:
</P>
<P>
   -- Make it a felony for a person to purchase or obtain a firearm
for another person who reasonably should know the transaction is
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bar a person from giving a firearm to any juvenile without the
consent of the parent or legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make it illegal for a person not to make reasonable efforts to
prevent a juvenile from committing a crime with a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   -- Increase the penalty for possession of a weapon by a felon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think today is a reflection of Columbine. While I didn't get
all I wanted, this is a substantial improvement,'' the Republican
governor said, acknowledging that the new laws were the product of
compromises between gun control supporters and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Ken Gordon, D-Denver, issued a statement
saying the bills ''do not address the core problem of access to
guns by felons and juveniles.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These bills are small steps in the right direction, but in no
way make up for the Republican majority killing meaningful
legislation that would close the gun-show loophole, require safe
storage of guns in the home, or stop 18-year-olds from buying a
handgun at a gun show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mauser, whose son, Daniel, was killed in the rampage, said:
''I think clearly they're more punitive than they are preventative.
They're not bad laws, but they aren't as effective as they should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending Friday's signing ceremony was state Rep. Don Lee, a
Republican from Littleton, whose son, Shawn, was in the high
school's cafeteria when gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold began
their rampage. Harris and Klebold killed 13 people and wounded 23
others inside the school on April 20, 1999 before taking their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lee helped draft the bill that would require parental consent
for providing a firearm to a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill is one that came directly out of Columbine. This
would not have prevented what happened at Columbine, but it would
have had a consequence for the participants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing law, two men in the Columbine case were charged
with providing a handgun to minors, as Harris and Klebold were 17
when they got the guns.
</P>
<P>
   But Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone said Klebold's
girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, who admitted supplying a rifle and two
shotguns to the youths, escaped arrest because the law then didn't
make it illegal to provide long guns to minors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
