<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Gunmen Kill Family of 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Gunmen firing assault rifles killed 11
adult members of a single family in Nicaragua and then burned their
home, police said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Thursday near the town of Siuna, about 200 miles
northeast of Managua, came a day after three soldiers were killed
in an ambush in the same general area, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The lone survivor of the attack, Guadalupe Montenegro, was once
a member of a group of former Sandinista soldiers suspected of
numerous attacks in the area, national police said.
</P>
<P>
   The group of ex-Sandinista soldiers was one of several groups of
former combatants that formed to demand government aid in the
aftermath of Nicaragua's Contra war in the 1980s. The group
officially disarmed in 1997 under an agreement with the government,
but police say some members kept their weapons and turned to crime.
</P>
<P>
   The dead, some of whom were badly burned, included seven women
and four men. Authorities said they all were members of the same
family, but did not specify the exact relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, nearly a dozen assailants attacked a military
truck in the region, killing an army captain and two soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's attacks bring the number of assaults to four in the
past two months in the country's Atlantic coast region. Last month,
gunmen ambushed a police vehicle, killing five people.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, a government representative escaped injury
when soldiers shielded him from gunmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
