<HEADLINE> World Cup Soccer Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Dwight Yorke's goal helped Trinidad and Tobago move
into the
semifinals of regional qualifying for the 2002 World Cup with a 1-1
tie against Haiti at Port-Au-Prince on Friday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Manchester United forward, who skipped early qualifying
games to play for the English champions, scored off a counterattack
in the 24th minute as Trinidad and Tobago held on to win the
home-and-home, total-goals series 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Dieufene Delamour scored for Haiti with 17 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad won the first leg 3-1 at home on May 7, with Yorke
contributing one goal.
</P>
<P>
   With its victory in the third round of Caribbean qualifying,
Trinidad advanced to the 12-nation semifinals of soccer's North and
Central American and Caribbean region, where it will be grouped
with Mexico; either Honduras or Panama; and Barbados, Canada or
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti faces either Honduras or Panama in a playoff for another
semifinal spot.
</P>
<P>
   In a meaningless Central America Group A game later Friday
night, Belize played Guatemala at Panama City.
</P>
<P>
   El Salvador won the group and advanced to the regional
semifinals. Guatemala finished second and will play either Antigua
or St. Vincent in a playoff for another semifinal berth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
