<HEADLINE> Notes From Friday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Manager Joe Torre must have done a double take when
the four umpires for Friday's game came out on the field wearing
Cleveland windbreakers and caps. The crew's equipment didn't arrive
from Seattle by game time, delaying the start for five minutes. ...
INF Clay Bellinger, who had made four consecutive starts at
shortstop with Derek Jeter out, was only cleared to play after
going through pregame warmups without difficulty. Bellinger was
struck in the left shoulder by a pitch on Tuesday night before
Friday was unable to lift his arm above his head. ... With their
three-game sweep here earlier this month, the Yankees entered
Friday night's game 24-9 (.727) at Jacobs Field. New York has won
14 of the last 18 games against Cleveland and is 54-27 against the
Indians since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Thursday's postponed game against Detroit will be
made up as part of a day-night doubleheader against the Tigers on
June 24 at 1:05 p.m. The second game will start at 7:05 p.m. ...
RHP Charles Nagy had successful arthroscopic surgery to remove bone
chips from his right elbow Friday at Lutheran Hospital. Nagy had
made 192 consecutive starts since Oct. 3, 1993, before being placed
on the 15-day disabled list on Thursday. Nagy is expected to be
sidelined 6-to-8 weeks. ... Indians manager Charlie Manuel said LHP
Ricardo Rincon was going to visit famed surgeons Dr. Frank Jobe and
Dr. James Andrews before having surgery on his left elbow. Rincon,
the Indians' most consistent reliever this season, went on the DL
Thursday with bone spurs. ... RHP Paul Rigdon was recalled from
Triple-A Buffalo and will make his major league debut when he
starts on Sunday against the Yankees. Rigdon was 4-1 with a 3.07
ERA in seven starts for the Bisons.
White Sox-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox won five of their six games at SkyDome
last season, batting .335 and outscoring the Blue Jays 40-23. ...
The White Sox are in the midst of a 38-game stretch where they play
22 games against the New York Yankees and Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays purchased the contracts of RHP Darwin
Cubillan and OF-DH Todd Greene from Triple A Syracuse. To make
room, Toronto optioned SS Chris Woodward and designated LHP Eric
Gunderson for assignment. In order to clear a spot on the 40 man
roster the Blue Jays designated minor league 3B Casey Blake for
assignment. ... Greene, released by Anaheim in spring training, hit
.297 with seven home runs and 14 RBIs for Syracuse. ... RHP Pete
Munro will make his first start of the season on Monday. Munro
replaced LHP Lance Painter, who returned to the bullpen.
Tigers-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: OF Luis Polonia began serving a three-game suspension
for last month's brawl against the Chicago White Sox after his
appeal was rejected by the commissioner's office. OF Juan
Encarnacion's suspension also was upheld; he will begin serving on
May 27. Paul Beeston, the chief operating officer of the
commissioner's office, reduced C Robert Fick's suspension from five
games to four, and it will begin Tuesday. ... The Tigers activated
RHP Brian Moehler from the 15-day disabled list and put RHP Mark
Johnson on the DL with a strained lower back. Detroit also optioned
RHP Masao Kida to Triple-A Toledo and called up RHP Brandon
Villafuerte. Moehler, recovering from an April 22 appendectomy,
started Friday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: 3B John Valentin was back in the lineup for the first
time since he was put on the 15-day disabled list, effective April
6, with left knee tendinitis. INF Andy Sheets was optioned to
Triple-A Pawtucket. ... The Red Sox presented legislators with a
plan for a new $627 million Fenway Park. The team is asking
taxpayers to pitch in $275 million to buy the land and build a
parking garage.
Orioles-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Before Friday night, the Orioles had given up 29
homers in May, allowing at least one home run in 14 of 16 games
during the month. ... Baltimore's bullpen entered Friday night with
an 8.59 ERA in May and had six blown saves. ... Before Friday,
Orioles opponents had scored four or more runs in an inning 20
times this season, including one seven-run inning, six six-run
innings and four five-run innings.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Rangers owner Tom Hicks was released from a hospital in
Sante Fe, N.M., on Friday after being treated for dehydration.
Hicks felt faint at a business meeting Thursday night and was
hospitalized as a precautionary measure. Hicks also owns the Dallas
Stars, and he attended the Stars' playoff game in Denver against
the Colorado Avalanche on Friday night. Hicks said he was
dehydrated after taking a steam bath and did not drink enough
fluids to compensate. ... Frank Catalanotto's streak of 10 straight
hits, which was halted Thursday night, is the longest in the major
leagues since Kansas City's Joe Randa had 10 consecutive hits last
June 8-12. Catalanotto's streak of reaching base 12 straight times
also was stopped Thursday night. It tied Jim Edmonds of the St.
Louis Cardinals for the longest in the majors this season.
Catalanotto had 10 hits and two walks; Edmonds had nine hits and
three walks.
Twins-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA:Travis Miller went a season-long 2 1-3 innings in
relief but was lifted with one out to go, leaving him short of his
second save of the year. Twins manager Tom Kelly wasn't taking any
chances after Miller gave up a pair of singles in the ninth. After
all, the Twins bullpen has blown six saves in 12 chances. So closer
Bob Wells came on to finish Minnesota's 10-5 win at Oakland on
Thursday night even though it wasn't a save situation. ...
Minnesota pitchers did not walk a batter against Oakland during
Thursday's 10-5 win over the A's. Oakland entered the game leading
the majors in walks with 219. Twins pitchers have allowed the third
fewest walks in the AL with 133.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Left-handed reliver Mike Magnante is listed as
day-to-day after spraining his left ankle while delivering a pitch
Thursday night. ''Basically, the team told me it was up to me if I
could pitch,'' Magnante said. ''I plan on being available unless it
balloons up on me.'' Rich Sauveur is the only other lefty in the
A's bullpen. ... Kevin Appier had his shortest outing of the season
and failed to get through the sixth inning for the second straight
outing when he went just three innings Thursday night against
Minnesota. He allowed five runs and had a no decision. Appier had
gone at least six innings in four of his first five starts but
since returning from the disabled list for a strained right
forearm, he's given up 10 runs, five earned, in 8 2-3 innings
pitched.
Devil Rays-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: RHP Billy Taylor was recalled from Triple-A Durham
and RHP Jeff Sparks was optioned to the International League team.
At Durham, Taylor was 1-0 with a 4.29 ERA with 21 innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: OF Rickey Henderson, signed as a free agent Wednesday
night after being released by the New York Mets, arrived at Safeco
Field an hour before the game with Tampa Bay and was activated. RHP
Kevin Hodges was optioned to Triple-A Tacoma to make room for
Henderson. With Seattle, Hodges was 0-0 with a 4.26 ERA in three
games and 6 1-3 innings, all in relief.
Royals-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals, who led the AL with 48 steals heading
into Friday night's game against the Angels, have had just five
runners thrown out attempting to steal. ... Since being promoted to
the closer role, Jerry Spradlin had made three saves in as many
appearances. He came into the season with only four career saves,
two since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS: Angels right-hander Jason Dickson will be placed on the
disabled list with tendinitis in his left hip and stiffness in his
right shoulder. Anaheim also will purchase the contract of
right-hander Brett Hinchliffe from its Triple-A Edmonton affiliate
and make room on the 40-man roster by transferring right-hander Tim
Belcher to the 60-day DL. All the moves become effective Saturday.
... Belcher, 38, has not made the progress hoped for in his return
from elbow surgery in the off-season. He was placed on the 15-day
DL on March 27.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Reds-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: When Ken Griffey Jr., played at Wrigley Field in
1990, he was just 20 and became the second youngest player -- behind
Al Kaline -- to start an All-Star game. ... The Reds were more than
six hours late arriving in Chicago because of bad weather. Their
charter flight from Cincinnati on Thursday was delayed 3{ hours by
poor weather and once they took off, conditions were so lousy they
had to divert to Milwaukee and then take a 90-mile bus ride,
arriving at their hotel around midnight. ... Asked how his team's
chemistry is, Reds manager Jack McKeon had this reply: ''To this
day I don't know what chemistry is. I didn't take it in high
school.'' ... The Reds have won four straight series and 8 of their
last 10.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Manager Don Baylor had no problem with Sammy Sosa's
display of anger after his star shattered a clubhouse table with
his bat Wednesday. Baylor called a release of emotions from the
Cubs' miserable start. ''I'm still waiting for mine,'' Baylor said.
Baylor recalled a tantrum he had during his playing days with the
Angels when he was smashing a bat in the runway to the dugout and
he nearly hit a teammate. ''I missed him,'' Baylor said. The
teammate's name? Nolan Ryan. ... The Chicago Tribune reported that
the Cubs are talking with the Yankees about trading LF Henry
Rodriguez to New York for OF Ricky Ledee and a pitching prospect
for their moribund bullpen. General manager Ed Lynch refused
comment. Gene Michael, the Yankees' top scout, was at Wrigley on
Friday. Rodriguez is out of the Cubs' lineup, nursing a bruised
knee after fouling a ball off it. Also attending Friday's game was
Dan Evans, who is an assistant to White Sox's general manager Ron
Schueler.
Astros-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: The Astros return to Milwaukee on Monday to play a
doubleheader beginning at 12:05 p.m. CDT, after the last two games
of their three-game series were rained out. ... Houston has had
four rainouts this season, including their season opener in
Pittsburgh on April 3 and a rare rainout in Los Angeles on April
17. ... The Astros are playing their first game on artificial turf
since their season-opening three-game set in Pittsburgh Apr. 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos signed free-agent LHP Jim Poole to a major
league contract Friday. Released by Detroit on Wednesday after
going 1-0 with one save and a 7.27 ERA in 18 games this season,
Poole will be playing for his eighth major league team since
breaking into the big leagues with Los Angeles in 1990. He is
expected to join the team on Saturday. ... C Chris Widger has a
deep bone bruise on his left hand and will be rested for the first
two games of the series. Lenny Webster started for the fifth time
on Friday night.
Rockies-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: The Rockies have been plagued by rain this season,
having four games washed out. That has led to two doubleheaders
being scheduled later this season and two off-days taken away. ...
Saturday's pitcher, Kevin Jarvis, has not thrown against the
Philadelphia Phillies since 1997, his last start as a member of the
Cincinnati Reds and in the National League until this season.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: LHP Trever Miller has been claimed on waivers from
the Phillies by the Los Angeles Dodgers. To take his spot on the
roster, Philadelphia has recalled RHP Steve Schrenk from Triple A
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre. Miller was 0-0 with an 8.36 ERA in 14
appearances this season. Schrenk had started the season with the
Phillies before being optioned to Scranton on May 4. He is 1-1 with
a 6.30 ERA in eight appearances. ... Eight of the Phillies' nine
opponents this season have been above .500.
Dodgers-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers didn't arrive in South Florida until 2
a.m. EDT. They spent almost three hours waiting for Thursday's game
to be called for rain in Chicago. It took them an hour and a half
to get to the airport, then they spent another six hours on the
plane -- four on the runway and two in the air. They were not
allowed to take off until the bad weather cleared. The Padres,
waiting in Miami for the same plane to take them to Atlanta, didn't
get off the ground until about 3 a.m. ... The Dodgers claimed LHP
Trever Miller off waivers from Philadelphia on Friday. ... Before
the game, bullpen coach Rick Dempsey was in the stands, talking to
some friends when OF Shawn Green joked, ''Hey Demper, we're not
supposed to be in the stands.'' Green, of course, was referring to
the Dodgers' fight Tuesday at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: With RHP Alex Fernandez (shoulder, elbow) back on the
disabled list, the Marlins will not need to make a roster move when
reliever Ricky Bones (strained back) is activated Sunday. ...
Manager John Boles is still trying to figure out how his team stole
10 bases in five innings Thursday night against San Diego and
scored only twice: ''It's mind boggling.''... Many of the Miami
Dolphins rookie class got their first look at Pro Player Stadium on
Friday. The group got a guided tour of the facility, home to the
Dolphins and Marlins.
Cardinals-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Mark McGwire, coming off his three-homer night
Thursday in Philadelphia, hit third in the Cardinals' order Friday
for the first time this season. McGwire hit cleanup in his first 30
starts. The left-handed hitting Jim Edmonds batted fourth Friday
against Pirates RHP Kris Benson. ... McGwire has 176 homers since
joining the Cardinals on Aug. 1, 1997. ... Garrett Stephenson is
the first Cardinals pitcher to start 6-0 since Bob Tewksbury was
7-0 in 1994. Tewksbury finished with 12 victories in the
strike-shortened season. ... RHP Matt Morris, recovering from elbow
surgery, pitched five shutout innings Wednesday for Triple-A
Memphis. He will have make at least two and possibly three more
rehabilitation starts. The Cardinals expect both Morris and Andy
Benes, also on a rehab assignment at Memphis, to rejoin them by
June 1.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: 2B Warren Morris, batting .192 in 14 games this
month, took the night off Friday against Cardinals LHP Rick Ankiel.
... Pirates 1B Kevin Young committed his sixth error of the season
Friday. He led all major league 1B with 23 errors last season. ...
RHP Francisco Cordova (1-3) will come off the disabled list to
start Saturday night against St. Louis. ... Manager Gene Lamont
decided to move rookie CF Chad Hermansen out of the leadoff spot
when Hermansen starts. Hermansen began the season batting eighth,
but was moved to leadoff when Jason Kendall dropped to third.
Hermansen hit .130 with two homers in 12 games as the leadoff
hitter. ... The Pirates haven't been above .500 all season.
Diamondbacks-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Tony Womack led off Friday night's game with a single,
extending his hitting streak to 15. His career-best string was 16
for Pittsburgh in 1998. ... Injured 3B Matt Williams was off to a
4-for-7 start in his rehabilitation stint with Double-A El Paso.
Williams, who broke his right foot in spring training, left
Thursday night's Texas League game with a cramp in his leg.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Mets were trying to post consecutive victories for
the first time since April 29-30 at Colorado. ... Mark Johnson made
his first start in left field since 1996 while with Pittsburgh. He
got an assist in the second inning, making a throw that led to
rundown that trapped Todd Stottlemyre. ... Reliever Turk Wendell
turned 33.
Padres-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: 2B Bret Boone and 1B Ryan Klesko returned to Atlanta
for the first time since being traded to San Diego in an offseason
deal. Boone made an immediate impact, hitting a three-run homer in
the first against former teammate Terry Mulholland. ... Boone is
the only San Diego player to see action in all 41 games. ... Klesko
already has set a career high for steals, swiping his seventh of
the season Thursday night at Florida. His previous high was six for
the Braves in 1996. ... The Padres had won only three of 10 series
openers prior to Friday's game, all on the road. They are 0-5 in
the opening game of home series.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: It was old home night for Braves hitting coach Merv
Rettenmund, who served the same role in San Diego the previous nine
years. He visited around the batting cage with Padres manager Bruce
Bochy and chatted with San Diego third baseman Phil Nevin. ''You
don't want them to beat you,'' Rettenmund said, ''but you pull for
them, especially guys like Eric Owens,'' the outfielder who was
hitting .333 before Friday's game. ... Glenn Hubbard returned to
the first base coaching box, two days after undergoing surgery to
remove kidney stones. ''I feel fine,'' he said. ... P Tom Glavine
was ill and remained home Friday night. The Braves hope he is
recovered in time to make his scheduled start Sunday. ... 2B
Quilvio Veras, a former Padre, left the game in the first inning
after being struck on the right knee with a pitch by Brian Meadows.
The severity of the injury was not immediately known.
Giants-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Manager Dusty Baker faced his friend and former
teammate, Davey Lopes, for the first time as a manager. Lopes, the
rookie manager of the Brewers, and Baker were on the Los Angeles
Dodgers 1981 World Series championship team. ... RHP Mark Gardner
is scheduled to make the 300th outing of his major league career
Saturday against Milwaukee. It will be his 243rd start. Gardner is
85-83. ... Barry Bonds returned to the lineup Friday after going
down last Saturday with lower back pain. The Giants were 17-15 with
Bonds in the lineup and 1-5 without him. ... Not only did the
Giants lose the first six games of their current road trip, the
opposing team didn't bat in the ninth inning of any of those games.
Closer Robb Nen hasn't pitched in over a week.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Tyler Houston was placed on the 15-day disabled list
Friday retroactive to May 15 with a contusion on his right calf.
The Brewers purchased the contract of catcher Raul Casanova from
Triple-A Indianapolis to fill Houston's roster spot ... Milwaukee
was rained out Wednesday and Thursday at home, but the skies were
mostly clear on Friday night. The last time the Brewers were rained
out on consecutive nights was April 11-12, 1997 vs. Toronto ... RHP
John Snyder, acquired in the offseason from the Chicago White Sox,
is expected to make his first appearance of the season Sunday
against the Giants. Snyder has been on the disabled list since the
beginning of the season with a strained left oblique muscle.
</P>
