<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floating restaurant next to collapsed pier has long history  </HEADLINE>
With AM-NJ--Pier Collapse Bjt   
rltjkb1
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The tall ship Moshulu, with lights strung
along the ropes to its mast, has commanded the waterfront at Pier
34 and symbolized the rebirth of nightlife along the Delaware River
waterfront for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Moshulu, once the world's largest squarerigger, was docked
off Penn's Landing on the eastern edge of Philadelphia from 1975 to
1989, until it was damaged by fire. It then docked in Camden, N.J.,
until developer Eli Karetny and his HMS Ventures bought the ship in
1994 and opened it two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Karetny, who released a statement Friday saying he was
cooperating with investigators, also opened Eli's Pier 34 seafood
restaurant in 1992 at the same pier where the Heat was. In 1994,
part of that pier collapsed but was later repaired. No injuries
were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The 394-foot-long Moshulu was launched in 1904 in Hamburg,
Germany, under the name Kurt. It was in Astoria, Ore., when the
United States entered World War I, confiscated the ship and gave
renamed it Moshulu, which means ''Fear Not'' in the language of the
Seneca tribe of American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, the Moshulu was in service in the grain trade and
won a 1939 race among the grain carriers for the fastest time from
Australia and around Cape Horn to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, now permanently tied at Pier 34, is decorated in
Victorian style and the restaurant's menu reflects the lands it
once visited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-19-00 2246 </TRAILER>
