<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 19, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giuliani Drops Out of NY Senate Race
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rep. Rick Lazio became the favorite to replace Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani in the New York senate race, after Giuliani ended his campaign today
against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Battling prostate cancer and with his
marriage in turmoil, Giuliani said it wasn't the right time for him to run for
office. Giuliani's departure from the race propels Lazio, a relatively unknown
Long Island congressman, to the top of a list of Republicans hoping to replace
him.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwanese President Takes Office
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taking office under tremendous pressure to smooth out
potentially explosive relations with China, Taiwan's new president was sworn in
Saturday. In his raspy voice, Chen Shui-bian faced the red, blue and white flag
of the Republic of China, Taiwan's official name, and took the oath of office.
''With sincerity, I swear to the people of this country that I will follow the
constitution to increase the people's welfare and safeguard the country,'' he
said, before taking the seal of the presidency, wrapped in bright yellow cloth.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blair's Wife Gives Birth
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The wife of British Prime Minister Tony Blair gave birth to a
baby boy early Saturday morning -- the couple's fourth child, officials said.
Cherie Blair, 45, and the baby were in good health, officials at Blair's Downing
Street office said. Mrs. Blair had been due to give birth on May 24, but was
admitted to Chelsea and Westminster hospital in west London at midday Friday.
The prime minister joined her early in the evening. The boy, whose name was not
immediately disclosed, becomes the first child born to a serving British prime
minister in 152 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Civilians Flee Advancing Ethiopians
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ZRON, Eritrea (AP) -- Tens of thousands of Eritrean civilians fled advancing
Ethiopian troops and the government struggled to set up camps to house and feed
them Friday, a week after Ethiopia launched an all-out offensive to end a
two-year border war with its neighbor. U.N. and Eritrean aid officials said
Eritrea, a country of 4 million people in the Horn of Africa, was hovering on
the edge of a humanitarian tragedy: The more than half million people escaping
fighting in western Eritrea added to a drought crisis that already threatened
300,000 others.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nicaraguan Gunmen Kill Family of 11
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Gunmen firing assault rifles killed 11 adult
members of a single family in Nicaragua and then burned their home, police said
Friday. The attack on Thursday near the town of Siuna, about 200 miles northeast
of Managua, came a day after three soldiers were killed in an ambush in the same
general area, the police said. The lone survivor of the attack, Guadalupe
Montenegro, was once a member of a group of former Sandinista soldiers suspected
of numerous attacks in the area, national police said. The dead, some of whom
were badly burned, included seven women and four men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury Finds Couple Guilty of Killing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A couple was convicted today of killing a casino heir after
a trial that captivated this gambling community with tales of love, drug
addiction and buried treasure. Ted Binion, who lost his casino license because
of drug use and association with a mob figure, died Sept. 17, 1998 after being
forced to ingest of a lethal dose of heroin and the prescription anti-depressant
Xanax. Sandra Murphy, who was Binion's live-in girlfriend, and Tabish, her
lover, were charged with murder nine months later. Convicted of murder and other
charges, they could be sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Millionaire' Wins Emmy Award
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The show that transformed prime-time television, ''Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire,'' won a Daytime Emmy award tonight. The game show was
shunted off to the Daytime Emmy awards when the prime-time show declared it had
no category it could compete in, a decision that miffed ABC, the show's
producer, and host Regis Philbin. Producer Michael Davies ignored the
controversy in accepting the award. Rosie O'Donnell won her fourth straight Emmy
as best talk show host. She's won the award every year she was nominated.
Longtime winner Oprah Winfrey no longer competes in the category.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 150, Nasdaq Falls 148
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell broadly today with high-tech stocks
leading the decline. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 150.43 points to end
at 10,626.85. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,932-951. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 148.31 to 3,390.40.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Defeat Diamondbacks 4-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bobby J. Jones earned his first victory in more than a year
and the New York Mets posted consecutive wins for the first time this month,
using Mike Piazza's home run to beat the Arizona Diamondbacks 4-3 tonight. The
Mets had not won two in a row since April 29-30 at Colorado.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
