<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activist Leader in Vieques Detained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A leader of anti-Navy activists on
the island of Vieques was detained for allegedly trying to prevent
a military convoy from leaving the Navy base.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rabin, of the group Coordinator of Justice and Peace for
Vieques, was detained Thursday night by Puerto Rican police outside
the Navy's Camp Garcia, said Agent Ricardo Ayala of the Vieques
police force. Activists want the Navy to end its bombing exercises
on the island of 9,300 people.
</P>
<P>
   But Angel de Leon, a spokesman for the group, said Rabin was in
his vehicle, which had stalled in the middle of the road, and was
not trying to block the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, federal agents detained 216 people, including Rabin,
and cleared them from the bombing range and other Navy land on the
island of Vieques. Some had been camping on the range since an
April 1999 accident in which a civilian guard was killed by two
off-target bombs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 2259 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000519.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sather Resigns As Oilers' Boss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Glen Sather, the architect of the
Edmonton Oilers' five Stanley Cup championship teams from 1984-90,
resigned Friday night as president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't wish this franchise any bad luck,'' Sather said during
a news conference at Skyreach Centre. ''It's the first time since
I've been 16 years old that I've been unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This hasn't been a quick decision, but it's something that I
had to do. I never contemplated leaving this organization. I
thought I'd retire here. But things change.''
</P>
<P>
   Sather, 56, who joined the Oilers as a player in 1976 and became
general in 1979, has reportedly been targeted by the New York
Rangers and Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no job offer on the table,'' said Sather, who was
under contract at $2 million annually for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to the Hockey Hall of Fame as a builder in 1997, Sather
has not been happy with the team's ownership group in recent
months. He has had problems with Cal Nichols, chairman of the
Edmonton Investors Group that took over the team in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a clashing of strong personalities,'' Sather said. ''If
this is a mistake, then I'll live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, the head coach for Edmonton's fifth Stanley Cup in
1990, spent more than a decade working with Sather.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you think of the Oilers, you think of Glen Sather,''
Muckler told the Edmonton Sun. ''He's done so many great things for
that franchise and for that community.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I never, ever thought this day would come. Mind you, I never
thought, back in the '80s, that anybody would leave, myself
included.''
</P>
<P>
   Oilers captain Doug Weight wasn't surprised by Sather's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the rope was getting shorter over the last couple of
seasons,'' Weight said. ''I think if this happened two years ago I
would have been very surprised. ... It's going to be really strange
going back to Edmonton and not have Glen there.''
</P>
<P>
   A Rangers spokesman said the team would have no comment. Sather
said earlier that he was given by the Oilers to talk with the
Rangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-19-00 2259 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
