<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Jackson May Miss Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- It turns out that Mike Jackson may not throw
a single pitch this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies reliever, signed during the offseason
to a $3 million, one-year contract, stopped himself while throwing
off the mound on Friday due to soreness in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just feel like I can't be the type of pitcher that Mike
Jackson is capable of being with the stuff that I have,'' Jackson
said. ''And I still feel like I would be on a roller coaster with
my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies manager Terry Francona was not optimistic about
Jackson's chances of recovering this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't look like it's going to work with Mike,'' Francona
said. ''If it turns out that it was sort of a gamble, I wouldn't
second guess it one bit. I was happy when we got him.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals appeared set to sign Jackson to a $12
million, three-year contract, even calling a news conference on
Nov. 19, but the news conference was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia then signed him on Dec. 1 to a deal that would have
guaranteed him $7 million for two years if he remained healthy. The
Phillies have an option for 2002 that would make the contract worth
$11.25 million for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I regret that he is hurt, but do I regret signing him? No,''
said Phillies general manager Ed Wade. ''It was a risk but I was
hoping to pay him in full and I'm sure he was hoping to collect in
full.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson got hurt during the team's first series of the year
while warming up in Arizona and never threw a pitch for the team.
Jackson's rehab took a step forward when he threw to hitters for
the first time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Ciccotti, the Phillies' team physician, examined
Jackson on Friday night and recommended that he see orthopedist Dr.
Craig Morgan in Wilminton, Del., on Tuesday for another opinion.
Ciccotti hopes to treat Jackson without operating.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would love to avoid it,'' Ciccotti said. ''That may not be
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciccotti was the one who had examined Jackson prior to the
Phillies' signing and he still thinks it was a sound decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a risk like any pitcher at the major league level who
had thrown the innings he had,'' Ciccotti said. ''But he had proven
himself with his record.''
</P>
<P>
   The physician couldn't say how long it would be before a
decision is reached.
</P>
<P>
   ''It depends on what we see,'' he said. ''There is certainly a
reasonable chance that he would miss the rest of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
