<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 19, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giuliani Drops Out of NY Senate Race
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Saying he agonized over the decision for days, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani dropped out of the Senate race Friday, abruptly halting an emerging
campaign against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Battling prostate cancer and
with his marriage in turmoil, Giuliani said it wasn't the right time for him to
run for office. Giuliani's departure from the race propels Rep. Rick Lazio, a
relatively unknown Long Island congressman, to the top of a list of Republicans
hoping to replace him in the battle for the Senate seat.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwanese President Takes Office
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's new president was sworn in Saturday, taking
office under tremendous pressure to smooth out potentially explosive relations
with China. In his raspy voice, Chen Shui-bian faced the red, blue and white
flag of the Republic of China, Taiwan's official name, and took the oath of
office. ''With sincerity, I swear to the people of this country that I will
follow the constitution to increase the people's welfare and safeguard the
country,'' he said, before taking the seal of the presidency, wrapped in bright
yellow cloth.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blair's Wife Gives Birth
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The wife of British Prime Minister Tony Blair gave birth to a
baby boy early Saturday morning -- the couple's fourth child, officials said.
Cherie Blair, 45, and the baby were in good health, officials at Blair's Downing
Street office said. Mrs. Blair had been due to give birth on May 24, but was
admitted to Chelsea and Westminster hospital in west London at midday Friday.
The boy, whose name was not immediately disclosed, becomes the first child born
to a serving British prime minister in 152 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nicaraguan Gunmen Kill Family of 11
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Gunmen firing assault rifles killed 11 adult
members of a single family in Nicaragua and then burned their home, police said
Friday. The attack on Thursday near the town of Siuna, about 200 miles northeast
of Managua, came a day after three soldiers were killed in an ambush in the same
general area, the police said. The lone survivor of the attack, Guadalupe
Montenegro, was once a member of a group of former Sandinista soldiers suspected
of numerous attacks in the area, national police said. The dead, some of whom
were badly burned, included seven women and four men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury Finds Couple Guilty of Killing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A couple was convicted Friday of killing a casino heir
after a trial that captivated this gambling community with tales of love, drug
addiction and buried treasure. Ted Binion, who lost his casino license because
of drug use and association with a mob figure, died Sept. 17, 1998 after being
forced to ingest of a lethal dose of heroin and the prescription anti-depressant
Xanax. Sandra Murphy, who was Binion's live-in girlfriend, and Tabish, her
lover, were convicted of murder and other charges. They could be sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Motorcycle Gang Target of Raid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Federal agents across the nation raided the homes of
members of a motorcycle gang Friday, arresting more than two dozen people and
confiscating firearms, drugs and thousands of dollars. Members of the Mongols
were arrested in Pasadena, San Diego, Porterville and Frazier Park, as well as
cities in Georgia and Oklahoma, according to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms. The case was cracked after an ATF agent infiltrated the motorcycle
gang and spent two years as a member.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Regis Philbin Shut Out at Emmys
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Regis Philbin was shut out of Daytime Emmy Awards Friday for
his talk show and as host of ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' Bob Barker of
''The Price is Right'' and Tom Bergeron of ''Hollywood Squares'' were the
surprise winners of the best game show host award. ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' won the Daytime Emmy for best game show. Even though it has
transformed prime-time television since its debut nine months ago, it was
shunted off to the Daytime Emmy awards when the prime-time awards show declared
it had no category it could compete in. Rosie O'Donnell won her fourth straight
Emmy as best talk show host.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 150, Nasdaq Falls 148
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell broadly Friday with high-tech stocks
leading the decline. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 150.43 points to end
at 10,626.85. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,932-951. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 148.31 to 3,390.40.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Avalanche Defeat Stars 2-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Patrick Roy tied an NHL record with his 15th career playoff
shutout as the Colorado Avalanche beat the Dallas Stars 2-0 on Friday night.
Shjon Podein and Adam Deadmarsh scored goals and rookie Martin Skoula had two
assists as Colorado took a 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven Western Conference
finals. Game 4 is Sunday in Denver.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
